[White "Introduction"]
[Black "Introduction"]
[Result "*"]

{ Hey everyone! This is GM Eugene Perelshteyn, and thank you for buying my course, Every Gambit Refuted!  Some of you may already know me as a Chessable author from my previous courses: The Grand Prix Attack Reloaded or the Lifetime Repertoire: Hyper-Accelerated Dragon. I'm also a book author of Chess Openings Explained for White/Black co-authored with GMs Dzindzi & Alburt and a more recent book: Evaluate Like A Grandmaster, co-authored with my friend FM Nate Solon.  I've been teaching and playing chess for over 30 years, and one topic that keeps on recurring for many of my students is how to deal with annoying gambits. Let's face it, you don't want to be embarrassed by losing in less than 20 moves to an unsound Monkey's Bum Gambit!   Recently, big chess influencers like IM Rosen, IM Levy Rozman, a.k.a Gothamchess, and GM Simon Williams  (GingerGM)  have been posting tons of YouTube videos, recommending lots of unsound gambits. The big one is of course the Stafford Gambit, where Black gambits a central pawn early and sometimes gets a big winning attack. These gambits are tricky, have a big surprise value, and work well in blitz & rapid time controls.  I started refuting these gambits one by one in my popular Every Gambit Refuted series on chess.com. However, I believe that Chessable is the perfect platform to actually LEARN the moves on how to refute a bunch of these gambits. Thus, this course!  In my course, I hold nothing back and give you the best and most practical ways to handle many gambits. Some are silly like the Monkey's Bum Gambit while others are quite popular such as the King's Gambit and the Benko Gambit. Overall, you will see 35 gambits in total for both White & Black sides. I picked the most common gambits, with a big focus on those recommended by GothamChess, GingerGM, and Eric Rosen.  My philosophy is to choose lines that are most practical and easy to understand & remember. You will see lots of fresh ideas and new setups, with a total of over 30  (!)  novelties.  Please enjoy this course and share with me your favorite wins on the Discussion board! }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nxe5 Nc6
{ This is the famous Stafford Gambit. It's easy to get in trouble with White after natural moves. }
4. Nxc6 dxc6 5. Nc3 Bc5 6. Be2
{ 6.h3!  This little pawn move is my refutation of the gambit.  It's vital to overprotect the key g4-square, and to be able to meet  6...Qd4  with  7.Qf3  . }
6... Qd4 7. O-O h5
{ 7...Nxe4  is better, but for illustrative purposes, let's see how the game could unfold after the text move. }
8. h3
{ A natural move to stop ...Ng4, but  8.d3!  is the only move to fight back:  8...Ng4  9.Bxg4  hxg4  10.Bf4!  and White should hold off Black's attack for now. }
8... Ng4 9. hxg4 hxg4 { Believe it or not, White is already lost! } 10. g3 Qe5
11. Kg2 Bxf2 { White's kingside structure is totally destroyed. } 12. Rxf2
{ 12.Kxf2  Rh2+  13.Ke3  @@StartBracket@@  13.Kg1  Qxg3  @@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@r1b1k3/ppp2pp1/2p5/4q3/4P1p1/2N1K1P1/PPPPB2r/R1BQ1R2 b q - 2 13@@EndFEN@@  13...Qxg3+  14.Kd4  Be6-+  and the king is about to be checkmated soon... }
12... Qh5
{ White will have to give up too much material to stop the mate.  I hope this example convinces you that it's important to be prepared for such gambits. The good news is that you can start learning the Stafford Gambit refutation right away! }
