1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Bc5
{ The game starts as a well-known Giuoco Piano @@StartBracket@@Italian for Quiet Game@@EndBracket@@ or also known as the Italian Game. }
4. c3 { White prepares to take over the center with the d4 push next. } 4...
Nf6 5. d4
{ This was analyzed by the Italian player Greco in the 17th century. He is not only known for gambits but perhaps for being the first ever professional chess player! It is also said that Greco was the first to record chess games in written notation, perhaps his greatest legacy! }
5... exd4 6. cxd4
{ White achieves their goal of full central control for now.  6.e5!?  is a very popular move these days. It is recommended by GM Wesley So in his Chessable course. }
6... Bb4+
{ The key move that allows Black rapid counterplay against the e4-pawn. } 7.
Nc3
{ This move was analyzed by Greco; White gambits the e4-pawn.  7.Bd2!?  and  7.Nbd2!?  are interesting continuations. }
7... Nxe4 { Black should take the central pawn! } 8. O-O Bxc3
{ The most precise! } 9. d5
{ This move is known as the Møller Attack, first published by the Danish player in 1898. Black has a big choice to make, with two pieces under attack. }
9... Bf6
{ Preserving the bishop is best, as it acts as a powerful attacker on the long diagonal and as a defender of our kingside. }
10. Re1 { White pins the e4-knight. } 10... Ne7 11. Rxe4 d6
{ Black stabilized the position and is about to castle. White has just enough compensation for the pawn to maintain equality but not more. }
12. Bg5 Bxg5 13. Nxg5 h6
{ The most accurate.  13...O-O  allows an annoying sacrifice:  14.Nxh7!  Kxh7  15.Qh5+  Kg8  16.Rh4  f5  17.Qh7+  Kf7  18.Rh6!  Rg8!  @@StartBracket@@  18...Bd7?  loses after  19.Be2!  @@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@r1bq2r1/ppp1nkpQ/3p3R/3P1p2/2B5/8/PP3PPP/R5K1 w - - 4 19@@EndFEN@@  19.Re1  , with a strong attack. }
14. Qh5 O-O
{ Don't be afraid to castle, as White doesn't really have any threats on the kingside for now. }
15. Rae1 Nf5
{ Now Black wants to take the knight.  15...hxg5??  loses to  16.Rxe7+-  , with a winning attack for White. }
16. Nxf7 { Hoping for a trick... } 16... Qf6
{ A must-know move that traps the knight. Don't fall for  16...Rxf7?  17.Re8++-  . }
