{ Black stops Qh5+ and will play ...Kf8-g7 next. White is struggling to generate any counterplay. Black is clearly better.   20.Qf3  is nothing to worry about given  20...Qa5  21.Re2  Qf5  , and if now  22.Qb3  O-O-O-+  ,  White is down a pawn and the king on g1 is weak as well.   Conclusion: The Møller Gambit or Møller Attack is not dangerous at all if you know the key defensive setup starting with @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/pppp1ppp/2n5/3P4/2B1n3/2b2N2/PP3PPP/R1BQ1RK1 b kq - 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9...Bf6!  and followed up by @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/pppp1ppp/2n2b2/3P4/2B1n3/5N2/PP3PPP/R1BQR1K1 b kq - 2 10@@EndFEN@@  10...Ne7  and @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/ppppnppp/5b2/3P4/2B1R3/5N2/PP3PPP/R1BQ2K1 b kq - 0 11@@EndFEN@@  11...d6!  This is well-known theory and known to be totally fine for Black. Remember the cool idea in the main line: @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/ppp1npp1/3p4/3P2p1/2B1R3/8/PP2QPPP/4R1K1 b kq - 1 15@@EndFEN@@  15...Be6!!  , which will surely shock your opponent! Black aims to create a nice pawn fortress and will eventually convert the extra pawn. }
