1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Bc5 4. b4
{ The Evans Gambit, named after the Welsh sea Captain William Davies Evans from the 1800s, is a favorite move of the famous Youtuber Agadmator. The main point of the pawn sacrifice is that White wins a tempo to get a superior center with c3 & d4.   First of all, I'd like to point out that this is a totally sound gambit, meaning that there's no refutation. It was played by such chess giants as Garry Kasparov and Magnus Carlsen!  However, I will show you a simple setup where Black willingly returns the pawn back to reach a superior pawn structure. }
4... Bxb4
{ We take the pawn, which is the best and the most principled reply. } 5. c3
Be7
{ This variation is the Lasker Defense, and it's quite popular at GM level. Most players prefer the autopilot  5...Bc5  or  5...Ba5  , however the statistics after  5...Be7!  are quite good for Black!  In the lichess database, White's winning percentage is the following:  5...Bc5  @@StartBracket@@1.3 million games, 57% score for White@@EndBracket@@,  5...Ba5  @@StartBracket@@1.1 million games, 51% score for White@@EndBracket@@,  5...Be7  @@StartBracket@@500,  000  games, 49% score for White@@EndBracket@@.  So, your opponent will likely be surprised since it's the 3rd most popular move. But the big bonus is that this setup is very strong for Black! }
6. d4 { The main line, White immediately builds a strong center. } 6... Na5
{ The key idea to remember. This move looks awkward at first. Black moves the same piece twice in the opening and puts the knight on the rim. But chess is a concrete game and the ideas will become clear soon.  It's vital to attack the c4-bishop. White has two approaches here: retreat with the bishop to a more passive square @@StartBracket@@e2 or d3@@EndBracket@@ or take the pawn with Nxe5. }
7. Be2 { Kasparov's choice and Magnus tried it once too. } 7... d6
{ For simplicity, I would recommend the same approach for Black to keep the center intact. We also play this way vs. @@StartFEN@@r1bqk1nr/ppppbppp/8/n3p3/2BPP3/2P2N2/P4PPP/RNBQK2R w KQkq - 1 7@@EndFEN@@  7.Bd3  , which is easy to remember!   7...exd4  8.Qxd4  is the famous game Kasparov-Anand, 1995 that White won. However, this position is totally fine for Black with both  8...d6  and  8...Nf6  . }
8. dxe5 dxe5 9. Qxd8+ { 9.Qa4+  c6  10.Nxe5  transposes. See 8...Qa4+. } 9...
Bxd8 10. Nxe5 Nf6
{ White got the pawn back, but the endgame is actually unpleasant for them. Just compare the pawn structures for Black & White. The big glaring weaknesses on e4, c3, and a2 are not easy to fix. Black is clearly better long-term, even though the engine claims 0.00. }
