{ A nice novelty! The knight is targeting f2 and sets up a cool trap in case of h3.   15...c5  16.Bb2  Nc6  17.Qc2  Rad8=  , with about an even game was seen in Shomoev-Sakaev, Plovdiv 2008. }
16. h3
{ White is unaware of the dangers... After  16.Bb2  Bc5⩱  , White is forced to play a passive move like  17.Rf1  . Black is clearly in control. }
16... Nxf2
{ A sudden sacrifice out of the blue that jump-starts the winning attack! } 17.
Kxf2 Bc5+ { Driving the king back. } 18. Kf1 { 18.Ke1  Qg3+  19.Kf1  Qf2# }
18... Qg3
{ White can't stop the forced mate! Game over.   Conclusion: The Evans Gambit is a serious opening as White aims to win full control of the center. However, with two unusual moves @@StartFEN@@r1bqk1nr/pppp1ppp/2n5/4p3/1bB1P3/2P2N2/P2P1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Be7!  (a backward move)  and @@StartFEN@@r1bqk1nr/ppppbppp/2n5/4p3/2BPP3/2P2N2/P4PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Na5!  , Black happily gives up the pawn to get excellent counterplay. We will either get a solid structure with the bishop pair or long-term counterplay targeting White’s damaged pawns on the queenside. }
