[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3) Deutz Gambit"]
[Black "Deutz Gambit 5.d4 − 7.Bg5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Bc5 4. O-O Nf6 5. d4
{ This is the Deutz Gambit, sometimes also known as the Italian Gambit or the Koltanowski Gambit. George Koltanowski was an American chess player, famous for setting the world's blindfold record in 1937 by playing 34 chess games simultaneously!   These days, the gambit is played by some top players such as Abdusattorov and Dubov. White happily gives up the central pawn for rapid development. Accuracy is required from Black! }
5... Bxd4
{ The best move!  5...exd4  6.e5  d5  leads to a sharp and doubled-edged Max Lange Attack.   5...Nxd4?  is bad,  as it gives up the e5-pawn:  6.Nxe5  , with a nice edge for White. }
6. Nxd4 Nxd4 7. Bg5
{ A less popular choice than  7.f4  , but a logical move, as White establishes a pin right away. This is the preferred move by GM Abdusattorov. }
7... h6 { Asking the bishop a question on its intentions. } 8. Bh4
{ It's important for White to maintain the pin. } 8... Qe7
{ I like this quiet queen move, preparing an aggressive idea!   8...d6  is a standard reaction, leading to a forced endgame after  9.f4  Bg4  10.Bxf6  Bxd1  11.Bxd8  Rxd8  12.Rxd1  Nxc2  13.Nc3  Nxa1  14.Rxa1  exf4  15.Nd5  Kd7  16.Nxf4  Rhe8⩱  as in the game Riehle-Vrolijk, chess.com 2020. The imbalance of R+2P vs N+B favors Black here. }
9. f4 { White's most logical move, trying to pry open the f-file. } 9... Qc5
{ The point behind Black's last move. Now the game gets quite sharp and requires very accurate play from White. }
10. Bxf7+
{ This was played in a few games in the database, but the sacrifice is not sound. }
10... Kxf7 11. Bxf6 gxf6 12. fxe5 Qxe5
{ Black has a nice defensive shield with the f-pawn, queen, and knight. White is lacking any attacking ideas. Black eventually converted the extra piece in the game Lopez Silva-Hess, Khanty-Mansiysk 2010. }
*

