[White "4) Jerome Gambit"]
[Black "Jerome Gambit 4.Bxf7+ Kxf7 5.Nxe5 Nxe5 6.Qh5+ #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Bc5
{ The game starts as a normal Italian or Giucco Piano, which is a respectable opening, known for its deep strategic ideas for both sides. }
4. Bxf7+
{ This crazy bishop sacrifice for a pawn, out of nowhere, is the worst or one of the worst gambits that you will see in this Chessable course! It was first played by an American player, Alonzo Wheeler Jerome @@StartBracket@@1834-1902@@EndBracket@@, and published in Dubuque Chess Journal in 1876.  Chess romantics of that era perhaps may have used the gambit, but it doesn't stand a chance to modern scrutiny. Chess engines think the move is so bad that it's not even close to the top 20 moves White can play in this position.   Yes, even moves like going back with  4.Bf1  or  4.Ng1  is much better than this 'sacrifice'. Hopefully, after learning the lines, you will refer to this as Jerome's blunder rather than Jerome Gambit! Let me show you the simple refutation. }
4... Kxf7 { Of course, we take the free gift. } 5. Nxe5+
{ This knight sacrifice is the 'big' follow-up. But after giving up a 2nd piece, White's best hope is trying to win one back but will still be totally lost. }
5... Nxe5 { Black now has 2 extra minor pieces for two pawns. } 6. Qh5+
{ White tries to use Black's slightly exposed king to set up a double attack. }
6... g6
{ I like the direct approach here: let's give White hope that they will win some material back.   6...Kf8  7.Qxe5  d6-+  should be winning for Black, but for those who like to live dangerously, @@StartFEN@@r1bq2nr/pppp1kpp/8/2b1n2Q/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNB1K2R b KQ - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Ke6!?  works too.  7.Qf5+  Kd6  8.f4  Qf6  9.fxe5+  Qxe5-+  .   6...Ng6?!  7.Qd5+  Kf8  8.Qxc5+  d6  9.Qe3  gives White some chances, while @@StartFEN@@r1bq2nr/pppp1kpp/8/2b1n2Q/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNB1K2R b KQ - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Ke7??  DON'T DO THIS!  7.Qxe5+  Kf7  8.Qxc5+-  and White is totally winning now. }
7. Qxe5
{ Forced. Now it seems like the gambit worked. White is attacking the rook and the bishop, what to do? }
7... Qe7
{ The star move and the only winning move in this position! I like that we give White some hope after they win the h8-rook. }
8. Qxh8
{ White takes the bait, but what else to do?  8.Qd5+  Kg7-+  should be an easy win for Black with an extra piece. }
8... Qxe4+ { Now, it's White's monarch who's feeling uncomfortable... } 9. Kf1
Nf6
{ The simplest, now the queen on h8 has nowhere to go, and it's a matter of time before we either trap it or get a deadly attack. }
10. d3 Qh4 { Threatening mate in one move. } 11. g3 Qh3+ 12. Kg1 b6
{ A simple and effective way to finish the game. White should resign due to the unstoppable ...Bb7 with mate or trapping the queen. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4) Jerome Gambit"]
[Black "Jerome Gambit 4.Bxf7+ Kxf7 5.Nxe5 Nxe5 6.Qh5+ #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Bc5
{ The game starts as a normal Italian or Giucco Piano, which is a respectable opening, known for its deep strategic ideas for both sides. }
4. Bxf7+
{ This crazy bishop sacrifice for a pawn, out of nowhere, is the worst or one of the worst gambits that you will see in this Chessable course! It was first played by an American player, Alonzo Wheeler Jerome @@StartBracket@@1834-1902@@EndBracket@@, and published in Dubuque Chess Journal in 1876.  Chess romantics of that era perhaps may have used the gambit, but it doesn't stand a chance to modern scrutiny. Chess engines think the move is so bad that it's not even close to the top 20 moves White can play in this position.   Yes, even moves like going back with  4.Bf1  or  4.Ng1  is much better than this 'sacrifice'. Hopefully, after learning the lines, you will refer to this as Jerome's blunder rather than Jerome Gambit! Let me show you the simple refutation. }
4... Kxf7 { Of course, we take the free gift. } 5. Nxe5+
{ This knight sacrifice is the 'big' follow-up. But after giving up a 2nd piece, White's best hope is trying to win one back but will still be totally lost. }
5... Nxe5 { Black now has 2 extra minor pieces for two pawns. } 6. Qh5+
{ White tries to use Black's slightly exposed king to set up a double attack. }
6... g6
{ I like the direct approach here: let's give White hope that they will win some material back.   6...Kf8  7.Qxe5  d6-+  should be winning for Black, but for those who like to live dangerously, @@StartFEN@@r1bq2nr/pppp1kpp/8/2b1n2Q/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNB1K2R b KQ - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Ke6!?  works too.  7.Qf5+  Kd6  8.f4  Qf6  9.fxe5+  Qxe5-+  .   6...Ng6?!  7.Qd5+  Kf8  8.Qxc5+  d6  9.Qe3  gives White some chances, while @@StartFEN@@r1bq2nr/pppp1kpp/8/2b1n2Q/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNB1K2R b KQ - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Ke7??  DON'T DO THIS!  7.Qxe5+  Kf7  8.Qxc5+-  and White is totally winning now. }
7. Qxe5
{ Forced. Now it seems like the gambit worked. White is attacking the rook and the bishop, what to do? }
7... Qe7
{ The star move and the only winning move in this position! I like that we give White some hope after they win the h8-rook. }
8. Qxh8
{ White takes the bait, but what else to do?  8.Qd5+  Kg7-+  should be an easy win for Black with an extra piece. }
8... Qxe4+ { Now, it's White's monarch who's feeling uncomfortable... } 9. Kd1
Qg4+ { 9...Qxg2  also wins. } 10. f3
{ After  10.Ke1  Nf6-+  , White's queen is trapped  on h8, and Black has a killer attack. Please note that White can't castle! }
10... Qxg2
{ Black invades deep into the enemy territory. White is totally lost here, but let me show you a fun line. }
11. Qxh7+ Kf8 12. Re1 Qxf3+ 13. Re2 { White's army is all tied up. } 13... d5
{ Simple chess, we just want to play ...Bg4 next. } 14. Nc3
{ This allows a pretty checkmate. } 14... Qf1+ 15. Re1 Bg4+ 16. Ne2 Bxe2#
{ Conclusion: Perhaps a fun gambit in romantic times, the Jerome Gambit doesn't stand a chance with modern scrutiny. I decided to show you a fun line that involves giving up the rook on h8 with a deadly attack, however, you can pretty much do anything against this bygone opening idea. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5) The Dark Knight Gambit"]
[Black "The Dark Knight Gambit 4...Nxe4 5.Bxf7+ Ke7 6.d4 Nxd4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Nf6 4. Ng5
{ White begins the game with the Fried Liver Attack. } 4... Nxe4
{ Recommended by IM Levy Rozman  (GothamChess)  , this dubious capture is known as the Dark Knight Gambit. But I will show you the refutation! }
5. Bxf7+
{ You have to be precise! This is the only way to refute Black, but it's a very natural move.  5.Nxf7?  is very tempting and exactly what GothamChess expects from White. After  5...Qh4!  ,  Black is threatening mate on f2 and gets a huge attack. }
5... Ke7 6. d4
{ The most difficult move! But this is the refutation of Levy's Dark Knight Gambit. White opens up the c1-bishop & blows up the center, while Black's king is found right in the crossfire. }
6... Nxd4 { 6...Nxg5??  7.Bxg5+  is a big oops. } 7. c3 Nc6 8. Bb3
{ White happily traded the d4-pawn for the f7-pawn and made Black's king go for a little walk. White has a clear edge as Nf7 or O-O is next, with a big attack. Please note that Black can't do anything to release the pressure, not even taking on g5, as White will recapture with a skewer.   8.Bd5  is good too, while  8.Bc4  works as well. }
