[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6) Scotch Gambit − Max Lange Attack"]
[Black "Max Lange Attack 6.c3 Bg4 7.Qb3 Bxf3 8.gxf3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Bc4
{ White goes for the Scotch Gambit move order. } 4... Bc5
{ A logical move. Black develops the bishop while defending the central pawn.  4...Nf6  5.O-O  Nxe4  is covered in the Scotch Gambit − Anderssen Attack. }
5. O-O
{ 5.c3!  is the main line, but rather than the gambit variations, we now transpose to the well-known Giuoco Piano  (or the Italian Game)  after  5...Nf6!  6.cxd4  @@StartBracket@@  6.e5!?  d5!  is a popular line these days recommended by Wesley So in his Chessable course.@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/pppp1ppp/2n2n2/2b5/2BPP3/5N2/PP3PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Bb4+  . I covered the gambit lines with  7.Nc3  in the Moller Gambit chapter. }
5... d6
{ With this little pawn move we avoid the main line of the Max Lange Attack.   5...Nf6  6.e5!  d5!  Black's best try!  7.exf6  dxc4  8.fxg7  Rg8  , this sharp position is the classic Max Lange Attack that we're trying to avoid as Black. I believe it's easier to play with White, as our king is quite weak. }
6. c3
{ The most popular move. White doesn't care about pawns and tries to go for rapid development. }
6... Bg4
{ I believe this is the best move: we develop while pinning the enemy knight. Interesting that it was first played by Staunton in 1841! }
7. Qb3
{ White creates an annoying battery on the f7-pawn as well as hitting the b7-pawn. }
7... Bxf3
{ The key intermezzo! Black ruins White's pawn structure but allows them to take on f7. }
8. gxf3 { This allows a strong regrouping. } 8... Ne5
{ The key move that gives Black a nice edge. } 9. f4 Nxc4 10. Qxc4 Bb6
{ A strong novelty. } 11. cxd4 d5
{ The point! Black undermines White's strong center. } 12. exd5 Ne7 13. Nc3 O-O
14. Be3 Qd7
{ Black is better, as we will pick up the d5-pawn after ...Rad8. White is left with a terrible pawn structure. }
*

