[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "7) Scotch Gambit − Anderssen Attack"]
[Black "Anderssen Attack  5.O-O Nxe4 6.Nc3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Bc4
{ This is the Scotch Gambit, a tricky opening! } 4... Nf6
{ An invitation to the Two Knights Defense. } 5. O-O
{ White sacrifices another pawn but gets a big lead in development.  5.e5  d5  6.Bb5  Ne4  is the main line of the Two Knights Defense. }
5... Nxe4
{ The principled approach!   The sharp  5...Bc5!?  6.e5  d5!  7.exf6  dxc4  8.fxg7  Rg8  is the classic Max Lange Attack that we're trying to avoid as Black. }
6. Nc3 { Magnus Carlsen tried it in an online bullet game vs. Andrew Tang. }
6... d5
{ The best move!  6...dxc3  7.Bxf7+  Kxf7  8.Qd5+  Kf6  9.Qxe4  leads to a crazy position  with Black's king totally exposed on f6. I wouldn't recommend this line unless you love to live dangerously! }
7. Bxd5 { A better try than  7.Nxd5  , which is analyzed next. } 7... dxc3 8.
Bxe4 Qxd1 9. Rxd1 Bd7 10. bxc3 O-O-O
{ Black is a bit better in this endgame due to White's shattered pawns. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "7) Scotch Gambit − Anderssen Attack"]
[Black "Anderssen Attack  5.O-O Nxe4 6.Nc3 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Bc4
{ This is the Scotch Gambit, a tricky opening! } 4... Nf6
{ An invitation to the Two Knights Defense. } 5. O-O
{ White sacrifices another pawn but gets a big lead in development.  5.e5  d5  6.Bb5  Ne4  is the main line of the Two Knights Defense. }
5... Nxe4
{ The principled approach!   The sharp  5...Bc5!?  6.e5  d5!  7.exf6  dxc4  8.fxg7  Rg8  is the classic Max Lange Attack that we're trying to avoid as Black. }
6. Nc3 { Magnus Carlsen tried it in an online bullet game vs. Andrew Tang. }
6... d5
{ The best move!  6...dxc3  7.Bxf7+  Kxf7  8.Qd5+  Kf6  9.Qxe4  leads to a crazy position  with Black's king totally exposed on f6. I wouldn't recommend this line unless you love to live dangerously! }
7. Nxd5
{ This is already a losing move! But if it was played by World #1, your opponent may also play it! }
7... Be6 { All of a sudden, the knight is trapped in the middle of the board. }
8. Ng5 Bxd5 9. Bxd5 Nxg5
{ Accuracy is needed!  9...Qxd5?  allows White to win back the piece with  10.Nxe4  and Black can't take on e4, as  10...Qxe4??  11.Re1+-  loses the queen. }
10. Re1+ Ne6 { Black's knight is a hero in this game! } 11. Qh5 g6
{ This fends off White's attack and Black should win with the extra piece. }
12. Rxe6+ { A desperate attempt. } 12... fxe6 13. Bxc6+ bxc6 14. Qe5 Rg8
{ The most precise, White is lost.  14...Qe7  should also win as in the bullet game Carlsen-Tang, lichess.org 2021. }
15. Qxe6+ Qe7 { Due to the back-rank mate, it's all over. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "7) Scotch Gambit − Anderssen Attack"]
[Black "Anderssen Attack  5.O-O Nxe4 6.Re1 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Bc4
{ This is the Scotch Gambit, a tricky opening! } 4... Nf6
{ An invitation to the Two Knights Defense. } 5. O-O
{ White sacrifices another pawn but gets a big lead in development.  5.e5  d5  6.Bb5  Ne4  is the main line of the Two Knights Defense. }
5... Nxe4
{ The principled approach!   The sharp  5...Bc5!?  6.e5  d5!  7.exf6  dxc4  8.fxg7  Rg8  is the classic Max Lange Attack that we're trying to avoid as Black. }
6. Re1
{ White pins the knight and puts a lot of pressure on the e-file. This has been played by many top players. Recently Gawain Jones beat Wesley So in a rapid game, as Wesley forgot the correct move and lost in a 19-move miniature! }
6... d5 7. Nc3
{ An interesting move. White offers us a choice of which piece to take. } 7...
dxc3
{ Taking the knight is the best move.  7...dxc4  8.Rxe4+  Be7  is playable as well, and now after  9.Nxd4  f5!  10.Rf4!  , we have a truly fighting game! }
8. Bxd5 Be6
{ I like this simple developing move. We are about to lose the e4-knight anyway, so let's develop. }
9. Rxe4 { This loses to a not-so-obvious pin tactic. } 9... Ne7
{ White will now lose the light-squared bishop. } *

