[Black "Anderssen Attack  5.O-O Nxe4 6.Re1 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Bc4
{ This is the Scotch Gambit, a tricky opening! } 4... Nf6
{ An invitation to the Two Knights Defense. } 5. O-O
{ White sacrifices another pawn but gets a big lead in development.  5.e5  d5  6.Bb5  Ne4  is the main line of the Two Knights Defense. }
5... Nxe4
{ The principled approach!   The sharp  5...Bc5!?  6.e5  d5!  7.exf6  dxc4  8.fxg7  Rg8  is the classic Max Lange Attack that we're trying to avoid as Black. }
6. Re1
{ White pins the knight and puts a lot of pressure on the e-file. This has been played by many top players. Recently Gawain Jones beat Wesley So in a rapid game, as Wesley forgot the correct move and lost in a 19-move miniature! }
6... d5 7. Bxd5 Qxd5 8. Nc3
{ This is the so-called Anderssen Attack, named after an attacking genius Adolf Anderssen @@StartBracket@@1818-1879@@EndBracket@@. He was a German master well-known for the 'Evergreen game' vs. Kieseritzky. Anderssen also famously lost to Paul Morphy in a match held in Paris in 1858. Morphy won 8-3 and became the unofficial World Champion of that time!  White wins a pawn with this nifty little tactic, but with accurate play, Black is able to neutralize White's initiative. }
8... Qd7
{ A rare move, but the one that gives Black good winning chances!   8...Qa5  is fine as was seen in Jones-So, but look what could happen if you forget your prep:  9.Nxe4  Be6  10.Bd2  Qf5  11.Bg5  Bc5?  , a losing move by Wesley!  @@StartBracket@@  11...h6!  keeps the game balanced@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@r3k2r/ppp2ppp/2n1b3/2b2qB1/3pN3/5N2/PPP2PPP/R2QR1K1 w kq - 5 12@@EndFEN@@  12.Nh4!  Qd5  13.c4!!  and Black is lost.  13...Qe5  @@StartBracket@@  13...dxc3  14.Nf6+  gxf6  15.Qxd5+-  , or  13...Qxc4  14.Rc1+-  @@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@r3k2r/ppp2ppp/2n1b3/2b1q1B1/2PpN2N/8/PP3PPP/R2QR1K1 w kq - 1 14@@EndFEN@@  14.Nf3  @@StartBracket@@  14.f4!  also wins@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@r3k2r/ppp2ppp/2n1b3/2b1q1B1/2PpN3/5N2/PP3PPP/R2QR1K1 b kq - 2 14@@EndFEN@@  14...Qf5  15.Nh4  Qe5  16.f4!  d3+  17.Kh1  Qd4  18.Nf3  Qxc4  19.Rc1  1-0 Jones-So, chess24.com 2021. }
9. Nxe4 { White's most common move, but it quickly leads to equality. } 9...
Be7 { Black gets ready to castle. } 10. Bg5 O-O 11. Bxe7 Qxe7 12. Nxd4
{ White wins the pawn back. } 12... Bd7
{ The game is even, as the pawn structure is symmetrical. } *

