1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Bc4
{ This is the Scotch Gambit, a tricky opening! } 4... Nf6
{ An invitation to the Two Knights Defense. } 5. O-O
{ White sacrifices another pawn but gets a big lead in development.  5.e5  d5  6.Bb5  Ne4  is the main line of the Two Knights Defense. }
5... Nxe4
{ The principled approach!   The sharp  5...Bc5!?  6.e5  d5!  7.exf6  dxc4  8.fxg7  Rg8  is the classic Max Lange Attack that we're trying to avoid as Black. }
6. Re1
{ White pins the knight and puts a lot of pressure on the e-file. This has been played by many top players. Recently Gawain Jones beat Wesley So in a rapid game, as Wesley forgot the correct move and lost in a 19-move miniature! }
6... d5 7. Bxd5 Qxd5 8. Nc3
{ This is the so-called Anderssen Attack, named after an attacking genius Adolf Anderssen @@StartBracket@@1818-1879@@EndBracket@@. He was a German master well-known for the 'Evergreen game' vs. Kieseritzky. Anderssen also famously lost to Paul Morphy in a match held in Paris in 1858. Morphy won 8-3 and became the unofficial World Champion of that time!  White wins a pawn with this nifty little tactic, but with accurate play, Black is able to neutralize White's initiative. }
8... Qd7
{ A rare move, but the one that gives Black good winning chances!   8...Qa5  is fine as was seen in Jones-So, but look what could happen if you forget your prep:  9.Nxe4  Be6  10.Bd2  Qf5  11.Bg5  Bc5?  , a losing move by Wesley!  @@StartBracket@@  11...h6!  keeps the game balanced@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@r3k2r/ppp2ppp/2n1b3/2b2qB1/3pN3/5N2/PPP2PPP/R2QR1K1 w kq - 5 12@@EndFEN@@  12.Nh4!  Qd5  13.c4!!  and Black is lost.  13...Qe5  @@StartBracket@@  13...dxc3  14.Nf6+  gxf6  15.Qxd5+-  , or  13...Qxc4  14.Rc1+-  @@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@r3k2r/ppp2ppp/2n1b3/2b1q1B1/2PpN2N/8/PP3PPP/R2QR1K1 w kq - 1 14@@EndFEN@@  14.Nf3  @@StartBracket@@  14.f4!  also wins@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@r3k2r/ppp2ppp/2n1b3/2b1q1B1/2PpN3/5N2/PP3PPP/R2QR1K1 b kq - 2 14@@EndFEN@@  14...Qf5  15.Nh4  Qe5  16.f4!  d3+  17.Kh1  Qd4  18.Nf3  Qxc4  19.Rc1  1-0 Jones-So, chess24.com 2021. }
9. Rxe4+ { White's most ambitious try. } 9... Be7 10. Nxd4 f5
{ A must-know move for Black! This is the way to fight for an edge, as White has to be careful now. }
11. Rf4
{ An awkward square for the rook, but it has to keep the knight protected. }
11... O-O { Black's king is now safe. } 12. Nxc6 Qxc6 13. Nd5 Bd6 14. Rd4 Be6
{ Black has easy play thanks to the bishop pair and an open position. White is still not fully developed and lacks coordination.   Conclusion: The Anderssen Attack in the Scotch Gambit is a tricky line, as White is trying to confuse us with various piece sacrifice ideas. However, if you are well-prepared, even Magnus Carlsen sitting in front of you won’t stop you from getting a nice edge with Black.  Remember some key ideas such as @@StartFEN@@r1b1kb1r/ppp2ppp/2n5/3q4/3pn3/2N2N2/PPP2PPP/R1BQR1K1 b kq - 1 8@@EndFEN@@  8...Qd7!?  in the main line, with a small but pleasant edge, as well as @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pppp1ppp/2n5/8/2Bpn3/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQ1RK1 w kq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Nc3  d5!  , leading to a good position for Black as GM Andrew Tang demonstrated by beating Magnus. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8) Belgrade Gambit"]
[Black "Belgrade Gambit 5.Nd5 Nb4 6.Bg5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. d4
{ The game starts out as a quiet Four Knights Scotch, but... } 4... exd4 5. Nd5
{ This rare move is known as the Belgrade Gambit. It was played by attacking genius Mikhail Tal in the 1950s, and these days a popular streamer, GM Daniel Naroditsky, uses it quite successfully. Daniel has beaten both Carlsen and Nakamura with this gambit in bullet chess! We have to take this one seriously! }
5... Nb4
{ Black's best move but a very difficult one to play without any knowledge. Interesting that both Carlsen & Nakamura didn't play this move. Perhaps, they should buy my course?! The idea of the ...Nb4 jump is to trade the d5-knight as quickly as possible with ...Nbxd5!   5...Nxe4  is playable but risky, as both  6.Bd3  and  6.Qe2  give White some initiative.   5...Nxd5?  is exactly what White is hoping to see.  6.exd5  Nb4  7.Bc4⩲  , with a clear  edge for White as the b4-knight is a bit stranded and the d4-pawn is also hit. }
6. Bg5 { This allows Black to demonstrate the idea in full. } 6... Nbxd5 7.
exd5 Bb4+ { Making White play a defensive move, losing a tempo. } 8. Nd2 O-O
{ Black is the first to develop. We will follow up with ...Re8+ and ...h6 next. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8) Belgrade Gambit"]
[Black "Belgrade Gambit 5.Nd5 Nb4 6.Bc4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. d4
{ The game starts out as a quiet Four Knights Scotch, but... } 4... exd4 5. Nd5
{ This rare move is known as the Belgrade Gambit. It was played by attacking genius Mikhail Tal in the 1950s, and these days a popular streamer, GM Daniel Naroditsky, uses it quite successfully. Daniel has beaten both Carlsen and Nakamura with this gambit in bullet chess! We have to take this one seriously! }
5... Nb4
{ Black's best move but a very difficult one to play without any knowledge. Interesting that both Carlsen & Nakamura didn't play this move. Perhaps, they should buy my course?! The idea of the ...Nb4 jump is to trade the d5-knight as quickly as possible with ...Nbxd5!   5...Nxe4  is playable but risky, as both  6.Bd3  and  6.Qe2  give White some initiative.   5...Nxd5?  is exactly what White is hoping to see.  6.exd5  Nb4  7.Bc4⩲  , with a clear  edge for White as the b4-knight is a bit stranded and the d4-pawn is also hit. }
6. Bc4
{ This is the 2nd most played move after  6.Nxf6+  . White goes for rapid development. }
6... Nbxd5 { Black is happy to do this trade. } 7. exd5 Bb4+
{ Now White has to make some uncomfortable choices. } 8. Kf1
{ This is the most aggressive idea, but also dangerous, as the king loses the right to castle. }
8... Be7
{ I like this solid regrouping, but Black has many promising moves here. The point of ...Be7 is to prepare for the Bg5 pin. }
9. Nxd4
{ 9.Bg5  h6  10.Bh4  O-O  11.Qxd4  d6  transposes to the 9.Qxd4 variation. }
9... d6
{ We'll follow with ...O-O and natural development, with easy play for Black, while White struggles to coordinate the pieces. }
*

