[Black "Belgrade Gambit 5.Nd5 Nb4 6.Bc4 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. d4
{ The game starts out as a quiet Four Knights Scotch, but... } 4... exd4 5. Nd5
{ This rare move is known as the Belgrade Gambit. It was played by attacking genius Mikhail Tal in the 1950s, and these days a popular streamer, GM Daniel Naroditsky, uses it quite successfully. Daniel has beaten both Carlsen and Nakamura with this gambit in bullet chess! We have to take this one seriously! }
5... Nb4
{ Black's best move but a very difficult one to play without any knowledge. Interesting that both Carlsen & Nakamura didn't play this move. Perhaps, they should buy my course?! The idea of the ...Nb4 jump is to trade the d5-knight as quickly as possible with ...Nbxd5!   5...Nxe4  is playable but risky, as both  6.Bd3  and  6.Qe2  give White some initiative.   5...Nxd5?  is exactly what White is hoping to see.  6.exd5  Nb4  7.Bc4⩲  , with a clear  edge for White as the b4-knight is a bit stranded and the d4-pawn is also hit. }
6. Bc4
{ This is the 2nd most played move after  6.Nxf6+  . White goes for rapid development. }
6... Nbxd5 { Black is happy to do this trade. } 7. exd5 Bb4+
{ Now White has to make some uncomfortable choices. } 8. Kf1
{ This is the most aggressive idea, but also dangerous, as the king loses the right to castle. }
8... Be7
{ I like this solid regrouping, but Black has many promising moves here. The point of ...Be7 is to prepare for the Bg5 pin. }
9. Qxd4
{ This was played by a Swedish GM Jonny Hector in a recent game.  9.Bg5  h6  10.Bh4  O-O  11.Qxd4  d6  transposes. }
9... d6 10. Bg5 h6
{ It's a good idea to insert this before kingside castling to discourage White from playing h4 with a classic piece sac.   10...O-O  is playable but passive.  11.Bd3  Re8  @@StartBracket@@  11...h6  12.h4!  is exactly what we don't want to allow as Black!@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@r1bqr1k1/ppp1bppp/3p1n2/3P2B1/3Q4/3B1N2/PPP2PPP/R4K1R w - - 4 12@@EndFEN@@  12.Re1  Bd7  , Black allows White an attack:  13.h4!  as in the game Hector-Krantz, Vaxjo 2023. }
11. Bh4 O-O 12. Bd3 { Here Black can choose among several plans. } 12... c5
{ My favorite setup. Black is ready to open up the position, as White's h1-rook is not entering the game anytime soon. }
13. dxc6 bxc6 14. Re1 c5
{ With active play! I prefer Black here, as clearly the combo of Kf1 & Rh1 is not what White wanted. }
