[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. d4
{ The game starts out as a quiet Four Knights Scotch, but... } 4... exd4 5. Nd5
{ This rare move is known as the Belgrade Gambit. It was played by attacking genius Mikhail Tal in the 1950s, and these days a popular streamer, GM Daniel Naroditsky, uses it quite successfully. Daniel has beaten both Carlsen and Nakamura with this gambit in bullet chess! We have to take this one seriously! }
5... Nb4
{ Black's best move but a very difficult one to play without any knowledge. Interesting that both Carlsen & Nakamura didn't play this move. Perhaps, they should buy my course?! The idea of the ...Nb4 jump is to trade the d5-knight as quickly as possible with ...Nbxd5!   5...Nxe4  is playable but risky, as both  6.Bd3  and  6.Qe2  give White some initiative.   5...Nxd5?  is exactly what White is hoping to see.  6.exd5  Nb4  7.Bc4⩲  , with a clear  edge for White as the b4-knight is a bit stranded and the d4-pawn is also hit. }
6. Nxf6+ { This is the main line. } 6... Qxf6 7. a3
{ A somewhat popular insertion.  7.Nxd4?  is a rather basic fork tactic:  7...Qxd4  8.Qxd4  Nxc2+-+  , oops. }
7... Nc6 8. Bg5 { Played by Mikhail Tal back in 1953! } 8... Qg6
{ This is much better than  8...Qe6  , played by Tal's opponent. } 9. Bd3 d6
{ Black is inviting White to play  10.e5  . } 10. e5 Qe6
{ The queen dance is complete and the e5-pawn is lost.  10...Bf5⩱  is quite strong as well. }
11. O-O dxe5 12. Re1 f6
{ The strong pawn chain g7-d4 is hard to break, giving Black time to finish development.   After  13.Bd2  Qf7  ,  we can castle queenside following ...Be6, but ...Bd6 and ...O-O is also a valid plan, depending on White's setup. Black will slowly convert the extra material. }
