[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "9) Halloween Gambit"]
[Black "Halloween Gambit 4.Nxe5 − 7.Bc4 d5 8.Nxd5 "]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Nxe5
{ Out of many dubious gambits, Halloween Gambit is a tough one to face for club players, as White gets quick initiative with a big center. Surprisingly, in the lichess database, White scored 52% @@StartBracket@@!@@EndBracket@@ with  4.Nxe5  . It's exactly the same percentage as the main theoretical move  4.d4  .  The modern name 'Halloween Gambit' was given by the German player Steffen Jakob, who explained that "Many players are shocked the way they would be frightened by a Halloween mask when they are mentally prepared for a boring Four Knights, and then they are faced with Nxe5."  However, in this chapter, I will show you an amazing idea for Black that returns some material back to get a big initiative. White will not stand a chance once you learn the key move! }
4... Nxe5 5. d4
{ White gains a tempo on the knight and builds a strong pawn center. Accuracy is required from Black. }
5... Ng6
{ The best square for the knight.  5...Nc6?!  loses more time after  6.d5  Ne5  7.f4!  , when White continues rolling the pawns.  7...Ng6  8.e5  and White has clear compensation. }
6. e5 { Pushing Black's other knight to its initial square. } 6... Ng8
{ Sometimes we need to retreat in order to attack!  6...Bb4  7.exf6  Qxf6  8.Qe2+  Kd8  9.Be3⩲  is not quite enough for Black. }
7. Bc4
{ All of White's moves are very simple. However, here we have a powerful idea to give up the d-pawn to fight for the initiative. }
7... d5
{ The key move to remember! Black happily gives up the d-pawn for development and still maintains the material advantage. Now the c8-bishop can enter the game.   7...c6!?  is not a bad idea either, but requires accuracy and is more complicated than ...d5. For example  8.Qf3  f6?  is a knee-jerk reaction, but allows White a big attack.  @@StartBracket@@  8...d5!∓  has to be played!@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp1p2pp/2p2pn1/4P3/2BP4/2N2Q2/PPP2PPP/R1B1K2R w KQkq - 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9.O-O  d5  10.exd6  Bxd6  11.Ne4  N8e7??  This line leads to total disaster for Black after  @@StartBracket@@  11...Qc7!  @@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/pp2n1pp/2pb1pn1/8/2BPN3/5Q2/PPP2PPP/R1B2RK1 w kq - 2 12@@EndFEN@@  12.Qxf6!  gxf6  13.Nxf6+  Kf8  14.Bh6#  , with mate on the board!   7...Bb4  is a natural move, but it allows White a strong attack after  8.Qf3  Qe7  @@StartBracket@@  8...d5!  is still the best move even here!@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@r1b1k1nr/ppppqppp/6n1/4P3/1bBP4/2N2Q2/PPP2PPP/R1B1K2R w KQkq - 5 9@@EndFEN@@  9.h4!  ,  with the idea of h5 and a strong attack coming. }
8. Nxd5 Be6 9. Ne3 Bxc4 10. Nxc4 Qd5
{ Black is about to castle long and has no problems. } *

