[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "10) Cochrane Gambit"]
[Black "Cochrane Gambit 4.Nxf7 Kxf7 5.Nc3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nxe5 d6 4. Nxf7
{ White gives up the knight for the pawn to draw Black's king out. This gambit was invented by Scottish chess master John Cochrane. It was played a few times by creative GMs such as Morozevich, Nigel Short, and Topalov. Even Magnus Carlsen tried it once in a blitz game but lost. Black should be able to repel White's attack with accurate play and get an edge. }
4... Kxf7 5. Nc3
{ This is probably more accurate than  5.d4  ,  with the idea of Bc4+ next. }
5... c5
{ An interesting idea played by a former World Champ, Vladimir Kramnik. Black controls d4, making it harder for White to seize the center. }
6. Bc4+ Be6
{ 6...d5?!  is not as good since White can take  on d5 with the knight:  7.Nxd5  . }
7. Bxe6+ Kxe6
{ Black's king is a bit exposed, but at the moment White is lacking development to cause trouble. }
8. O-O Nc6 { Now the d4-square is firmly in Black's hands. } 9. f4 h5
{ A clever way to get the h8-rook involved in the game. We also obtain g4 as a landing spot for the knight. }
10. f5+ Kd7
{ I like the king going to the queenside. but there's nothing wrong with ...Kf7. }
11. d3 Kc7 { Black's king is now safe, and we will convert the extra piece. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "10) Cochrane Gambit"]
[Black "Cochrane Gambit 4.Nxf7 Kxf7 5.Nc3 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nxe5 d6 4. Nxf7
{ White gives up the knight for the pawn to draw Black's king out. This gambit was invented by Scottish chess master John Cochrane. It was played a few times by creative GMs such as Morozevich, Nigel Short, and Topalov. Even Magnus Carlsen tried it once in a blitz game but lost. Black should be able to repel White's attack with accurate play and get an edge. }
4... Kxf7 5. Nc3
{ This is probably more accurate than  5.d4  ,  with the idea of Bc4+ next. }
5... c5
{ An interesting idea played by a former World Champ, Vladimir Kramnik. Black controls d4, making it harder for White to seize the center. }
6. Bc4+ Be6
{ 6...d5?!  is not as good since White can take  on d5 with the knight:  7.Nxd5  . }
7. Bxe6+ Kxe6
{ Black's king is a bit exposed, but at the moment White is lacking development to cause trouble. }
8. d4 { The best try, as White needs to act quickly. } 8... Kf7
{ Black doesn't care about the c5-pawn and safeguards the king. } 9. dxc5 Nc6
{ This position occurred in the high-level GM game Topalov-Kramnik, Linares 1999. Black is a bit better, but White is close to equalizing. }
10. cxd6 { The endgame favors Black. } 10... Qxd6 11. Qxd6 Bxd6
{ Here, active pieces should be better than 3 pawns. } 12. f4 Nxe4 13. Nxe4
Rhe8 { Black wins due to the pin.  13...Rae8  also wins. } *

