{ This position occurred in the high-level GM game Topalov-Kramnik, Linares 1999. Black is a bit better, but White is close to equalizing. }
10. Qe2 { Topalov's choice. } 10... Qd7
{ A nice idea from Kramnik to meet Qc4+ with ...Qe6. } 11. O-O
{ The best try. } 11... Re8
{ Black has many good options, but I like this simple move to activate the rook. }
12. cxd6 Qxd6
{ A strong novelty!  12...Bxd6  13.f4  Bc5+  14.Kh1⇆  gives White counterplay due to the  strong f4 & e4-pawns. }
13. f4
{ A logical move, but it loses to tactics!  13.Bg5!  is probably White's best. The game may continue  13...Nd4  14.Qc4+  Ne6!  15.Bxf6  gxf6  16.Qb5  Nc5  17.Rad1  Qc6⩱  , where White has some compensation for the piece, but I prefer Black. }
13... Nxe4 14. Nxe4 Qd4+
{ The point! It's now clear why we took on d6 with the queen. White is losing the knight. }
15. Kh1 Qxe4 16. Qxe4 Rxe4 { With a won endgame for Black. } *

