1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nxe5 d6 4. Nxf7
{ White gives up the knight for the pawn to draw Black's king out. This gambit was invented by Scottish chess master John Cochrane. It was played a few times by creative GMs such as Morozevich, Nigel Short, and Topalov. Even Magnus Carlsen tried it once in a blitz game but lost. Black should be able to repel White's attack with accurate play and get an edge. }
4... Kxf7 5. d4
{ This is the main line. White gets the center and plans to build up their attack. }
5... c5 { Black undermines White's center with a pawn sacrifice! } 6. Nc3
{ Played by Magnus Carlsen in a blitz game vs. Chinese GM Yu Yangyi in 2019. }
6... cxd4 7. Bc4+ d5
{ A strong novelty, not seen at GM level!  7...Ke8  8.Qxd4  Nc6⩱  and Magnus eventually lost in Carlsen-Yu Yangyi, Saint Louis 2019. }
8. Nxd5 Be6 { Black pins the d5-knight and develops the bishop. } 9. O-O Bxd5
10. exd5 Bd6
{ An instructive idea that is common for this gambit. Black shuts off the c4-bishop and gets ready to castle-by-hand with ...Re8 and ...Kg8 next. }
11. Qxd4 Re8 12. Bg5 Nbd7 13. Rae1 Qb6
{ Trades are good for us! Black is close to winning, as White can't generate any threats. The game may continue with  14.Qh4  Rxe1  15.Rxe1  Qxb2  , so why not grab a pawn?  16.Re6  Qa1+  17.Bf1  Bc5-+  and White doesn't have any threats, while Black should win with an extra piece. }
