[White "10) Cochrane Gambit"]
[Black "Cochrane Gambit 4.Nxf7 Kxf7 5.d4 #5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nxe5 d6 4. Nxf7
{ White gives up the knight for the pawn to draw Black's king out. This gambit was invented by Scottish chess master John Cochrane. It was played a few times by creative GMs such as Morozevich, Nigel Short, and Topalov. Even Magnus Carlsen tried it once in a blitz game but lost. Black should be able to repel White's attack with accurate play and get an edge. }
4... Kxf7 5. d4
{ This is the main line. White gets the center and plans to build up their attack. }
5... c5 { Black undermines White's center with a pawn sacrifice! } 6. dxc5
{ This is the most common response. White wins the pawn but loses vital time to develop. }
6... d5
{ The key move! Black wants to destroy White's last remaining center pawn. The key is rapid piece development! }
7. e5
{ A logical response, White moves forward to attack the knight.  7.exd5  Bxc5  leads to a winning edge for Black. White's king is just too weak. }
7... Ne4
{ A nice centralization; it's not easy for White to get rid of the strong knight. }
8. Qf3+ Ke8
{ The only square for Black's king that keeps the winning edge!   8...Kg8??  allows a pretty checkmate:  9.Qxe4!  dxe4  10.Bc4+  Be6  11.Bxe6#  , oops. And if @@StartFEN@@rnbq1b1r/pp3kpp/8/2PpP3/4n3/5Q2/PPP2PPP/RNB1KB1R b KQ - 2 8@@EndFEN@@  8...Ke6?  9.Nd2  , with a strong attack for White, as Black's king is too exposed here. }
9. Nc3 { White wants to trade off the monster knight. } 9... Bxc5
{ Black continues to develop and happily sacs a pawn in the process. } 10. Nxe4
dxe4 11. Qxe4
{ White may claim material balance having gained 3 pawns for the piece... }
11... Qb6
{ The natural  11...Nc6  is also winning. Black uses a tempo move to hit White's weak pawn on f2. Surprisingly, despite the material balance, White is almost lost here with the engine showing close to -3 edge for Black! The extra minor piece and Black's activity are way more important.   Here are some possible lines:  12.Be3  Bxe3  13.fxe3  Qxb2-+  , @@StartFEN@@rnb1k2r/pp4pp/1q6/2b1P3/4Q3/8/PPP2PPP/R1B1KB1R w KQ - 1 12@@EndFEN@@  12.f4  Bf2+  13.Kd1  Rf8  14.Bd3  Bg4+  15.Kd2  Nc6-+  , @@StartFEN@@rnb1k2r/pp4pp/1q6/2b1P3/4Q3/8/PPP2PPP/R1B1KB1R w KQ - 1 12@@EndFEN@@  12.Bc4  Bxf2+  13.Ke2  Qd4  14.Qxd4  Bxd4-+  , with a winning endgame for Black.   Conclusion: The Cochrane Gambit is somewhat dangerous, but only if Black is too greedy. The key idea is to destroy White’s center and go for rapid development, sometimes giving up more pawns in the process. Remember, a minor piece is worth more than a few pawns, especially if you can get your pieces out faster! Don’t be afraid of leaving your king in the middle of the board, as long as it's shielded by White’s e5-pawn, as your pieces can then develop quickly. }
