[White "11) Stafford Gambit"]
[Black "Stafford Gambit 3...Nc6 4.Nxc6 dxc6 5.Nc3 Bc5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6
{ The Petroff Defense is the most common way Black tries to achieve the Stafford Gambit. However, we can also transpose via a different move order if Black plays  2...Nc6  and White tries the Scotch Four Knights  3.Nc3  and now  3...Bc5  . Black willingly falls for a known trap.  4.Nxe5!  Nf6  is the invitation to the Stafford  @@StartBracket@@  4...Nxe5  5.d4!  is a known trap that allows White to get a small edge after winning back the piece@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/pppp1ppp/2n2n2/2b1N3/4P3/2N5/PPPP1PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Nxc6  dxc6  transposes to our main line. }
3. Nxe5 Nc6
{ Black offers the trade of knights and chooses to play down a pawn. } 4. Nxc6
dxc6 5. Nc3
{ I recommend this simple developing move since we can get into this position via the Four Knights Scotch move order. There's nothing wrong with  5.d3  as well and I give it as an alternative.   5.e5  was played in the original game Lowens-Stafford, 1950. While not a bad move, it resulted in a nice miniature after a horrible blunder by White and gave this Gambit its tricky reputation.  5...Ne4  6.d3??  Don't do this at home kids! Black now wins by force. @@StartBracket@@After  6.d4!  Qh4  7.Qf3±  , White is clearly better here, as Black is running out of tricks.@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/ppp2ppp/2p5/4P3/4n3/3P4/PPP2PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Bc5  and White resigned, as they are about to lose a queen after  7.dxe4  Bxf2+!  8.Ke2  Bg4+-+  . }
5... Bc5
{ We've reached the main position of the Stafford Gambit. The biggest advocate for this opening is the famous streamer IM Eric Rosen, who inspired legions of amateurs and GMs to take it up in blitz. However, someone has to put the hammer down and refute this gambit once and for all! Welcome to my course. :@@EndBracket@@  In the lichess DB, this position occurred about 1.7 million times, and Black scores an incredible 56% @@StartBracket@@!@@EndBracket@@. So, we have to take this move seriously. I will show you a simple idea based on the concept of Prophylaxis that stops Black's attack in its tracks and gives White a big edge. }
6. h3
{ This little pawn move goes a long way. I recommend that you remember the key idea: White wants to stop Black from playing ...Ng4 or ...Bg4.   ➢  6.Be2?  allows Black to execute the main idea:  6...Qd4!  7.O-O  h5!?  @@StartBracket@@  7...Nxe4=  @@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@r1b1k2r/ppp2pp1/2p2n2/2b4p/3qP3/2N5/PPPPBPPP/R1BQ1RK1 w kq h6 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8.h3?  @@StartBracket@@  8.d3!  @@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@r1b1k2r/ppp2pp1/2p2n2/2b4p/3qP3/2N4P/PPPPBPP1/R1BQ1RK1 b kq - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8...Ng4!  9.hxg4  hxg4  , Black's rook and bishop control the key file and diagonal, and White's king is helpless against the massive attack.  For example  10.g3  @@StartBracket@@  10.Bxg4  Qe5-+  @@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@r1b1k2r/ppp2pp1/2p5/2b5/3qP1p1/2N3P1/PPPPBP2/R1BQ1RK1 b kq - 0 10@@EndFEN@@  10...Qe5  11.Kg2  Bxf2!!  A wonderful sacrifice!  12.Rxf2  @@StartBracket@@After  12.Kxf2  Rh2+  13.Ke3  Qxg3+  14.Kd4  Be6-+  ,  Black will activate the a8-rook and White is just lost.@@EndBracket@@  @@StartFEN@@r1b1k2r/ppp2pp1/2p5/4q3/4P1p1/2N3P1/PPPPBRK1/R1BQ4 b kq - 0 12@@EndFEN@@  12...Qh5  , with unstoppable threats on the h-file.   ➢  6.d3?  allows Black's main idea  6...Ng4!∓  , with a big attack. }
6... Qd4
{ Black is playing for one-move tricks, but White is able to defend the f2-pawn quite easily. }
7. Qf3
{ The most natural square for White's queen, we don't want to block the f1-bishop. }
7... Be6
{ Black's attack is stopped, and they are trying to castle long to finish development. }
8. d3 { White also plans to castle long. } 8... O-O-O 9. Be3
{ Let's chase the queen away.  9.a3!  is also strong. } 9... Qb4 10. O-O-O
{ 10.Bxc5?  Qxb2-+  , but after @@StartFEN@@2kr3r/ppp2ppp/2p1bn2/2b5/1q2P3/2NPBQ1P/PPP2PP1/R3KB1R w KQ - 3 10@@EndFEN@@  10.O-O-O  , White's king is quite safe on the queenside and here we can see that Black doesn't have any compensation for the pawn. For example  10...Bxe3+  11.Qxe3  Kb8  12.a3  Qa5  13.Be2  . White has finally finished development and has a winning edge.  After all, you can't just give up a central pawn in chess for nothing! }
