{ This little pawn move goes a long way. I recommend that you remember the key idea: White wants to stop Black from playing ...Ng4 or ...Bg4.   ➢  6.Be2?  allows Black to execute the main idea:  6...Qd4!  7.O-O  h5!?  @@StartBracket@@  7...Nxe4=  @@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@r1b1k2r/ppp2pp1/2p2n2/2b4p/3qP3/2N5/PPPPBPPP/R1BQ1RK1 w kq h6 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8.h3?  @@StartBracket@@  8.d3!  @@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@r1b1k2r/ppp2pp1/2p2n2/2b4p/3qP3/2N4P/PPPPBPP1/R1BQ1RK1 b kq - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8...Ng4!  9.hxg4  hxg4  , Black's rook and bishop control the key file and diagonal, and White's king is helpless against the massive attack.  For example  10.g3  @@StartBracket@@  10.Bxg4  Qe5-+  @@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@r1b1k2r/ppp2pp1/2p5/2b5/3qP1p1/2N3P1/PPPPBP2/R1BQ1RK1 b kq - 0 10@@EndFEN@@  10...Qe5  11.Kg2  Bxf2!!  A wonderful sacrifice!  12.Rxf2  @@StartBracket@@After  12.Kxf2  Rh2+  13.Ke3  Qxg3+  14.Kd4  Be6-+  ,  Black will activate the a8-rook and White is just lost.@@EndBracket@@  @@StartFEN@@r1b1k2r/ppp2pp1/2p5/4q3/4P1p1/2N3P1/PPPPBRK1/R1BQ4 b kq - 0 12@@EndFEN@@  12...Qh5  , with unstoppable threats on the h-file.   ➢  6.d3?  allows Black's main idea  6...Ng4!∓  , with a big attack. }
