[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "11) Stafford Gambit"]
[Black "Stafford Gambit 3...Nc6 4.Nxc6 dxc6 | Alternative 5.d3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6
{ The Petroff Defense is the most common way Black tries to achieve the Stafford Gambit. However, we can also transpose via a different move order if Black plays  2...Nc6  and White tries the Scotch Four Knights  3.Nc3  and now  3...Bc5  . Black willingly falls for a known trap.  4.Nxe5!  Nf6  is the invitation to the Stafford  @@StartBracket@@  4...Nxe5  5.d4!  is a known trap that allows White to get a small edge after winning back the piece@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/pppp1ppp/2n2n2/2b1N3/4P3/2N5/PPPP1PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Nxc6  dxc6  transposes to our main line. }
3. Nxe5 Nc6
{ Black offers the trade of knights and chooses to play down a pawn. } 4. Nxc6
dxc6 5. d3
{ This is also quite strong with similar ideas as  5.Nc3  .  As long as White remembers to play h3 at the right moment to stop ...Ng4, we will have a nice advantage.   5.e5  was played in the original game Lowens-Stafford, 1950. While not a bad move, it resulted in a nice miniature after a horrible blunder by White and gave this Gambit its tricky reputation.  5...Ne4  6.d3??  Don't do this at home kids! Black now wins by force. @@StartBracket@@After  6.d4!  Qh4  7.Qf3±  , White is clearly better here, as Black is running out of tricks.@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/ppp2ppp/2p5/4P3/4n3/3P4/PPP2PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Bc5  and White resigned as is about to lose a queen after  7.dxe4  Bxf2+!  8.Ke2  Bg4+-+  . }
5... Bc5 6. Be2 { 6.h3  is fine too. } 6... h5 7. h3
{ This is the must-know idea that stops all of Black's counterplay. White takes control over g4. Not  7.O-O?  , as it allows Black's main idea:  7...Ng4!  , with attack. }
7... Qd4 8. O-O { 8.Rf1!?  is also strong. } 8... Qe5 9. c3
{ Given the big threat of d4, Black is facing serious issues. Not  9.Nd2?  as played by GM Gata Kamsky in a blitz game.  9...Qg3!  and Black's attack is too strong.  Now ...Bxh3 is a huge threat! }
9... Ng4 { A last-ditch effort to confuse White. } 10. Bxg4
{ 10.hxg4??  results in White getting mated in 4 moves!  10...hxg4  and White is dead. }
10... Bxg4 11. Qc2
{ The simplest. Please note that other queen moves are fine as well. } 11...
Bb6 12. d4 Qe7 13. hxg4
{ Now that the dark-squared bishop's diagonal is blocked, we can just take the piece. }
13... hxg4 14. Rd1 Qh4 15. Kf1
{ White's monarch is super-safe on e2 and it's just a matter of time for White to develop the bishop and knight and convert the extra piece. }
