[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "12) Philidor Countergambit"]
[Black "Philidor Countergambit 3...f5 4.Bc4 fxe4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 d6
{ This is the Philidor opening, a rare guest at tournament practice due to its passive nature. }
3. d4 f5
{ A dubious gambit, invented by famous French 18th-century player François-André Danican Philidor. He famously said, "Pawns are the Soul of chess." }
4. Bc4
{ A rare move, seen only in a few GM games! But I believe Black is facing serious issues due to the weak a2-g8 diagonal. }
4... fxe4 { The 2nd most played move allows a thematic tactic. } 5. Nxe5
{ Black is more or less lost after this. } 5... dxe5 6. Qh5+
{ The point! This is a famous tactic seen from many openings where the f7-pawn is missing. }
6... Kd7
{ The king goes for a walk. At this point, White is winning pretty much with any normal move, but let me show you this line.  6...g6  7.Qxe5+  wins the h8-rook. }
7. Qf5+ Kc6 { 7...Ke8  8.Qf7# } 8. Qxe5 a6
{ Black tries to stay alive, but it's too late already.  8...Bd6  9.Qb5#  , while @@StartFEN@@rnbq1bnr/ppp3pp/2k5/4Q3/2BPp3/8/PPP2PPP/RNB1K2R b KQ - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8...Nf6  allows mate in 4:  9.Qb5+  Kd6  10.Bf4+  Ke7  11.Qe5+  Be6  12.Qxe6#  . }
9. d5+ { The only move that wins! } 9... Kb6 { 9...Kd7  10.Qe6# } 10. Be3+ Bc5
11. Bxc5+ Kxc5 12. b4+ { What a fun position to play as White! } 12... Kxb4
{ After  12...Kxc4  , Black gets mated even faster:  13.Qxe4+  Kb5  14.Nc3+  Kb6  15.Qd4+  c5  16.Qxc5#  . }
13. Qd4 { This quiet move is the most precise. Now, checkmate is unstoppable. }
13... Nc6 14. c3+ Ka5 15. Qc5+ b5 16. a4
{ A great way to involve the a1-rook in the attack, as axb5 would be mate. }
16... Qd6 17. axb5# *

