[Black "Philidor Countergambit 3...f5 4.Bc4 exd4 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 d6
{ This is the Philidor opening, a rare guest at tournament practice due to its passive nature. }
3. d4 f5
{ A dubious gambit, invented by famous French 18th-century player François-André Danican Philidor. He famously said, 'Pawns are the Soul of chess.' }
4. Bc4
{ A rare move, seen only in a few GM games! But I believe Black is facing serious issues due to the weak a2-g8 diagonal. }
4... exd4 { The most common move in the database. } 5. O-O
{ A simple move and Black's position is completely hopeless! White's rook enters the game. Let's look at some possible lines. }
5... Nc6 6. exf5
{ White opens the e-file and it's all over for Black's king.  6.Re1!  is also quite strong. }
6... Bxf5 7. Re1+ Nge7
{ 7...Be7  8.Nxd4  Nxd4  9.Qxd4  Nf6  10.Bg5  Kf8  11.Nc3+-  , with a crushing attack. }
8. Nxd4 Nxd4 9. Qxd4 Qd7 { Trying to castle queenside, but it's not easy. } 10.
Bg5 { Black can't even castle queenside since the a7-pawn hangs. } 10... c5 11.
Qf4 O-O-O
{ Black finally castled in this game, but the position is still lost. Just look at the kingside. }
12. Nc3
{ White completes development and enjoys a winning edge. The game won't last long.   Conclusion: The Philidor Countergambit has not withstood the test of time. The simple way to refute it is with active development: @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp3pp/3p4/4pp2/3PP3/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq f6 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Bc4!  and @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp3pp/3p4/5p2/2BpP3/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R w KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5.O-O!  White gets a quick edge in development and never looks back. The lines are easy to learn, and you’ll have a lot of fun attacking the enemy king! }
*

