1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 f5
{ This dubious gambit is also known as Greco's Countergambit. It was analyzed as far back as the 1600s by the Italian player Gioachino Greco @@StartBracket@@1600-1634@@EndBracket@@. In the early 1900s, Latvian players started playing it, and the name stuck!  These days it's a rare guest in tournament practice, but you can still see it in blitz games among top players. White should get an edge with the best moves, but you have to be tactically aware, as the game opens up quickly. Even the great Bobby Fischer lost to this opening back in 1955 when he was only 12 years old. }
3. Nxe5 { White should take the central pawn! } 3... Nf6 4. Bc4
{ White doesn't care about the e4-pawn and points out the biggest weakness in Black's camp: the f7-square. }
4... Qe7 5. d4 { White takes over the center and protects the knight. } 5... d6
6. Nf7 { The knight is quite safe on f7, but the rook has to move. } 6... d5 7.
Nxh8 dxc4 8. Nc3 fxe4 9. Bg5 Bf5 10. Nd5 { This is winning for White. } *

