1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 f5
{ This dubious gambit is also known as Greco's Countergambit. It was analyzed as far back as the 1600s by the Italian player Gioachino Greco @@StartBracket@@1600-1634@@EndBracket@@. In the early 1900s, Latvian players started playing it, and the name stuck!  These days it's a rare guest in tournament practice, but you can still see it in blitz games among top players. White should get an edge with the best moves, but you have to be tactically aware, as the game opens up quickly. Even the great Bobby Fischer lost to this opening back in 1955 when he was only 12 years old. }
3. Nxe5 { White should take the central pawn! } 3... Qf6
{ The most common move. Black tries to dislodge the knight, but the queen is now too exposed on f6. }
4. d4
{ Simple chess. White takes more central control and protects the knight. }
4... d6 { Black has to insert this first and then take the e4-pawn. } 5. Nc4
{ 5.Nd3!?  is also interesting and quite good. } 5... fxe4 6. Nc3
{ Black managed to win back the pawn but at a significant loss in development. Remember, the queen on f6 doesn't count as a developed piece! }
6... Qg6
{ Black protects e2, keeps an eye on the g2-pawn, and gets ready to develop the knight to f6. However, it's another tempo loss in the opening! }
7. f3
{ White can get an edge with pretty much any developing move, but I like the idea of opening up the game! }
7... exf3 { 7...Be7?  simply drops a pawn after  8.Nxe4  d5  9.Ne5!+-  . } 8.
Qxf3 { The game has opened up more and White's pieces are better developed. }
8... Nf6 9. Ne3
{ A nice regrouping, taking the g4-square under control to stop ...Bg4.  9.Bd3±  is natural and strong as well. }
9... Nc6 10. Bd3 Qf7 11. Bc4
{ White keeps attacking the queen, improving our bishop. } 11... Qg6 12. Ned5
{ White points out that c7 is now quite weak. } 12... Bg4 13. Qe3+ Kd7 14. O-O
{ White's king is much safer now, with a winning edge. For example  14...Re8  15.Qf2  Nxd5  16.Nxd5  Kc8  17.Ne3  Bh5  18.Qh4  Be7  19.Qh3+  Kb8  20.Bd3  Qh6  21.Nf5+-  is crushing. }
*

