4... d6 { Black has to insert this first and then take the e4-pawn. } 5. Nc4
{ 5.Nd3!?  is also interesting and quite good. } 5... fxe4 6. Nc3
{ Black managed to win back the pawn but at a significant loss in development. Remember, the queen on f6 doesn't count as a developed piece! }
6... Qg6
{ Black protects e2, keeps an eye on the g2-pawn, and gets ready to develop the knight to f6. However, it's another tempo loss in the opening! }
7. f3
{ White can get an edge with pretty much any developing move, but I like the idea of opening up the game! }
7... exf3 { 7...Be7?  simply drops a pawn after  8.Nxe4  d5  9.Ne5!+-  . } 8.
Qxf3 { The game has opened up more and White's pieces are better developed. }
8... Nc6 9. Nb5
{ An excellent jump with the knight. White attacks c7 and protects d4. } 9...
Bg4 { Black inserts a tempo on the queen. } 10. Qc3
{ Anticipating Black's long castle in order to x-ray the king on c8. } 10...
Rc8 { In my database of 13 games, White won 12 and drew one! } 11. d5
{ The key move. Black is falling apart now. } 11... Nce7
{ 11...Ne5  12.Nxa7  Ra8  13.Nb5+-  , White stole a pawn and continues the attack. }
12. Ne3
{ A strong move. White protects the d5-pawn, making it hard for Black to develop. }
12... Nf6 13. Bd3 { White develops with tempo, hitting the queen. } 13... Qh5
14. Nxg4 { The simplest, but many moves win here. } 14... Qxg4 15. Nxc7+
{ The concrete approach.  15.O-O  is good too. } 15... Kd8
{ 15...Kd7  16.Bb5+  Kd8  17.Ne6++-  wins material, as Black has to give up the queen. }
16. Ne6+ Kd7 17. Qb3 { White targets b7, with a winning attack. } 17... Nfxd5
{ 17...Qxg2  18.Qxb7+  Ke8  19.Rf1+- } 18. Ng5
{ It's important to save the knight first. } 18... Qb4+ 19. Bd2 Qxb3 20. axb3
{ With threats such as Nf7 & Bxh7 and Rxa7, White has a winning endgame.   Conclusion: The Latvian Gambit is more of a surprise weapon than a real opening. White should take the e5-pawn and develop rapidly, not caring about losing their e4-pawn. Remember, active play and rapid development are key here. The tactical complications starting with @@StartFEN@@r1b1kbnr/ppp3pp/2np2q1/8/2NP4/2N2Q2/PPP3PP/R1B1KB1R w KQkq - 1 9@@EndFEN@@  9.Nb5!  favor White, and if you remember this key idea, then you may get a winning position in less than 20 moves! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "14) Elephant Gambit"]
[Black "Elephant Gambit 2...d5 3.Nxe5 Bd6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 d5
{ This is the so-called Elephant Gambit. The origin of the name is unclear but perhaps both Black's central pawns represent the tusks of the elephant, thus the name. It is definitely a dubious gambit, but often club players are overwhelmed by White's choices:  Do we take on d5? Do we take on e5? Do we ignore the pawns and develop? }
3. Nxe5
{ I recommend this principled approach. White grabs the central pawn with the knight and asks Black a question: why did you give up the pawn? }
3... Bd6
{ This move is more common on master level, but with accurate play, White should still get a comfortable advantage. }
4. d4
{ A nice central pawn move. We protect the knight on e5 and get ready to develop the c1-bishop. Notice we don't care about losing the e4-pawn since we just snacked on the e5-pawn earlier. }
4... dxe4
{ Black wins the central pawn back, but we get a new tempo to develop. } 5. Bc4
{ Pointing out the classic weakness in e4-e5 openings: the f7-pawn. } 5... Bxe5
{ Forced. } 6. Qh5
{ A must-know move! White creates a double threat of checkmate on f7 and hits the e5-bishop.   6.dxe5?  loses all the edge and White can even be worse after  6...Qxd1+  7.Kxd1  Nc6  , with a pleasant endgame for Black. }
6... Qe7 { Black protects f7 and gets ready to trade on e5. } 7. Qxe5
{ The most precise, White doesn't mind the endgame. } 7... Qxe5 8. dxe5
{ We've reached the critical position of this line. White's bishop pair should give us a long-term edge due to the open nature of the position and there are no clear outposts for Black's knights. }
8... Nc6
{ The most natural move, Black develops and hits our e5-pawn. Do we defend it or not? }
9. Nc3
{ Remember, when you're leading in development, the initiative is above all! White attacks the e4-pawn but most importantly develops. }
9... Nxe5 10. Bb3 { Easy does it. We get our bishop into safety first. } 10...
Nf6 11. Bf4 { An annoying x-ray on the c7-pawn. } 11... Nc6
{ 11...Ng6  is better than the text, but it won't change the reputation of this gambit. After  12.Bxc7  O-O  13.O-O-O+-  followed by Rhe1, Black will have a hard time fighting our bishop pair and defending the pawn on e4 as well. }
12. Nb5
{ This move is just crushing Black! There's no way to stop Nxc7 next.   12.Bxc7  is not bad and was played in a blitz game by top American junior Sam Sevian  12...O-O  13.O-O-O⩲  , with a pleasant edge for White due to the bishop pair. Sevian-Gadimbayli, chess.com 2020. }
12... O-O 13. Nxc7 Rb8 14. Nd5
{ A nice centralization, hitting the b8-rook as well. } 14... Ra8
{ 14...Nxd5  15.Bxb8  Be6  16.O-O-O+-  and Black is just down an exchange for nothing. }
15. Nxf6+ gxf6 16. O-O-O
{ White has an overwhelming advantage in this endgame. Two bishops and clear targets in Black's camp make this position easy to play.   Conclusion: The Elephant Gambit and specifically the @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/8/3pN3/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Bd6!?  line is somewhat playable, but as you can see, White can force an endgame with a big edge that is very uncomfortable for Black. It's important to remember the intermezzo idea @@StartFEN@@rnbqk1nr/ppp2ppp/8/4b3/2BPp3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R w KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Qh5! }
*

