1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 d5
{ This is the so-called Elephant Gambit. The origin of the name is unclear but perhaps both Black's central pawns represent the tusks of the elephant, thus the name. It is definitely a dubious gambit, but often club players are overwhelmed by White's choices:  Do we take on d5? Do we take on e5? Do we ignore the pawns and develop? }
3. Nxe5
{ I recommend this principled approach. White grabs the central pawn with the knight and asks Black a question: why did you give up the pawn? }
3... dxe4
{ This is more common at lower levels, as Black simply takes back the pawn. }
4. Bc4 Be6 { A very common move in the lichess DB, but it's just bad. } 5. Bxe6
fxe6 6. Qh5+ { Black's monarch is too exposed to tactics. } 6... g6 7. Nxg6
{ The key tactic. Now you can see that Black will lose the h8-rook due to the pin. }
7... hxg6 { 7...Nf6  8.Qh3+-  and Black has too many weaknesses. } 8. Qxh8
{ With a winning material advantage for White. } *

