[Round "?"]
[White "14) Elephant Gambit"]
[Black "Elephant Gambit 2...d5 3.Nxe5 dxe4 #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 d5
{ This is the so-called Elephant Gambit. The origin of the name is unclear but perhaps both Black's central pawns represent the tusks of the elephant, thus the name. It is definitely a dubious gambit, but often club players are overwhelmed by White's choices:  Do we take on d5? Do we take on e5? Do we ignore the pawns and develop? }
3. Nxe5
{ I recommend this principled approach. White grabs the central pawn with the knight and asks Black a question: why did you give up the pawn? }
3... dxe4
{ This is more common at lower levels, as Black simply takes back the pawn. }
4. Bc4 Qg5
{ The tricky Wasp Variation! Of course, it's completely unsound, but again, White has to be accurate. }
5. Bxf7+ { 5.d4  Qxg2  6.Bxf7+  transposes. } 5... Ke7 6. d4
{ A nice tempo move! White protects the knight and attacks the queen. } 6...
Qxg2 7. Rf1 { The rook is now safe and White already has a big edge. } 7... Nc6
8. Bc4
{ White gets the bishop out of danger, as Black had the threat of ...Nxe5 and ...Kxf7, and overprotects the f1-rook. }
8... Nf6 9. Nc3 Bh3 10. Bf4
{ Now we just develop, as the rook is well-protected. } 10... Rd8 11. Nxc6+
bxc6 12. Qd2 { White is getting ready to castle long. } 12... Qg4 13. Rh1
{ Saving our rook. } 13... Kd7 14. Ne2
{ It's important to block the enemy's queen control of the d1-square so we can castle next. }
14... Qh5 15. O-O-O
{ White finally finished development and has a winning edge. Black's king is just too open with a terrible structure. }
