1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 d5
{ This is the so-called Elephant Gambit. The origin of the name is unclear but perhaps both Black's central pawns represent the tusks of the elephant, thus the name. It is definitely a dubious gambit, but often club players are overwhelmed by White's choices:  Do we take on d5? Do we take on e5? Do we ignore the pawns and develop? }
3. Nxe5
{ I recommend this principled approach. White grabs the central pawn with the knight and asks Black a question: why did you give up the pawn? }
3... dxe4
{ This is more common at lower levels, as Black simply takes back the pawn. }
4. Bc4 Qg5
{ The tricky Wasp Variation! Of course, it's completely unsound, but again, White has to be accurate. }
5. Bxf7+ { 5.d4  Qxg2  6.Bxf7+  transposes. } 5... Ke7 6. d4
{ A nice tempo move! White protects the knight and attacks the queen. } 6...
Qxg2 7. Rf1 { The rook is now safe and White already has a big edge. } 7... Bh3
{ The most common move, Black develops a bishop and attacks the f1-rook. } 8.
Bc4
{ An important defensive idea you must know! The bishop overprotects the f1-rook. }
8... Nf6 { 8...Qxh2  9.Bg5+  Nf6  10.Qh5+- } 9. Bf4 Nbd7
{ 9...Nc6  10.Nc3  transposes to the 7...Nc6 move order. } 10. Nc3
{ White continues with natural development. We want to play Qd2 and castle long here. }
10... Nb6 11. Be2 Nbd5 12. Nxd5+ Nxd5 13. Qd2
{ The simplest, but  13.Bg3  is fine as well. } 13... Nxf4 14. Qxf4
{ White is totally winning due to Black's terrible king and poor development. We are about to castle long and have all the fun!   Conclusion: The Elephant Gambit and specifically the @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/8/3pN3/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Bd6!?  line is somewhat playable, but as you can see, White can force an endgame with a big edge that is very uncomfortable for Black. It's important to remember the intermezzo idea @@StartFEN@@rnbqk1nr/ppp2ppp/8/4b3/2BPp3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R w KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Qh5!   The Wasp Variation is a bit tricky to navigate, but once you learn the key ideas such as @@StartFEN@@rn3bnr/ppp1kBpp/8/4N3/3Pp3/7b/PPP2PqP/RNBQKR2 w Q - 2 8@@EndFEN@@  8.Bc4!  , you then take the sting out of Black's threats and will get a winning position once you castle queenside. }
