[White "14) Elephant Gambit"]
[Black "Elephant Gambit 2...d5 | Alternative 3.exd5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 d5
{ This is the so-called Elephant Gambit. The origin of the name is unclear but perhaps both Black's central pawns represent the tusks of the elephant, thus the name. It is definitely a dubious gambit, but often club players are overwhelmed by White's choices:  Do we take on d5? Do we take on e5? Do we ignore the pawns and develop? }
3. exd5 { This is perfectly playable as well. } 3... e4
{ 3...Bd6!?  4.d4!  e4  5.Ne5!±  should give White an edge, while @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/8/3Pp3/8/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Qxd5  4.Nc3  guarantees an improved Scandinavian due to  the useless pawn on e5 and our lead in development. }
4. Qe2 { The key move. } 4... Nf6 5. Nc3 Be7
{ Black gives up the e-pawn for rapid development. } 6. Nxe4 O-O
{ Here you can see that Black is first to castle, that's why White has to be a bit careful. }
7. Nxf6+ Bxf6 8. d4 { It's important to meet ...Re8 with Be3! } 8... Qxd5 9.
Be3
{ White is better here, as we would play Qc4 or Qb5 and castle queenside. Black still has to prove that there's enough compensation for the pawn. }
