[White "15) Danish Gambit"]
[Black "Danish Gambit 3.c3 d5 4.exd5 Nf6 5.c4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. d4 exd4 3. c3
{ The Danish Gambit. A tricky opening to face if you are a pawn grabber, but I will show you a simple concept that is easy to play right away as Black! }
3... d5
{ Black doesn't waste any time on grabbing pawns and strikes in the center right away! It's also an unpleasant surprise for your opponent, who may be less familiar with this move.   In the big lichess database we see  3...dxc3  in over 8 million games and White scores a nice 56%.  3...d5!  is only seen in about 700,  000  games, but scores an abysmal 45% for White. Let's make statistics work for you!  3...dxc3  is fine, but you have to be prepared both for  4.Nxc3  and  4.Bc4  cxb2  5.Bxb2  with compensation. }
4. exd5 { White's most common move by far. } 4... Nf6
{ I recommend this rare move, played only in 126 games in the Chessbase DB @@StartBracket@@compare it to  4...Qxd5  with over 1000 games!@@EndBracket@@. Black just develops a piece and wants to recapture  the d5-pawn with the knight. Why bring the queen out early?   White has many moves here, but  5.cxd4  is the most common. In this case, we are happy to play vs. the Isolated Queen's Pawn @@StartBracket@@IQP@@EndBracket@@, which is a long-term weakness in White's camp. }
5. c4
{ It is a tempting option to connect the pawns and protect d5, leaving the d4-pawn weak. However, it's too slow, as White neglects development. }
5... Bb4+ { A nice tempo move! } 6. Bd2 Qe7+
{ Another tempo move and a novelty already! } 7. Be2 Na6
{ Black overprotects the strong b4-bishop and the knight can enter the fight via the c5 or b4-squares. Don't play  7...d3  8.Qa4+  , which spoils Black's advantage and brings White back into the game. }
8. Bxb4 { 8.Nf3?  loses outright to  8...d3!  9.Qa4+  Bd7-+  . } 8... Qxb4+
{ A nice double attack. } 9. Qd2 Ne4 10. Qxb4 Nxb4
{ With a clear edge for Black due to multiple threats. } *

