5. Bb5+ { A decent try by White, trying to develop the bishop with tempo. }
5... Bd7 { The simplest. } 6. Bc4
{ A clever attempt to hold on to the pawn, but White does lose a tempo now.   6.Bxd7+  is inferior since after  6...Qxd7  ,  White will drop the pawn on d5 anyway. Defending it with  7.c4  only deteriorates the position further due to  7...Bb4+  8.Bd2  Bxd2  9.Qxd2  O-O  ,  when Black has a lead in development and ...c5 ideas as well.  10.Qxd4?  spells disaster in view of  10...Nc6  followed by ...Rfe8+. }
6... c6 { Black blows open the center! } 7. dxc6 Bxc6
{ Now the g2-pawn is a clear target. } 8. Nf3 Qe7+
{ An important intermezzo check, making it hard for White to finish development. }
9. Qe2
{ 9.Be2  Bxf3!  10.gxf3  Nc6  11.cxd4  O-O-O∓  , with a clear edge for Black. Just look at White's pawns. }
9... Bxf3 { Black takes the opportunity to ruin White's pawn structure. } 10.
gxf3 Nc6 { Black just develops and is not in a hurry to take on e2 yet. } 11.
Bf4 Nh5 { Asking the bishop where it wants to go next. } 12. Bg5 Qxe2+ 13. Kxe2
Be7 14. Bxe7 Kxe7
{ We've reached an endgame where Black is clearly better due to White's ruined pawn structure. Black will bring the rooks to the center quite soon whereas White is still lagging in development. }
