1. e4 e5 2. d4 exd4 3. c3
{ The Danish Gambit. A tricky opening to face if you are a pawn grabber, but I will show you a simple concept that is easy to play right away as Black! }
3... d5
{ Black doesn't waste any time on grabbing pawns and strikes in the center right away! It's also an unpleasant surprise for your opponent, who may be less familiar with this move.   In the big lichess database we see  3...dxc3  in over 8 million games and White scores a nice 56%.  3...d5!  is only seen in about 700,  000  games, but scores an abysmal 45% for White. Let's make statistics work for you!  3...dxc3  is fine, but you have to be prepared both for  4.Nxc3  and  4.Bc4  cxb2  5.Bxb2  with compensation. }
4. exd5 { White's most common move by far. } 4... Nf6
{ I recommend this rare move, played only in 126 games in the Chessbase DB @@StartBracket@@compare it to  4...Qxd5  with over 1000 games!@@EndBracket@@. Black just develops a piece and wants to recapture  the d5-pawn with the knight. Why bring the queen out early?   White has many moves here, but  5.cxd4  is the most common. In this case, we are happy to play vs. the Isolated Queen's Pawn @@StartBracket@@IQP@@EndBracket@@, which is a long-term weakness in White's camp. }
5. cxd4
{ The most common move, but White is now playing with a long-term weakness, the Isolated Queen's Pawn @@StartBracket@@IQP@@EndBracket@@. }
5... Bb4+ { We can also play  5...Nxd5  right away. } 6. Nc3 Nxd5 7. Bd2 O-O
{ Black is first to castle and we can clearly see that White's opening strategy didn't go well. Here, White can either develop the knight first with  8.Nf3  or the bishop with  8.Bd3  . }
8. Bd3 Nc6 9. Nge2
{ 9.Nf3  allows the annoying check  9...Re8+!  and White either has to lose the right to castle with  10.Kf1  or waste a tempo with  10.Be2  . }
9... Bg4 { Black pins the knight and tries to provoke the weakening move f3. }
10. f3 { 10.O-O?  just loses a pawn to  10...Nxd4  . } 10... Be6
{ A solid square for our bishop. } 11. O-O
{ Both sides have finished development, but White has a weaker pawn structure due to the IQP and a firm blockade by Black's d5-knight. Let me show you a cool regrouping for Black. }
11... Be7
{ The bishop will come to f6 and apply more pressure on the d4-pawn. } 12. a3
{ 12.Ne4  Ndb4!  and White is facing serious issues already. } 12... Bf6
{ We've reached a dream position vs. an IQP. All of Black's pieces are in perfect harmony, while White is struggling with a plan. The d4-pawn is just too weak. }
