[White "16) Vienna Gambit"]
[Black "Vienna Gambit 3.f4 d5 4.fxe5 Nxe4 5.Qf3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. f4
{ The Vienna Gambit is quite a dangerous gambit for Black if we take the pawn. I used to play this gambit for White as a kid and always loved it when Black took on f4 or just defended the pawn with  3...d6  as most club players do.   However, I will show you an idea based on central counterplay:  3...d5!  White players hate facing this countergambit, as Black gets fast central play. Please note that the popular YouTuber IM Levy Rozman a.k.a Gothamchess also loves the Vienna Gambit for White and recommends it in his videos. So, you have to be well-prepared here as Black! }
3... d5
{ The best and most direct approach. Always fight for the center!  3...exf4?  4.e5!  , with a big initiative for White. Also, @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pppp1ppp/5n2/4p3/4PP2/2N5/PPPP2PP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq f3 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3...d6?!  is too passive, and after  4.Nf3  , White gets a nice space advantage. }
4. fxe5 Nxe4 5. Qf3
{ This move pretty much replaced the old theoretical recommendation of  5.Nf3  . GothamChess also recommends this modern approach. White immediately wants to put pressure on  the e4-knight and clarify the situation in the center. }
5... f5
{ This is the key move! While it's only the 3rd most popular move for Black, White scores an abysmal 44% in the lichess DB. The point is to try to hold on to the monster knight on e4.   5...Nxc3  6.bxc3  Be7  is what I faced as White back in the Reykjavik Open 2018 against a strong 2600+, GM Gledura from Hungary. Clearly, Black didn't know the line and quickly got into trouble after  7.d4  c5  8.Bd3  cxd4  9.cxd4  Qa5+?  10.Bd2  Bb4  11.Rd1  Bxd2+  12.Rxd2±  .  White has a big edge and doesn't care about the a2-pawn. I went on to checkmate my opponent. The lesson: Know Thy Theory! }
6. Nh3 Nc6 7. Bb5 Qh4+ { White doesn't have a good way to block the check. } 8.
Kd1 { 8.Nf2  Bc5-+ } 8... Bc5
{ With a big edge for Black. White would be ill-advised to start grabbing material. After  9.Nxd5  O-O  10.Bxc6  @@StartBracket@@definitely not  10.Nxc7?  Nd4-+  @@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@r1b2rk1/ppp3pp/2B5/2bNPp2/4n2q/5Q1N/PPPP2PP/R1BK3R b - - 0 10@@EndFEN@@  10...bxc6  11.Nxc7?  Rb8-+  ,  the knight on c7 suddenly finds itself bereft of flight squares. Then there's the matter of White's king stuck in the center with an undeveloped queenside. }
*

