bxc3 d4 { The key move to prevent the pawn chain: c3-d4-e5. } 8. Qg3
{ This move was played by young IM Carissa Yip, who won the US Women's Championship in 2021 and 2023! White opens up the f3-square for the knight @@StartBracket@@or bishop via e2@@EndBracket@@ and makes it difficult for Black to develop the f8-bishop.   8.cxd4?  Qxd4  and White will drop material.   8.Be2!?  This unusual move was played by the ever-creative GM Rapport, but the game will transpose to our main line after  8...Nc6  9.Qg3  . See the 8.Qg3 variation. }
8... Nc6 9. Be2
{ This is the best try for White, aiming to put the bishop on f3 and develop the knight via h3 or e2 later. }
9... Be6
{ The key move! Make sure to remember this one!  9...dxc3?  falls into White's trap. Make sure NOT to take the pawn here!  10.Bh5+  g6  11.Bxg6+!  hxg6  12.Qxg6+  Kd7  and now White wins Black's queen by force:  13.Qxf5+  Ke8  14.Qg6+  Kd7  15.e6+!  Kd6  16.e7+  Kxe7  17.Bg5++-  . }
10. Bf3 Qd7
{ We don't want to allow tripled pawns with  10...dxc3  11.Bxc6+  bxc6  12.Ne2  . The text move instead gives Black a slight edge. }
11. Ne2 dxc3 { Now Black takes the pawn. } 12. O-O Bc5+ 13. Kh1 O-O-O
{ The game is still sharp due to opposite-side castling, but Black's extra pawn on c3 should tip the balance in our favor. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "16) Vienna Gambit"]
[Black "Vienna Gambit 3.f4 d5 4.fxe5 Nxe4 5.Qf3 #8"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. f4
{ The Vienna Gambit is quite a dangerous gambit for Black if we take the pawn. I used to play this gambit for White as a kid and always loved it when Black took on f4 or just defended the pawn with  3...d6  as most club players do.   However, I will show you an idea based on central counterplay:  3...d5!  White players hate facing this countergambit, as Black gets fast central play. Please note that the popular YouTuber IM Levy Rozman a.k.a Gothamchess also loves the Vienna Gambit for White and recommends it in his videos. So, you have to be well-prepared here as Black! }
3... d5
{ The best and most direct approach. Always fight for the center!  3...exf4?  4.e5!  , with a big initiative for White. Also, @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pppp1ppp/5n2/4p3/4PP2/2N5/PPPP2PP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq f3 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3...d6?!  is too passive, and after  4.Nf3  , White gets a nice space advantage. }
4. fxe5 Nxe4 5. Qf3
{ This move pretty much replaced the old theoretical recommendation of  5.Nf3  . GothamChess also recommends this modern approach. White immediately wants to put pressure on  the e4-knight and clarify the situation in the center. }
5... f5
{ This is the key move! While it's only the 3rd most popular move for Black, White scores an abysmal 44% in the lichess DB. The point is to try to hold on to the monster knight on e4.   5...Nxc3  6.bxc3  Be7  is what I faced as White back in the Reykjavik Open 2018 against a strong 2600+, GM Gledura from Hungary. Clearly, Black didn't know the line and quickly got into trouble after  7.d4  c5  8.Bd3  cxd4  9.cxd4  Qa5+?  10.Bd2  Bb4  11.Rd1  Bxd2+  12.Rxd2±  .  White has a big edge and doesn't care about the a2-pawn. I went on to checkmate my opponent. The lesson: Know Thy Theory! }
6. d3 { Best move by far and the one you have to be ready for! } 6... Nxc3 7.
bxc3 d4 { The key move to prevent the pawn chain: c3-d4-e5. } 8. Qg3
{ This move was played by young IM Carissa Yip, who won the US Women's Championship in 2021 and 2023! White opens up the f3-square for the knight @@StartBracket@@or bishop via e2@@EndBracket@@ and makes it difficult for Black to develop the f8-bishop.   8.cxd4?  Qxd4  and White will drop material.   8.Be2!?  This unusual move was played by the ever-creative GM Rapport, but the game will transpose to our main line after  8...Nc6  9.Qg3  . See the 8.Qg3 variation. }
8... Nc6 9. Be2
{ This is the best try for White, aiming to put the bishop on f3 and develop the knight via h3 or e2 later. }
9... Be6
{ The key move! Make sure to remember this one!  9...dxc3?  falls into White's trap. Make sure NOT to take the pawn here!  10.Bh5+  g6  11.Bxg6+!  hxg6  12.Qxg6+  Kd7  and now White wins Black's queen by force:  13.Qxf5+  Ke8  14.Qg6+  Kd7  15.e6+!  Kd6  16.e7+  Kxe7  17.Bg5++-  . }
10. Bf3 Qd7
{ We don't want to allow tripled pawns with  10...dxc3  11.Bxc6+  bxc6  12.Ne2  . The text move instead gives Black a slight edge. }
11. Ne2 dxc3 { Now Black takes the pawn. } 12. Be3 Nb4
{ Pointing out White's serious weakness: the pawn on c2. } 13. Rc1 Nd5
{ This strong regrouping was played by IM Justin Wang vs. Carissa Yip. This model game demonstrates how Black should play. }
14. Bf2 O-O-O 15. Rb1 Rg8
{ A clever idea, anticipating White's plan of castling kingside. } 16. O-O g5
{ The point of Black's last move. Now the attack is quite strong. } 17. Bxa7 b6
{ The bishop is now trapped as well. } 18. Qf2 g4
{ Forcing a favorable trade. } 19. Bxd5 Qxd5
{ Black has a dominant position and went on to win a nice game. Here's the full game:  20.Nxc3  Qd4  21.Qxd4  Rxd4  22.Kh1  g3  23.h3  Rh4  24.Rfd1  Bc5  25.Ne2  allows a pretty finish, mate in 2!  25...Rxh3+  26.gxh3  Bd5#  0-1 Yip-Wang, Irving 2019.   Conclusion: The Vienna Gambit is best met with central counterplay: @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pppp1ppp/5n2/4p3/4PP2/2N5/PPPP2PP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq f3 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3...d5!  Black gets to establish a  strong knight on e4, and remember to support it with the key move  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp2ppp/8/3pP3/4n3/2N2Q2/PPPP2PP/R1B1KBNR b KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5...f5!   Finally, the key idea @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp3pp/8/3pPp2/8/2PP1Q2/P1P3PP/R1B1KBNR b KQkq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7…d4!  prevents White from building the strong pawn  chain c3-d4-e5 and ruins White’s structure. Bear in mind that often Black castles queenside, with a nice attack against White’s king on the kingside.  Even the great attacker Carissa Yip got checkmated in just 26 moves! }
*

