{ This is the new main line. Black opens up White's king while White's d5-pawn is quite weak. The f4-pawn is often a thorn in White's kingside, as it's not so easy to win.   3...e4  was the old main line.  4.d3  Nf6  5.dxe4  Nxe4  6.Nf3⩲  , with an edge for White. }
4. Nf3
{ The most common move by far and the preferred choice of Nepo.  4.Bb5+  c6  5.dxc6  Nxc6  6.Nf3  Nf6  7.d4  Bd6  transposes to our main line. }
4... Nf6
{ Black prefers to win the d5-pawn with the knight. Note how vital it is for each side to develop as fast as possible without trying to win pawns right away. }
5. c4 { White holds on to the pawn but loses some time. } 5... c6
{ This is the fastest way to develop our b8-knight and open up the center. } 6.
dxc6 Nxc6 { Black's cavalry is ready for the fight! } 7. d4 Bg4
{ Black develops the bishop and indirectly pressures the d4-pawn by pinning the f3-knight. }
8. d5 { The most natural move, but it's just bad. } 8... Bb4+
{ Black activates the last minor piece with a big attack to come. } 9. Nc3 Ne4
{ The knight joins the party, renewing the pin on c3. } 10. dxc6 Qe7
{ A must-know move! The threats to White's king are too much. } 11. Be2
{ 11.cxb7  Nxc3+-+ } 11... Rd8 { A nice tempo on the queen. } 12. Qc2 Bf5
{ Another amazing idea, getting ready for a discovery tactic. White is lost in all lines. }
13. O-O { 13.Qb3  Nc5!  and the queen is trapped:  14.Qxb4  Nd3+-+  . } 13...
Bc5+ 14. Kh1 Nf2+ { Crushing.  14...Ng3+  also works. } *

