1. e4 e5 2. f4
{ The King's Gambit is perhaps the most well-known gambit to all chess players with a rich history. The darling gambit of the Romantic era of chess was first mentioned in a book by a Spanish player, Luis Ramírez de Lucena, titled Repetición de Amores y Arte de Ajedrez in 1497.   Over the years, it has evolved from a fighting weapon with many miniature wins by White to a less popular opening at the top. The last top players, who played it regularly, were great attackers such as David Bronstein and Boris Spassky. However, the great Bobby Fischer was quite skeptical of this gambit and even tried to find a refutation.  Modern players prefer to play this gambit mostly in rapid & blitz. The Russian, Ian Nepomniachtchi, has even published a Chessable course on it and plays it sometimes in speed chess. White's idea is quite simple. Give up the f-pawn to take over the center with a future d4 pawn push. Let's not give our opponents the type of position they dream of. Instead, I will propose a countergambit! }
2... d5
{ The Falkbeer Countergambit is named after the 19th-century Austrian master Ernst Falkbeer. Black doesn't care about winning a pawn, and instead, tries to blow open the center. The goal is rapid development above all!   2...exf4  3.Nf3  is the main line, but  3.Bc4!?  is also quite interesting and good. }
3. exd5
{ This is by far the most common move. White wants to draw Black's queen out to d5, where she'll be too vulnerable. }
3... exf4
{ This is the new main line. Black opens up White's king while White's d5-pawn is quite weak. The f4-pawn is often a thorn in White's kingside, as it's not so easy to win.   3...e4  was the old main line.  4.d3  Nf6  5.dxe4  Nxe4  6.Nf3⩲  , with an edge for White. }
4. Nf3
{ The most common move by far and the preferred choice of Nepo.  4.Bb5+  c6  5.dxc6  Nxc6  6.Nf3  Nf6  7.d4  Bd6  transposes to our main line. }
4... Nf6
{ Black prefers to win the d5-pawn with the knight. Note how vital it is for each side to develop as fast as possible without trying to win pawns right away. }
5. Bb5+ { A tempo move, White is now ready to castle. } 5... c6
{ This is the key idea that I want you to remember! Black uses the c-pawn to quickly develop the b8-knight into the game. White has to spend a tempo on dxc6, thus giving Black some initiative. }
6. dxc6 Nxc6 7. Nc3
{ This is a relatively new move with only 100 games in the DB. It's the choice of Nepo and many other top GMs. Also, the engine's top move by far. }
7... Be6
{ I prefer this rare move with a handful of games in the database to the more common  7...Bd6  .  8.Qe2+!  is the key check and quite unpleasant, as after  8...Be6  9.Nd4!  , Black is under a lot of pressure due to two pins. A lot of top-level games here. }
8. Qe2 { White is still hoping to use the pin with Ng5 next. } 8... Bb4
{ The best square for the bishop, inviting Ng5.  8...Bd6  9.Nd4!  is what we are trying to avoid. }
9. O-O O-O 10. Bxc6 bxc6 11. d4 Bd6
{ Black has a pleasant edge due to the bishop pair and White's passive bishop on c1. }
