{ The Falkbeer Countergambit is named after the 19th-century Austrian master Ernst Falkbeer. Black doesn't care about winning a pawn, and instead, tries to blow open the center. The goal is rapid development above all!   2...exf4  3.Nf3  is the main line, but  3.Bc4!?  is also quite interesting and good. }
3. exd5
{ This is by far the most common move. White wants to draw Black's queen out to d5, where she'll be too vulnerable. }
3... exf4
{ This is the new main line. Black opens up White's king while White's d5-pawn is quite weak. The f4-pawn is often a thorn in White's kingside, as it's not so easy to win.   3...e4  was the old main line.  4.d3  Nf6  5.dxe4  Nxe4  6.Nf3⩲  , with an edge for White. }
4. Nf3
{ The most common move by far and the preferred choice of Nepo.  4.Bb5+  c6  5.dxc6  Nxc6  6.Nf3  Nf6  7.d4  Bd6  transposes to our main line. }
4... Nf6
{ Black prefers to win the d5-pawn with the knight. Note how vital it is for each side to develop as fast as possible without trying to win pawns right away. }
5. Bb5+ { A tempo move, White is now ready to castle. } 5... c6
{ This is the key idea that I want you to remember! Black uses the c-pawn to quickly develop the b8-knight into the game. White has to spend a tempo on dxc6, thus giving Black some initiative. }
6. dxc6 Nxc6 7. d4
{ White's idea is simple, grab the center and win the f4-pawn. This is the main line but not a good one for White! Modern engines already give Black an edge after the logical  7...Bd6! }
7... Bd6 { Black protects the f4-pawn and gets ready to castle. } 8. O-O
{ More common than  8.Qe2+  . } 8... O-O
{ Both sides castled, but we can see how the f4-pawn is a big annoyance for White's bishop. }
9. Nbd2
{ White decides to develop the knight first, keeping the option of pushing the c-pawn for later. This is a rich position where Black has at least 5 moves to a slight edge. Most of them involve the ...h6 and ...g5 push, which is a bit risky. Let me show you a safer idea. }
9... Bg4 { We pin the knight and develop the bishop. } 10. Nc4 Bc7 11. Bxc6
bxc6
{ With a pleasant edge for Black, as the c1-bishop is still unhappy here, while we have the bishop pair too. }
