{ Black is clearly better, as White is totally tied up everywhere. Black's bishop pair rule the board, and we are ready to launch a kingside attack with a future ...g5!   Conclusion: King’s Gambit’s heydays are in the past, yet Black has to be able to meet this Romantic opening with concrete central play. Remember to play @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppp1ppp/8/4p3/4PP2/8/PPPP2PP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq f3 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2...d5!  and only then take on f4.  Active play is the best way to take advantage of White’s weakened king as we often sacrifice the pawn ourselves. Let’s put White on the defensive in this opening with energetic developing moves! Be ready to surprise your opponent in  the @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/pp3ppp/2nb1n2/1B6/3P1p2/5N2/PPP3PP/RNBQK2R w KQkq - 1 8@@EndFEN@@  8.Qe2+  line with a bombshell of a move: @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/pp3ppp/2nbNn2/1B6/3P1p2/8/PPP1Q1PP/RNB1K2R b KQ - 0 10@@EndFEN@@  10...Qb6!!  , sacrificing material to win White’s queen! }
