[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. d4 cxd4 3. c3
{ This is a very popular gambit at all levels, so you have to be well-prepared! The Smith-Morra Gambit is named after Pierre Morra @@StartBracket@@1900-1969@@EndBracket@@ from France, and Ken Smith @@StartBracket@@1930-1999@@EndBracket@@ of the Dallas Chess Club. It's been also popularized by IM Marc Esserman with his book Mayhem in the Morra!.  I have done some serious work on this gambit while working for my Chessable LTR course: Hyper-Accelerated Dragon. The analysis here is more or the less the same as given in my course. }
3... dxc3
{ In the past I have recommended the simple move  3...g6  to sidestep the Smith-Morra. While it's a good surprise weapon, in this course I have decided to focus on the refutation instead. }
4. Nxc3
{ White hopes to put pressure on Black with rapid development, so you have to know exactly what setup to choose as Black! }
4... Nc6 5. Nf3 e6
{ Getting ready to develop the f8-bishop while building a powerful wall in case White decides to play Bc4. }
6. Bf4
{ The 2nd most popular move in my Chessbase Megabase; White wants to play Nb5 next. }
6... Bb4
{ This simple developing move is my antidote against most tries by White. We pin the knight and develop the bishop. }
7. Bd6 { The most often played move. } 7... Bxd6 8. Qxd6 Nf6
{ More accurate to start with this move first.  8...Qe7  allows  9.Qg3  with some unpleasant pressure on  the g7-pawn. }
9. O-O-O Qe7 { With this simple move, Black is now ready to castle. } 10. Qg3
{ Exchanging queens will only increase Black's advantage. After  10.Qxe7+  Kxe7  , the extra pawn becomes more prominent, and finishing development  won't be a problem since ...d6, ...b6, or ...a6 followed by ...b5 are valid ideas. }
10... O-O 11. e5 Nd5 { A strong novelty to give back the pawn. } 12. Nxd5 exd5
13. Rxd5 d6
{ The star move! Black frees the bishop on c8, and White is now in trouble, as the king is too exposed. }
14. exd6
{ 14.Rxd6  Qc7!  , setting up some nice discoveries. After  15.Kb1  Nb4  ,  the c2-square is quite weak.  16.Rd2  Bf5+-+  and it's game  over, as Ka1 loses to a back-rank mate. }
14... Qe4 { A key tempo on the rook. } 15. Rg5 Bf5
{ We don't care about the g7-pawn, as our threats are bigger. } 16. Rxg7+ Kh8
{ White is lost due to many threats. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "18) Smith-Morra Gambit"]
[Black "Smith-Morra Gambit 3.c3 − 6.Bc4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. d4 cxd4 3. c3
{ This is a very popular gambit at all levels, so you have to be well-prepared! The Smith-Morra Gambit is named after Pierre Morra @@StartBracket@@1900-1969@@EndBracket@@ from France, and Ken Smith @@StartBracket@@1930-1999@@EndBracket@@ of the Dallas Chess Club. It's been also popularized by IM Marc Esserman with his book Mayhem in the Morra!.  I have done some serious work on this gambit while working for my Chessable LTR course: Hyper-Accelerated Dragon. The analysis here is more or the less the same as given in my course. }
3... dxc3
{ In the past I have recommended the simple move  3...g6  to sidestep the Smith-Morra. While it's a good surprise weapon, in this course I have decided to focus on the refutation instead. }
4. Nxc3
{ White hopes to put pressure on Black with rapid development, so you have to know exactly what setup to choose as Black! }
4... Nc6 5. Nf3 e6
{ Getting ready to develop the f8-bishop while building a powerful wall in case White decides to play Bc4. }
6. Bc4
{ By far the most popular move, White wants to castle as quickly as possible. }
6... Bb4
{ I recommend this simple setup. It's quite rare with just over 600 games in the Chessbase DB @@StartBracket@@compared to almost 3000 games with ...a6@@EndBracket@@. Black pins the knight and gets ready to develop the kingside first with ...Nge7 next. }
7. Bd2 { 7.Bf4  transposes to the 6.Bf4 variation. } 7... Nge7 8. O-O d5
{ Black achieves the goal of the central break. } 9. exd5 exd5
{ With a small plus, as White doesn't have full compensation for the pawn. } *

