[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. d4 cxd4 3. c3
{ This is a very popular gambit at all levels, so you have to be well-prepared! The Smith-Morra Gambit is named after Pierre Morra @@StartBracket@@1900-1969@@EndBracket@@ from France, and Ken Smith @@StartBracket@@1930-1999@@EndBracket@@ of the Dallas Chess Club. It's been also popularized by IM Marc Esserman with his book Mayhem in the Morra!.  I have done some serious work on this gambit while working for my Chessable LTR course: Hyper-Accelerated Dragon. The analysis here is more or the less the same as given in my course. }
3... dxc3
{ In the past I have recommended the simple move  3...g6  to sidestep the Smith-Morra. While it's a good surprise weapon, in this course I have decided to focus on the refutation instead. }
4. Nxc3
{ White hopes to put pressure on Black with rapid development, so you have to know exactly what setup to choose as Black! }
4... Nc6 5. Nf3 e6
{ Getting ready to develop the f8-bishop while building a powerful wall in case White decides to play Bc4. }
6. Bc4
{ By far the most popular move, White wants to castle as quickly as possible. }
6... Bb4
{ I recommend this simple setup. It's quite rare with just over 600 games in the Chessbase DB @@StartBracket@@compared to almost 3000 games with ...a6@@EndBracket@@. Black pins the knight and gets ready to develop the kingside first with ...Nge7 next. }
7. O-O
{ The most common move by far.  7.Bf4  transposes to the 6.Bf4 variation. }
7... Nge7
{ Black is ready to castle and/or strike with ...d5 at the right moment. We will cover all the popular tries by White. }
8. Qc2
{ Played by the Smith-Morra Expert, IM Marc Esserman. It's a bit similar to  8.Qe2  , as  White wants to play Rd1 next. }
8... O-O 9. Rd1
{ White puts pressure on the d-file, making it hard for Black to push the d-pawn. }
9... Ng6 { Securing Black's king long-term. } 10. Bg5
{ White develops the bishop with tempo, hitting our queen.  10.Be3  allows Black to finish development after  10...b6  11.Nb5  Bb7  , with a slight edge for Black. }
10... Qa5 { More aggressive than  10...Be7  . } 11. Nb5 a6 12. a3
{ A logical move trying to trap the bishop, but Black has a simple reply. After  12.Nd6  Qc7  13.Nxc8  Raxc8∓  ,  Black happily traded the passive c8-bishop for the knight. White doesn't have enough compensation for the pawn. }
12... axb5 { Black welcomes the complications! } 13. axb4 Qxa1 14. Rxa1 Rxa1+
15. Bf1 d5
{ Black's rooks and an extra pawn give a big edge as in the game: Moura-Hoffman, Florianopolis 2019. }
