{ Black tucks away the king from the x-ray of the b3-bishop and stands clearly better. We will finish development with ...Bd7 and dominate the game with the extra pawn and the mobile center.   Conclusion: The Smith-Morra Gambit is a very popular gambit at club levels. However, don’t be afraid to grab the pawn and go for the rare approach with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/8/4P3/2N5/PP3PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Nc6  , @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp1ppppp/2n5/8/4P3/2N2N2/PP3PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5...e6  , @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp1p1ppp/2n1p3/8/4PB2/2N2N2/PP3PPP/R2QKB1R b KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Bb4  . Black is rock solid due to the  strong f7-e6-d7 pawn triangle and with accurate play, White’s attack is easily repelled. Remember that Black’s strong central pawns give us a long-term advantage. Sooner or later they will start moving and seize the initiative! }
