[White "19) Sicilian Wing Gambit"]
[Black "Sicilian Wing Gambit 2.b4 cxb4 3.a3 e5 4.Nf3 #5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. b4
{ This is the Sicilian Wing Gambit, popular mostly at club level. Ginger GM Simon Williams recommends it as a sharp weapon against the Sicilian, so you have to be ready! }
2... cxb4 { We take the pawn and accept the challenge! } 3. a3
{ This is the most popular move, White offers this trade to activate the pieces. }
3... e5
{ This move is less common than the popular  3...d5  , but I prefer to fight for the center with simple moves. Black activates  the bishop and protects the b4-pawn. }
4. Nf3 Nc6
{ The game now resembles a 1.e4 e5 opening but with a nice extra pawn for Black on b4. }
5. Bc4 Nf6
{ The game looks a bit like the Two Knights Defense, but Black has the better version due to the extra b4-pawn. }
6. Qe2
{ White plays a solid defensive move, but this gives Black plenty of time to develop. }
6... Be7 7. axb4 Bxb4
{ The tempo loss is irrelevant since White also lost a tempo on Qe2. } 8. c3
Be7 9. O-O O-O 10. d4 d6
{ White does have a bit of compensation due to better central control but not enough for a full pawn! }
11. Rd1 Qc7
{ I prefer Black but lots of fight is ahead! Here's how the game may continue:  12.h3  Bd7  13.Bd3  Rfd8  14.d5  Na5  and it's clear that White is lacking a key pawn on the queenside as in a recent correspondence game Langheld-Reppert, LSS email 2022.   Conclusion: The Sicilian Wing Gambit is a rare but occasional guest at all levels. Don’t be afraid to grab the pawn but remember the key little pawn push @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/8/1p2P3/P7/2PP1PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3...e5!  Often, the game resembles standard 1.e4 e5 openings except with a big plus for Black, having the extra pawn on b4.  We can even get a funny version of the Fried Liver  @@StartBracket@@@@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp1p1ppp/2n2n2/4p3/1pB1P3/P4N2/2PP1PPP/RNBQK2R w KQkq - 4 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Ng5  d5!  @@EndBracket@@, where we set the board on fire with a nice @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp3ppp/2n2n2/3Pp1N1/1pB5/P7/2PP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7…b5!  Overall, if you know your lines, then you will have all the fun in this gambit. }
