[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "20) French Wing Gambit"]
[Black "French Wing Gambit 4.b4 cxb4 5.a3 Qa5 6.d4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. Nf3
{ White typically starts with this move to set up the French Wing Gambit, as they want to preserve the d-pawn. }
2... d5 3. e5 c5 4. b4
{ This is the idea behind the gambit. White wants to sacrifice the b-pawn in order to play d4 later and dominate the center. This is quite a dangerous gambit, as Black will be lacking central control for many moves. }
4... cxb4
{ The most principled reply! But accurate play is required from Black. } 5. a3
{ This is a bit more popular than an immediate  5.d4  . The point is that White wants to  achieve the c3-d4-e5 pawn chain if Black takes on a3. The other bonus is that sometimes White wants to trade the dark-squared bishop with Bxa3 next. }
5... Qa5
{ I recommend this rare move with the idea to stop White from building the c3-d4-e5 pawn chain, played by Firouzja in 2020. Now White can't take on b4, as the a1-rook is unprotected.   5...Nc6  6.axb4  Bxb4  7.c3  Be7  8.d4  is what White is aiming for, while @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/4p3/3pP3/1p6/P4N2/2PP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...bxa3  6.d4  Nc6  7.c3  is the point of White's plan. }
6. d4
{ White immediately takes the central control, unafraid of any discoveries on the diagonal. }
6... Bd7
{ Easy does it. Black goes for typical development, aiming to trade the bad 'French bishop' with ...Bb5 later.  6...Nc6  is fine as well. }
7. Bd3 Bb5 { Black achieves the strategic goal of trading the bishops. } 8. O-O
{ After  8.axb4  Qxa1  9.Bxb5+  Nc6∓  , White doesn't have enough for the exchange as in the game Day-Huebner, Jerusalem 1967. }
8... Bxd3 9. Qxd3 Qa6
{ Being a pawn up, Black is happy to trade queens.  9...Nc6  is quite good as well. }
10. Qb3 { White obviously avoids the trade. } 10... Nc6 11. Nbd2 b5
{ A strong novelty to expand on the queenside.  11...Nh6  12.Bb2  and now axb4 is an annoying threat. }
12. Bb2 bxa3 13. Bxa3 Bxa3 14. Rxa3 Qb6
{ Black secures a nice square for the queen and is about to finish development with ...Nge7 and ...O-O. Black can also push ...b4 if needed.   The game may continue:  15.Rb1  b4  16.Qa4  Nge7  17.c3  O-O!  18.cxb4  Nxd4∓  , when Black is still a pawn up and enjoys a clear edge. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "20) French Wing Gambit"]
[Black "French Wing Gambit 4.b4 cxb4 5.a3 Qa5 6.Be2 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. Nf3
{ White typically starts with this move to set up the French Wing Gambit, as they want to preserve the d-pawn. }
2... d5 3. e5 c5 4. b4
{ This is the idea behind the gambit. White wants to sacrifice the b-pawn in order to play d4 later and dominate the center. This is quite a dangerous gambit, as Black will be lacking central control for many moves. }
4... cxb4
{ The most principled reply! But accurate play is required from Black. } 5. a3
{ This is a bit more popular than an immediate  5.d4  . The point is that White wants to  achieve the c3-d4-e5 pawn chain if Black takes on a3. The other bonus is that sometimes White wants to trade the dark-squared bishop with Bxa3 next. }
5... Qa5
{ I recommend this rare move with the idea to stop White from building the c3-d4-e5 pawn chain, played by Firouzja in 2020. Now White can't take on b4, as the a1-rook is unprotected.   5...Nc6  6.axb4  Bxb4  7.c3  Be7  8.d4  is what White is aiming for, while @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/4p3/3pP3/1p6/P4N2/2PP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...bxa3  6.d4  Nc6  7.c3  is the point of White's plan. }
6. Be2 { White goes for natural development. } 6... Nh6 7. O-O Nc6
{ I like this natural novelty over Firouzja's choice.  7...Be7?!  8.d4  O-O  9.Bxh6  gxh6  10.Qc1⩲  and White is better as in the game Lagarde-Firouzja, Europe Echecs 2020. }
8. d4
{ White achieves the goal of the opening, but Black now has a clear target: the d4-pawn. }
8... Nf5 9. g4 { A bit too ambitious! } 9... Nfe7
{ Now, White's king is severely weakened and Black starts their regrouping to get the knight to g6. }
10. Bb2 Ng6 11. axb4 Qxb4 12. Ba3 Qb6 { 12...Qa5  is also quite good. } 13.
Bxf8 Rxf8
{ It looks as though White has made some progress by trading the dark-squared bishops and making Black lose the right to castle kingside. However, Black is still better due to the unstoppable ...f6! idea. }
14. Na3 f6 { A classic French idea to undermine the center. } 15. Nb5
{ This active jump can easily be ignored. } 15... fxe5 16. Nd6+ Ke7 17. Nxc8+
{ 17.dxe5  Ngxe5∓ } 17... Raxc8
{ Black's king is safe on e7 and both rooks are quite active. White is just down two pawns for nothing. }
*

