{ This is a bit more popular than an immediate  5.d4  . The point is that White wants to  achieve the c3-d4-e5 pawn chain if Black takes on a3. The other bonus is that sometimes White wants to trade the dark-squared bishop with Bxa3 next. }
5... Qa5
{ I recommend this rare move with the idea to stop White from building the c3-d4-e5 pawn chain, played by Firouzja in 2020. Now White can't take on b4, as the a1-rook is unprotected.   5...Nc6  6.axb4  Bxb4  7.c3  Be7  8.d4  is what White is aiming for, while @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/4p3/3pP3/1p6/P4N2/2PP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...bxa3  6.d4  Nc6  7.c3  is the point of White's plan. }
6. Bb2
{ The most logical move. White develops the bishop and protects the a1-rook. Now they want to take on b4. }
6... Nc6
{ Black develops the knight to a natural square and gets ready for axb4. } 7.
axb4 Qxb4
{ Now, you can see another point of the earlier ...Qa5. White's b2-bishop is under attack. }
8. Bc3
{ White keeps the e5-pawn protected, but the drawback of this move is that it's much harder to build the c3-d4-e5 pawn chain. }
8... Qb6
{ The queen is the hero in this game for Black!  8...Qe4+  doesn't make much  sense, as the e5-pawn is well protected.  9.Be2  , with compensation. }
9. d4 Nh6
{ The knight heads to a natural outpost on f5. In the meantime, White's queenside pieces are lacking good squares. }
10. Bd3 Nf5 11. O-O Bd7 12. Na3 a6
{ A simple prophylactic measure to restrict White's a3-knight.  12...Nfxd4  is a bit risky.  13.Nxd4  Nxd4  14.Qg4  , with good compensation for White. }
13. Rb1
{ 13.g4?  is a blunder. Now after  13...Nfxd4  14.Nxd4  Nxd4∓  , White no longer has the queen jump, as  the g4-square is covered. Black is much better here. }
13... Qc7 14. Rb3 b5
{ Black is clearly better, as White doesn't have much for the pawn. Just take a look at how pathetic the a3-knight and c3-bishop are. Black is threatening a ...b4 fork next, followed by a natural ...Be7, ...O-O development.   Conclusion: The French Wing Gambit has a sound foundation if White manages to build the c3-d4-e5 pawn chain. However, my recommendation @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/4p3/3pP3/1p6/P4N2/2PP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Qa5!?  stops White’s plan, by using  a simple pin idea since the a1-rook is unprotected. As a result, White doesn’t get good coordination and Black will enjoy typical French ideas but with a nice bonus – an extra pawn! }
