[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "21) Orthoschnapp Gambit"]
[Black "Orthoschnapp Gambit 4.Qb3 dxe4 5.Bc4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. c4 d5 3. cxd5 exd5 4. Qb3
{ This unusual way to play against the French Defense is known as the Orthoschnapp Gambit. It was invented by German FM Stefan Buecker in the 1980s. These days it is popularized by IM Eric Rosen and IM Levy Rozman @@StartBracket@@GothamChess@@EndBracket@@, so we have to take it seriously! }
4... dxe4 { Of course, we take the central pawn! It is the best move by far. }
5. Bc4
{ The point of White's gambit is clear now. They are going for fast development and hitting our weak f7-pawn. }
5... Qe7
{ Perhaps the most difficult move of the entire gambit refutation, but this is the best way to defend our f7-pawn.  5...Qd7⩱  and  5...Qf6⩱  . }
6. Nc3 { White continues with natural development. } 6... Nf6
{ We also develop and protect the d5-square. } 7. d3
{ White offers a 2nd pawn, and we can take it with check! } 7... exd3+
{ Let's go! } 8. Be3 d2+
{ Our pawn is wreaking havoc in White's camp. There's no good way to capture it, so White usually leaves it alone for now. }
9. Kxd2 { White's monarch is quite exposed now and Black gets a nice attack. }
9... Qd7+ 10. Kc2 Bd6 11. Rd1 O-O
{ Just compare the two kings: Black's is very safe while White's king is quite open. Don't forget that Black still has an extra pawn!   The game may continue with  12.Nf3  Nc6  13.Kb1  , where the king finally reached safety but at the cost of many moves.  13...Na5  is a simple fork, getting us a favorable trade. After  14.Qb5  Nxc4  15.Qxc4  Qg4∓  , Black offers the queen trade leading to a technical endgame up a pawn. }
*

