Nf3 Bd7
{ Remember this strong idea! The ...Na5! threat and the idea to castle long forces White to take the b7-pawn. }
11. Qxb7 { 11.Bxd2?  Na5  drops the c4-bishop! } 11... Rb8 12. Qxc7 Rxb2
{ We have a bit of a wild position, but Black's extra pawn and the ability to castle gives us a nice edge. }
13. Nxd2 { Probably White's best try. } 13... Qe5
{ A cool idea to remember; we force a favorable endgame now. } 14. Qxe5+ Nxe5
15. Re1 Kd8
{ Black is clearly better, as we have an easy plan to develop with ...Bb4 and ...Re8. White is struggling with their kingside development. A recent correspondence game reached this position and Black eventually converted the -1 edge: Faber-Targonski, ICCF email 2021.   Conclusion: The Orthoschnapp Gambit against the French is more for the memes, yet it’s a good idea to know the refutation just in case you run into an Eric Rosen or GothamChess fan.  It’s important to know the little intermezzo @@StartFEN@@rnb1kb1r/ppp1qppp/5n2/8/2B5/1QNpB3/PP3PPP/R3K1NR b KQkq - 1 8@@EndFEN@@  8...d2+!  , forcing White to lose the right to castle.  After that, remember development and active play are key, and don’t worry about sacrificing the b7-pawn. Even if White survives to the endgame as shown in the main line, they will be playing down the h1-rook. }
