8. O-O
{ This is the main point of the Milner-Barry Gambit. White sacrifices the pawn @@StartBracket@@or two@@EndBracket@@ for rapid development. However, I will show you that it's not very sound. White will fight for equality at best. }
8... Nxd4 { Of course, we take the pawn! } 9. Nxd4 Qxd4 10. Nc3
{ White's most common move, offering the 2nd pawn. } 10... a6
{ An important move, preventing Nb5:  10...Ne7  11.Nb5!   10...Qxe5  11.Re1  Qb8  12.Nxd5  Bd6  13.Qg4  Kf8  with good counterplay, while @@StartFEN@@r3kbnr/pp1b1ppp/4p3/3pP3/3q4/2NB4/PP3PPP/R1BQ1RK1 b kq - 1 10@@EndFEN@@  10...Bc5?  fails to  11.Be3  Qb4  12.a3  Qb6  13.Na4  Bxa4  14.Qxa4+±  . }
11. Qe2 Ne7
{ Black's idea is to transfer the knight to c6 where it could apply pressure on the e5-pawn. }
12. Kh1 { White prepares the f4 push. } 12... Nc6 13. f4 Nb4
{ It turns out that the bishop on d3 doesn't have many squares. } 14. Rd1 Bc5
{ Black proceeds with natural development, unafraid of discovered attacks. }
15. Bxa6 Qf2 { Forcing the queen trade. } 16. Qxf2 Bxf2 17. Bb5
{ White managed to win back the pawn, but Black is better in the resulting endgame due to the strongly protected passer on d5.   Instead,  17.Bxb7  self-traps the bishop due to  17...Ra7! }
17... Bxb5
{ This is the most direct! It leads to a long forced sequence that wins a pawn for Black. }
18. Nxb5 Rxa2 19. Rxa2 Nxa2
{ Black won a pawn but has to be a bit careful to avoid the knight getting trapped. }
20. Bd2
{ Now the knight has no squares and White is threatening Ra1; luckily Black is in time! }
20... Kd7 21. Ra1 Rc8
{ The key idea! White's weak back rank is the issue here. } 22. Na3
{ 22.Rxa2  Rc2!  and the bishop is lost. } 22... Bc5 { A nice regrouping. } 23.
Rxa2 Bb4 { An amazing idea, again using White's weak back rank. } 24. Be3
