24... d4 25. Bxd4 Rc1+ 26. Bg1 Bc5
{ Black will win the g1-bishop, with total endgame domination.   Conclusion: The classic Milner-Berry Gambit is not dangerous for Black at all, and don’t be afraid to grab the d4-pawn but only after inserting @@StartFEN@@r1b1kbnr/pp3ppp/1qn1p3/3pP3/3P4/3B1N2/PP3PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7...Bd7  @@StartBracket@@you don’t want to lose your queen to a famous Bb5+ tactic@@EndBracket@@. One key move to remember is the prophylactic idea  @@StartFEN@@r3kbnr/pp1b1ppp/4p3/3pP3/3q4/2NB4/PP3PPP/R1BQ1RK1 b kq - 1 10@@EndFEN@@  10...a6!   However, @@StartFEN@@r1b1kbnr/pp3ppp/1qn1p3/3pP3/3p4/2PB1N2/PP3PPP/RNBQK2R w KQkq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7.O-O!  is a very strong modern improvement, infusing new life into this old gambit. Black has to be careful and calmly develop with ...Bd7, ...Nge7, ...Rc8, and make sure to meet h4 with ...h6. The game is complex, but White is the one trying to prove compensation for the pawn. }
