[Black "Milner-Barry Gambit 6.Bd3 cxd4 7.cxd4 #5 | Alternative 17...h5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. e5
{ This is the Advance Variation of the French Defense. White makes their aggressive intention clear by creating a powerful pawn chain. }
3... c5 4. c3 Nc6 5. Nf3 Qb6 6. Bd3
{ This aggressive line is named after a British chess player, Stuart Milner-Barry, who among other things was a code breaker during WWII! }
6... cxd4 7. cxd4
{ White sets up a basic trap.   7.O-O!  is all the hype these days. It was first played by Swedish GM Jonny Hector. White doesn't waste any time on recapturing  the d4-pawn and goes for rapid development. It is actually a totally sound gambit and perhaps will be covered in the Totally Sound Gambits series!  7...Bd7  8.Re1  Nge7  9.h4  h6  10.h5  Rc8  11.Nbd2  dxc3  12.bxc3  Na5∞  , with complex play. }
7... Bd7
{ Black plays an important move in stopping White's trap. Make sure NOT TO DO this:  7...Nxd4??  8.Nxd4  Qxd4  9.Bb5+  . Oops, and the queen is lost... }
8. O-O
{ This is the main point of the Milner-Barry Gambit. White sacrifices the pawn @@StartBracket@@or two@@EndBracket@@ for rapid development. However, I will show you that it's not very sound. White will fight for equality at best. }
8... Nxd4 { Of course, we take the pawn! } 9. Nxd4 Qxd4 10. Nc3
{ White's most common move, offering the 2nd pawn. } 10... a6
{ An important move, preventing Nb5:  10...Ne7  11.Nb5!   10...Qxe5  11.Re1  Qb8  12.Nxd5  Bd6  13.Qg4  Kf8  with good counterplay, while @@StartFEN@@r3kbnr/pp1b1ppp/4p3/3pP3/3q4/2NB4/PP3PPP/R1BQ1RK1 b kq - 1 10@@EndFEN@@  10...Bc5?  fails to  11.Be3  Qb4  12.a3  Qb6  13.Na4  Bxa4  14.Qxa4+±  . }
11. Qe2 Ne7
{ Black's idea is to transfer the knight to c6 where it could apply pressure on the e5-pawn. }
12. Kh1 { White prepares the f4 push. } 12... Nc6 13. f4 Nb4
{ It turns out that the bishop on d3 doesn't have many squares. } 14. Rd1 Bc5
{ Black proceeds with natural development, unafraid of discovered attacks. }
15. Bxa6 Qf2 { Forcing the queen trade. } 16. Qxf2 Bxf2 17. Bb5
{ White managed to win back the pawn, but Black is better in the resulting endgame due to the strongly protected passer on d5.   Instead,  17.Bxb7  self-traps the bishop due to  17...Ra7! }
17... h5
{ I also like this expansion idea if you don't want to memorize super-long lines with ‘only moves’. }
18. Bxd7+ Kxd7 19. Ne4 Nc2 { A nice counter! } 20. Rb1 Bd4 21. Ng5 Rxa2
{ Black is better in this resulting endgame. For example  22.Nxf7  Rha8  23.Ng5  Ra1  24.Rxa1  Rxa1  and White is lost since there's no defense  against ...Bxb2. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "23) Hillbilly Attack"]
[Black "Hillbilly Attack 2.Bc4 d5 3.Bb3 − 5.Qe5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. Bc4
{ This rare 2nd move is the precursor to the Hillbilly Attack. } 2... d5 3. Bb3
{ White sacrifices the e4-pawn, hoping to use the a2-g8 diagonal for attack. }
3... dxe4 { We take the free central pawn and accept the challenge! } 4. Qh5
{ This rather straightforward approach that looks like a beginner going for a quick checkmate is the Hillbilly Attack @@StartBracket@@thus the name@@EndBracket@@. Surprisingly, it has been played by Magnus Carlsen, Firouzja, and Ginger GM Simon Williams. So, we have to take it seriously! }
4... g6
{ Simple chess! We drive the queen away, winning a tempo.  4...e6  is good too. }
5. Qe5
{ This looks like a clever double attack, but it is actually a serious mistake. }
5... Nf6
{ Black develops the knight while securing the e4-pawn. White is just down a pawn for no compensation. After the natural ...Bg7 & ...O-O, White's queen will be caught in the crossfire. Black is clearly much better! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "23) Hillbilly Attack"]
[Black "Hillbilly Attack 2.Bc4 d5 3.Bb3 − 5.Qh4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. Bc4
{ This rare 2nd move is the precursor to the Hillbilly Attack. } 2... d5 3. Bb3
{ White sacrifices the e4-pawn, hoping to use the a2-g8 diagonal for attack. }
3... dxe4 { We take the free central pawn and accept the challenge! } 4. Qh5
{ This rather straightforward approach that looks like a beginner going for a quick checkmate is the Hillbilly Attack @@StartBracket@@thus the name@@EndBracket@@. Surprisingly, it has been played by Magnus Carlsen, Firouzja, and Ginger GM Simon Williams. So, we have to take it seriously! }
4... g6
{ Simple chess! We drive the queen away, winning a tempo.  4...e6  is good too. }
5. Qh4
{ White prefers this square for the queen to hit the e4-pawn and prepare for a future kingside attack. }
5... a5
{ I recommend this rare move, with only 7 games in the DB. Black sets up a cunning trap!  5...Nf6  is the most common reply with over 100 games in the database. }
6. a4 { A natural reaction, but now the b4-square is weakened. } 6... Nf6 7.
Nc3 Bg7
{ There's no need to hold on to the e4-pawn, as development is more important. }
8. Nxe4 Na6 { The knight is aiming at the b4 or c5-square. } 9. Nf3 Nb4 10. d3
Be6 { White is in big trouble since the c2-pawn is now super weak. } 11. Bxe6
{ 11.O-O  Bxb3  12.cxb3  Qxd3∓  wins a pawn. } 11... Nxc2+
{ A nice intermezzo! } 12. Ke2 Nxa1 13. Neg5
{ White's last attempt at counterplay. Black has to be a bit careful here. }
13... fxe6 14. Nxe6 Qb6
{ The best square for the queen, keeping an eye on the b2 & f2-pawns. } 15.
Nxg7+ Kf7 16. Qh6 Nc2
{ The knight comes back to play a crucial role in defending the king! } 17.
Ne5+ Kg8 18. Ne6 { Threatening mate on g7. } 18... Nd4+ { The only move! } 19.
Nxd4 Qxd4
{ Black traded the e6-knight and secured a long-term material advantage. } *

