[White "23) Hillbilly Attack"]
[Black "Hillbilly Attack 2.Bc4 d5 3.Bb3 − 5.Qh4 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. Bc4
{ This rare 2nd move is the precursor to the Hillbilly Attack. } 2... d5 3. Bb3
{ White sacrifices the e4-pawn, hoping to use the a2-g8 diagonal for attack. }
3... dxe4 { We take the free central pawn and accept the challenge! } 4. Qh5
{ This rather straightforward approach that looks like a beginner going for a quick checkmate is the Hillbilly Attack @@StartBracket@@thus the name@@EndBracket@@. Surprisingly, it has been played by Magnus Carlsen, Firouzja, and Ginger GM Simon Williams. So, we have to take it seriously! }
4... g6
{ Simple chess! We drive the queen away, winning a tempo.  4...e6  is good too. }
5. Qh4
{ White prefers this square for the queen to hit the e4-pawn and prepare for a future kingside attack. }
5... a5
{ I recommend this rare move, with only 7 games in the DB. Black sets up a cunning trap!  5...Nf6  is the most common reply with over 100 games in the database. }
6. Nc3 { White goes for rapid development. } 6... Bg7
{ Don't worry about protecting the e4-pawn, development is key for Black as well! }
7. Nxe4 a4 { Another useful reason behind the ...a5 push. } 8. Bc4
{ After  8.Bxa4?  , White enters an inferior trade.  8...Rxa4  9.Nf6+  Nxf6  10.Qxa4  O-O∓  and Black's two minor pieces will dominate the rook! }
8... b5 { Now the bishop is forced back. } 9. Be2
{ Check out how Simon Williams lost to Gawain Jones in just a few moves here: }
9... Nh6
{ A clever way to develop. Black keeps the long diagonal open for the bishop. }
10. g4 { Overly ambitious! } 10... a3
{ It's funny that Simon Williams falls for his own favorite rook pawn push. Was it Anna the a-pawn who rocks the board now? }
11. Rb1 Qd5 { Very accurate play from the other strong British GM! } 12. Nc3
{ Did White set up a trap? } 12... Qxh1
{ Trust your calculation! The queen cannot be trapped! } 13. Kf1 Be5
{ Simple chess, hitting the h2-pawn. But many other moves win here for Black. }
14. Bf3 Qxh2 15. Nh3 Nxg4 16. Bxg4 Bf6
{ White threw in the towel in Williams-Jones, England 2011. } *

