[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "24) ICBM Gambit"]
[Black "ICBM Gambit 1.e4 d5 2.Nf3 dxe4 3.Ng5 Nf6 4.Bc4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d5 { Hello to all the #teamScandi fans! } 2. Nf3
{ If you love the Scandinavian Defense, or if you play @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/5N2/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1...d5  to White's 1.Nf3,  then you should be ready for the tricky ICBM  (Intercontinental Ballistic Missile)  Gambit, which is also known as the Tennison Gambit. The chess amateur Otto Mandrup Tennison played and analyzed this idea in the 1850s in New Orleans. }
2... dxe4
{ We don't hesitate for one moment and take the central pawn with tempo! } 3.
Ng5 Nf6
{ While I prefer  3...Bf5  here, which is the best move objectively, we are waiting for White to play the main ICBM Gambit idea: @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pppp/5n2/6N1/4p3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 2 4@@EndFEN@@  4.d3  . }
4. Bc4
{ This is probably White's best try. Black has to deal with the pressure on f7.  4.Nc3  Bf5  is covered via transposition. }
4... e6 5. Nc3 Be7 6. Ngxe4 { Sooner or later, White has to take this pawn. }
6... Nxe4 7. Nxe4 f5
{ I like this natural move, which is also a novelty, asking the knight where it's going to retreat. }
8. Ng3 Nc6 9. O-O O-O 10. Re1
{ It seems as though Black is having major issues defending the e6-pawn... }
10... Kh8 { Having a problem with the pawn? No problem, just give it up! } 11.
d3 f4 { With counterplay. } 12. Ne4 f3 13. g3 e5
{ The light squares around White's king are quite weak. Black can try ...Qd7-h3 or ...Nd4 next. }
*

