{ While I prefer  3...Bf5  here, which is the best move objectively, we are waiting for White to play the main ICBM Gambit idea: @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pppp/5n2/6N1/4p3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 2 4@@EndFEN@@  4.d3  . }
4. d3
{ This is the starting point of the ICBM gambit and recommended by IM Levy Rozman. We will refute this gambit outright! I have no idea who actually came up with the name ICBM for this one...   4.Nc3  Bf5  is covered via transposition. }
4... Bg4
{ The simple refutation, don't take the pawn on d3!  4...exd3  5.Bxd3  h6??  is what White had in mind, and now  6.Nxf7!  Kxf7  7.Bg6+  , when Black loses the queen:  7...Kxg6  8.Qxd8+-  . }
5. f3 { What else? Other options are just as bad for White... } 5... exf3
{ Black is happy with this trade. } 6. Nxf3
{ After  6.gxf3  Bh5  , White's structure is compromised and they are down a pawn. Black is close to winning already! }
6... e5
{ The pawn is taboo due to the pin. We will develop with natural moves and castle next. White is now down a pawn for nothing.   Conclusion: The ICBM Gambit is as bad as it gets, as long as you don't take on d3 and walk into a tactic. Natural developing moves starting with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pppp/5n2/6N1/4p3/3P4/PPP2PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Bg4!  pretty much take the fuse out of this gambit. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "24) ICBM Gambit"]
[Black "ICBM Gambit 1.e4 d5 2.Nf3 dxe4 3.Ng5 | Alternative 3...Bf5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d5 { Hello to all the #teamScandi fans! } 2. Nf3
{ If you love the Scandinavian Defense, or if you play @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/5N2/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1...d5  to White's 1.Nf3,  then you should be ready for the tricky ICBM  (Intercontinental Ballistic Missile)  Gambit, which is also known as the Tennison Gambit. The chess amateur Otto Mandrup Tennison played and analyzed this idea in the 1850s in New Orleans. }
2... dxe4
{ We don't hesitate for one moment and take the central pawn with tempo! } 3.
Ng5 Bf5
{ This is objectively best, but White is unlikely to enter the ICBM Gambit now, as  4.d3  doesn't make sense. }
4. Nc3 { The most common move and also played by GothamChess, IM Levy Rozman! }
4... Nf6 5. d3
{ I guess we can call it the delayed ICBM Gambit as GothamChess played it in a game in 2021. It may not be as bad as the original, but still White shouldn't get any compensation for the pawn. }
5... exd3 6. Qf3
{ Levy's tricky move.  6.Bxd3  Bxd3  7.cxd3  e6∓  is just a big edge for Black. White has nothing for the pawn. }
6... Qc8
{ Easy does it! Perhaps the most difficult move of this variation. Black protects both the f5-bishop and b7-pawn. }
7. Bxd3 Bxd3 8. Qxd3
{ White is still a pawn down, but Black is too solid to be in any trouble. }
8... Qd7 { Trades are good for us since we're up a pawn! } 9. Qf3 Qc6 10. Qg3
e6 11. Bd2 Nbd7 12. O-O-O h6
{ Black gets ready to castle long and kicks the knight away first. } 13. Nf3
O-O-O { Black is clearly better, as White has no compensation for the pawn. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "25) Monkey's Bum Gambit"]
[Black "Monkey's Bum Gambit 3.Qf3 e6 4.d4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 g6 2. Bc4 Bg7 3. Qf3
{ Yes, you may see this Scholar's Mate setup against the Modern Defense. It is the prelude to the Monkey's Bum Gambit. }
3... e6 { Why not, we just want to stop mate in one. } 4. d4
{ This dubious gambit is called the Monkey's Bum. Don't ask me how it's got its name. :@@EndBracket@@ But it is recommended by 'GingerGM' Simon Williams, and also IM Levy Rozman a.k.a GothamChess, who has played it at least 7 times and twice against GMs @@StartBracket@@in blitz of course!@@EndBracket@@. }
4... Bxd4 { Of course, we take the yummy central pawn! } 5. Ne2
{ White does get a tempo on the bishop, but we just retreat. } 5... Bg7 6. Nbc3
{ White's plan is to develop and wait for Black to castle so that Harry-the-h pawn can storm our castled king. }
6... Nc6 { We develop, with a simple idea to fork the queen and bishop. } 7.
Qg3 { This was seen in Rozman-Hakobyan, Titled Tuesday blitz game. } 7... d6 8.
Bg5 Nge7 9. O-O-O
{ White is first to castle, but Black is rock solid with no weaknesses. } 9...
Bd7
{ The GM goes for the solid choice.  9...a6!?  ,  with the idea ...b5, is interesting as well. }
10. h4 h6 { A good idea to kick this bishop. } 11. Be3 h5
{ I like this solid approach, don't give your opponent any play! } 12. Bg5 a6
13. f4 b5 14. Bb3
{ Here Black has two good choices:  14...f6  or  14...b4  . The GM chose the latter one. }
14... b4 15. f5
{ A speculative piece sac but the alternative is no better.  15.Na4  f6  wins a piece with no compensation for White. }
15... Be5 16. Qf2 bxc3 17. fxg6 cxb2+
{ Black went on to win the game:  18.Kb1  O-O!?  @@StartBracket@@  18...fxg6-+  @@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/2pbnp2/p1npp1P1/4b1Bp/4P2P/1B6/PpP1NQP1/1K1R3R w - - 2 19@@EndFEN@@  19.g7  Bxg7  20.Ng3  f6  21.Be3  Qe8  22.Qe2  Ne5-+  0-1 Rozman-Hakobyan, chess.com 2023. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "25) Monkey's Bum Gambit"]
[Black "Monkey's Bum Gambit 3.Qf3 e6 4.d4 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 g6 2. Bc4 Bg7 3. Qf3
{ Yes, you may see this Scholar's Mate setup against the Modern Defense. It is the prelude to the Monkey's Bum Gambit. }
3... e6 { Why not, we just want to stop mate in one. } 4. d4
{ This dubious gambit is called the Monkey's Bum. Don't ask me how it's got its name. :@@EndBracket@@ But it is recommended by 'GingerGM' Simon Williams, and also IM Levy Rozman a.k.a GothamChess, who has played it at least 7 times and twice against GMs @@StartBracket@@in blitz of course!@@EndBracket@@. }
4... Bxd4 { Of course, we take the yummy central pawn! } 5. Ne2
{ White does get a tempo on the bishop, but we just retreat. } 5... Bg7 6. Nbc3
{ White's plan is to develop and wait for Black to castle so that Harry-the-h pawn can storm our castled king. }
6... Nc6 { We develop, with a simple idea to fork the queen and bishop. } 7.
Bf4 Ne5 { Let's use the fork to win the bishop pair. } 8. Bxe5 Bxe5 9. O-O-O
{ White doesn't care about pawns or bishops, they only care about fast development. However, with simple play, I will show you how to refute White's setup. }
9... c6 { A funny idea, are we playing checkers? } 10. h4 b5
{ It's time for Black's snake, made out of pawns, to strike! } 11. Bb3 a5
{ The funny part is that Black is attacking with no pieces and the engine gives us a -2 advantage already! }
12. a3 a4 { Why not? } 13. Ba2 b4 14. axb4 Qb6
{ With a huge attack, as the b4-pawn is about to fall. Black's king is super safe on e8 for now. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "25) Monkey's Bum Gambit"]
[Black "Monkey's Bum Gambit 3.Qf3 e6 4.d4 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 g6 2. Bc4 Bg7 3. Qf3
{ Yes, you may see this Scholar's Mate setup against the Modern Defense. It is the prelude to the Monkey's Bum Gambit. }
3... e6 { Why not, we just want to stop mate in one. } 4. d4
{ This dubious gambit is called the Monkey's Bum. Don't ask me how it's got its name. :@@EndBracket@@ But it is recommended by 'GingerGM' Simon Williams, and also IM Levy Rozman a.k.a GothamChess, who has played it at least 7 times and twice against GMs @@StartBracket@@in blitz of course!@@EndBracket@@. }
4... Bxd4 { Of course, we take the yummy central pawn! } 5. Ne2
{ White does get a tempo on the bishop, but we just retreat. } 5... Bg7 6. Nbc3
{ White's plan is to develop and wait for Black to castle so that Harry-the-h pawn can storm our castled king. }
6... Nc6 { We develop, with a simple idea to fork the queen and bishop. } 7.
Bf4 Ne5 { Let's use the fork to win the bishop pair. } 8. Bxe5 Bxe5 9. O-O-O
{ White doesn't care about pawns or bishops, they only care about fast development. However, with simple play, I will show you how to refute White's setup. }
9... c6 { A funny idea, are we playing checkers? } 10. h4 b5
{ It's time for Black's snake, made out of pawns, to strike! } 11. Bb3 a5
{ The funny part is that Black is attacking with no pieces and the engine gives us a -2 advantage already! }
12. a4 { White tries to slow down our attack. } 12... b4
{ Pushing the knight all the way back. } 13. Nb1 Qf6
{ White is faced with a tough choice: trade queens or lose a 2nd pawn with check. Black is winning either way!   Conclusion: The Monkey's Bum Gambit should not deter you from playing the Modern @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq e3 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1…g6  but rather encourage you, especially if your opponent has a fondness for Scholar’s Mate. Take the free pawn  on d4 and grab the bishop pair while you’re at it with the  @@StartFEN@@rnbqk1nr/pppp1pbp/4p1p1/8/2B1P3/2N2Q2/PPP1NPPP/R1B1K2R b KQkq - 3 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Nc6  & @@StartFEN@@r1bqk1nr/pppp1pbp/2n1p1p1/8/2B1PB2/2N2Q2/PPP1NPPP/R3K2R b KQkq - 5 7@@EndFEN@@  7...Ne5  idea. Don’t worry about being behind in development,  as your wall of pawns will prevent any attack from White. Feel free to lash out with ...b5 & ...a5 once White castles queenside, and to attack at will! }
