[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "26) Blumenfeld Countergambit"]
[Black "Blumenfeld Countergambit 3...c5 4.d5 b5 5.Bf4 bxc4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6
{ This is the most common move order to reach the Blumenfeld Gambit as White avoids the Nimzo-Indian Defense  @@StartBracket@@  3.Nc3  Bb4  @@EndBracket@@ with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pppp1ppp/4pn2/8/2PP4/8/PP2PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nf3  .   2...c5  3.d5  e6  is the Benoni Defense move order.  4.Nf3  @@StartBracket@@  4.Nc3  is the more principled move, leading to the main line Benoni.@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pp1p1ppp/4pn2/2pP4/2P5/5N2/PP2PPPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 4@@EndFEN@@  4...b5  and we transpose to the Blumenfeld Gambit. }
3. Nf3 c5 4. d5 b5
{ This is the Blumenfeld Countergambit named after the Russian master Benjamin Blumenfeld @@StartBracket@@1884-1947@@EndBracket@@. Black sacrifices a wing pawn to get a superior pawn mass in the center. It's actually quite sound and, similarly to the Benko Gambit, I will advise you to avoid taking the pawn! }
5. Bf4
{ This is my recommendation and it is an extremely rare move with only 94 games in the DB. You are guaranteed to surprise your opponent, as it is only the 8th played move in this position. Compare that with the most common move  5.Bg5  , with over 2700 games played!  The idea is to go for rapid development and fight for initiative with a c4-pawn sacrifice.   5.dxe6  fxe6  6.cxb5  d5  is the main line. As you can see, Black's powerful center pawns give them a long-term initiative, something I prefer to avoid. }
5... bxc4 { Black grabs the pawn but gives White time to develop. } 6. Nc3
{ The pawn on c4 is a liability and will likely fall soon anyway. } 6... Qa5
{ Black pins the knight, setting up a threat to take on d5. But White has a nice regrouping in mind. }
7. Bd2
{ While it is a backward move, it now makes the queen on a5 very uncomfortable! }
7... Qb6 8. e4
{ White achieves the dream of a strong center and is ready to take on c4. }
8... Qxb2 { This is suicidal, as Black is losing too much time. } 9. Rb1 Qa3
10. Bxc4 Ba6 11. Nb5 Bxb5 12. Rxb5 { Ra5 next will trap Black's queen. } *

