{ This is my recommendation and it is an extremely rare move with only 94 games in the DB. You are guaranteed to surprise your opponent, as it is only the 8th played move in this position. Compare that with the most common move  5.Bg5  , with over 2700 games played!  The idea is to go for rapid development and fight for initiative with a c4-pawn sacrifice.   5.dxe6  fxe6  6.cxb5  d5  is the main line. As you can see, Black's powerful center pawns give them a long-term initiative, something I prefer to avoid. }
5... exd5 { Black's most common move. } 6. cxd5
{ White establishes a powerful pawn on d5 that paralyzes Black. But its friend, the e-pawn, is not far behind! The idea is to play e4 next! }
6... d6 7. e4
{ Just like against @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/p2p1ppp/5n2/1ppP4/5B2/5N2/PP2PPPP/RN1QKB1R b KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Bb7  , White executes the main idea. Development above pawns! }
7... a6
{ Black doesn't go pawn hunting and instead establishes a Benoni-like expansion on the queenside. }
8. a4 { White forces Black to make some concessions. } 8... b4 9. Nbd2
{ Now the c4-square is firmly in White's hands. White also maintains a nice space advantage thanks to the d5-e4 pawn combo. }
9... Be7 10. Bd3 O-O 11. O-O a5 12. Nc4
{ White has a clear long-term edge, while Black lacks a plan and doesn't have good squares for their pieces. }
