{ The Benko Gambit. This opening, named after the Hungarian-American GM Pal Benko, is actually very sound. For example, the world's best player, Magnus Carlsen, has played it at least 20 times in his career! Many 2700s have used it as a surprise weapon or in a must-win game.  Black's main point is to open up files on the queenside and fianchetto the bishop on g7, going for long-term compensation. Don't be surprised if Black even happily trades queens being a pawn down. That's how powerful this gambit really is!   Since this gambit is very sound, I will not try to refute it. Instead, I will propose a rare and underestimated queen move that goes for the central bind,  4.Qc2!?  , with the  idea to follow up with 5.e4. }
4. Qc2
{ White is ready to grab the center with 5.e4 next, most players won't be ready for it! So, we also have the element of surprise on our side!  4.cxb5  a6  is the main line. }
4... b4
{ Black grabs more space on the queenside but gives up full central control to White. }
5. e4
{ White creates a strong central bind. Black has to be careful as they can easily be suffocated here. }
5... d6 6. f4
{ Grabbing even more space. The game resembles the Benoni rather than the Benko. White goes for central play, while Black's plan is to undermine the center with ...e6. }
6... g6 7. Nf3 Bg7 8. Bd3 O-O 9. O-O Nbd7 10. h3
{ A useful move to prepare the e5 push.  10.e5?  is too early.  10...dxe5  11.fxe5  Ng4∓  and White will lose a pawn. }
10... e6 11. Be3 Bb7 12. Nbd2 Qc7 13. Rae1 { 13.f5!?  is an interesting try! }
13... Rae8 14. g4
{ Caruana is now playing White in an instructive Titled Tuesday blitz game. Black is under serious assault on the kingside. }
14... h6 15. Bf2
{ A clever regrouping! White opens up the rook to support the e5 push and the bishop may swing to h4 or g3. }
15... e5 16. f5
{ With total domination! Caruana went on to win the game in Caruana-Gelman, chess.com 2020. }
