[Black "Benko Gambit 3...b5 4.Qc2 bxc4 #6"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 b5
{ The Benko Gambit. This opening, named after the Hungarian-American GM Pal Benko, is actually very sound. For example, the world's best player, Magnus Carlsen, has played it at least 20 times in his career! Many 2700s have used it as a surprise weapon or in a must-win game.  Black's main point is to open up files on the queenside and fianchetto the bishop on g7, going for long-term compensation. Don't be surprised if Black even happily trades queens being a pawn down. That's how powerful this gambit really is!   Since this gambit is very sound, I will not try to refute it. Instead, I will propose a rare and underestimated queen move that goes for the central bind,  4.Qc2!?  , with the  idea to follow up with 5.e4. }
4. Qc2
{ White is ready to grab the center with 5.e4 next, most players won't be ready for it! So, we also have the element of surprise on our side!  4.cxb5  a6  is the main line. }
4... bxc4
{ This is the most common move. But now the sides are reversed, as White is playing in gambit style! }
5. e4
{ White achieves the objective of full central control. Please note the c4-pawn is so weak that White can pick it up pretty much at any point. }
5... e6 { Black immediately undermines the center. } 6. Nc3 exd5 7. e5
{ The key move! White is fighting for initiative at all costs, even though we are two pawns down at the moment. }
7... Ng4
{ Black's knight is attacking the e5-pawn. This move was played by a former top 10, GM Bareev. }
8. Nxd5 Nxe5 { Black's best move is to grab material. } 9. Qe4
{ White's queen is putting serious pressure in many directions. } 9... d6
{ The only move! } 10. Bf4
{ I like this simple developing move, inviting Black to play ...f5.   10.f4?  f5  11.Qe2  Be6  , @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/p4ppp/3p4/2pNn3/2p1Q3/8/PP3PPP/R1B1KBNR w KQkq - 0 10@@EndFEN@@  10.Nc7+?  Qxc7  11.Qxa8  Nec6  , but @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/p4ppp/3p4/2pNn3/2p1Q3/8/PP3PPP/R1B1KBNR w KQkq - 0 10@@EndFEN@@  10.Nf3!?  is interesting as well. }
10... f5 11. Qe3 { Keeping the pin alive. } 11... Nc6
{ This natural move is a serious mistake.  11...Qa5+!  is the only try to stay in the game. After  12.Nc3  Nbc6  13.O-O-O  , White gets a promising attack, but the game is still quite complex. }
12. O-O-O
{ White is quick to develop, while the other monarch is still stuck. Here's how the game may unfold:  12...Qa5  13.Nf3!  Who cares  about the a2-pawn?  13...Qxa2  14.Bxe5!  Nxe5  15.Nxe5  dxe5  16.Qxe5+  .  As my friend, GM Jesse Kraai, likes to say: "Check to the miserable king!".  16...Kf7  17.Be2  Qa1+  18.Kc2  Qa4+  19.Kb1  Bb7  20.Qxf5+  Ke8  21.Nc7+  Ke7  22.Qe6  is a nice checkmate! }
