{ This is called the Budapest Gambit. It's not a bad gambit and most players as White don't expect it, given how rare it is. However, I will show you a simple plan for neutralizing this tricky gambit to guarantee White a nice long-term edge. }
3. dxe5 { The most principled! } 3... Ne4
{ The so-called Fajarowicz Variation. It is less sound than the main line, but tricky nevertheless. }
4. a3
{ This is the most difficult move to remember! Believe it or not, this quiet pawn move is the best line! It's important to take away the ...Bb4+ option from Black.   4.Nf3  Bb4+  @@StartBracket@@  4...d6!?  5.exd6  Bxd6  ,  hoping for a natural g3 move, which loses the game on the spot!  6.g3?  Nxf2!  7.Kxf2  Bxg3+-+  and White drops the queen.@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/pppp1ppp/8/4P3/1bP1n3/5N2/PP2PPPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 3 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Nbd2  Nc6  is what Black wants. Eventually, White will drop  the e5-pawn. }
4... b6 { A sneaky move, hoping White will play Qd5. } 5. Nf3
{ White should go for simple development.  5.Qd5?!  walks right into Black's idea:  5...Nc5!  6.Qxa8  Bb7  7.Qxa7  Nc6  , trapping White's queen:  8.Qxb7  Nxb7∓  . }
5... Bb7 6. g3
{ Don't be afraid of the b7-bishop! White is getting ready to fianchetto with Bg2 and O-O next. }
6... Bc5 7. e3 { The only move but an easy one to make. } 7... a5 8. Bg2 Ng5 9.
Nbd2
{ White overprotects the f3-knight and gets ready to castle next.  9.O-O  is fine too.  9...Nxf3+  10.Bxf3  Bxf3  11.Qxf3  Nc6  and  the e5-pawn falls but White should still remain better. }
9... O-O 10. O-O Nxf3+ 11. Nxf3 Nc6 12. b3
{ A natural plan is to go for a double fianchetto with b3 and Bb2 next. } 12...
Qe7 13. Bb2
{ White has finished development and stands clearly better. Black doesn't have full compensation for the pawn. White will connect the rooks next with Qc2. }
