1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e5
{ This is called the Budapest Gambit. It's not a bad gambit and most players as White don't expect it, given how rare it is. However, I will show you a simple plan for neutralizing this tricky gambit to guarantee White a nice long-term edge. }
3. dxe5 { The most principled! } 3... Ng4 4. Nf3
{ This is the solid variation, I like it because it makes it very difficult for Black to obtain any activity. }
4... Bc5 { 4...Nc6  5.Nc3  Bc5  6.e3  will transpose. } 5. e3 Nc6 6. Nc3
{ White is happy to give back the e5-pawn in return for fast development. }
6... O-O { Black plays in the gambit spirit, delaying capturing the pawn. } 7.
Be2 { White offers the pawn back again. } 7... Re8 8. Nd2
{ This is the key idea to fight for a big edge. With only 6 games in the DB, White scores 90%!  8.O-O  has been played almost 300 times.  8...Ngxe5  9.Nxe5  Nxe5  , with a slight edge for White. }
8... Ngxe5 9. Nde4 { White centralizes the knight and attacks the bishop. }
9... Bf8 10. b3
{ White goes for natural development for the c1-bishop.  10.f4!?  is an interesting idea as well! }
10... d6 11. Bb2 Qh4 { This was seen in a GM game: Vitiugov-Shimanov, 2015. }
12. Ng3 Be6 13. Qd2 { White keeps the options open where to castle! } 13... f5
14. Nd5
{ The nice central outpost on d5 makes Black's position strategically suspicious. }
14... Rac8 15. O-O
{ A natural move and a strong novelty, there's no need to push the f-pawn yet for White.  15.f4  Ng4  16.Bxg4  Qxg4  17.O-O⩲  1-0 Vitiugov-Shimanov, Jerusalem 2015. }
15... Ng4 16. h3 Nge5 17. Rae1 { White brings the last piece into the fight. }
17... Nd8 18. e4 { Time to open up the game! } 18... fxe4 19. Bh5
{ Inducing the ...g6 weakness. } 19... g6 20. Rxe4
{ And just like that, Black is losing the queen! The game is over.   Conclusion: Remember to meet the tricky Fajarowicz Variation @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pppp1ppp/5n2/4P3/2P5/8/PP2PPPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Ne4  with the quiet pawn move  4.a3!  Black has several ways to try to confuse you, but White is better in all lines for sure!  The main line Budapest @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pppp1ppp/5n2/4P3/2P5/8/PP2PPPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Ng4  typically results in Black winning the pawn  back on e5. However, don’t worry about that and focus on development. Remember the key and unusual  @@StartFEN@@r1bqr1k1/pppp1ppp/2n5/2b1P3/2P3n1/2N1PN2/PP2BPPP/R1BQK2R w KQ - 5 8@@EndFEN@@  8.Nd2!?  idea, to transfer the knight to e4.  The dark-squared bishop typically gets fianchettoed on b2 and together with the control of the weak d5-outpost, this gives us a nice long-term advantage. }
