[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "29) Albin Countergambit"]
[Black "Albin Countergambit 1.d4 d5 2.c4 e5 − 5...Bg4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e5
{ This is the Albin Countergambit, named after Adolf Albin, who played it vs. Emmanuel Lasker in a New York tournament in 1893. It is a sound gambit and was played with good success by a former top-10 player, Alexander Morozevich. Black's idea is to sacrifice the e5-pawn to open up the game and go for rapid development. Accuracy is required here from White. }
3. dxe5 { We take the pawn! } 3... d4
{ Black gains some space and hopes to play around the e5-pawn or to win it back later. }
4. Nf3 Nc6 5. Nbd2
{ This is only the third most popular move behind  5.a3  and  5.g3  , but I like it, as White has a very simple plan to  play Nb3xd4 next. }
5... Bg4
{ Another typical way to develop for Black. They may try to castle long at the right moment with ...Qd7 & ...O-O-O. }
6. h3 { Let's ask the bishop a question: on which diagonal would you stay? }
6... Bxf3 { Surprisingly, giving up the bishop pair is best. } 7. Nxf3 Bb4+ 8.
Bd2 Qe7 { Black protects the bishop and gets ready to castle. } 9. g3
{ The simplest. White will fianchetto the bishop and castle kingside. Please note that without the light-squared bishop, Black can't generate an attack. }
9... O-O-O 10. Bg2 Nxe5
{ Black wins back the pawn, but White's strong g2-bishop should still give us an advantage. }
11. O-O Bxd2 12. Nxd2
{ The opening is over and I prefer White. We have a strong bishop on g2, eyeing b7, and potential for a quick queenside attack with Qa4 & Nb3. Black is lacking any counterplay here.   The game may continue  12...Nf6  13.Qa4  ,  hitting a7.  13...Kb8  14.Nb3  , the knight joins the attack.  14...h5  15.Na5!  c6  16.f4!  , kicking back the knight.  16...Ng6  17.Nxc6+!  , the start of a beautiful combination:  17...bxc6  18.Qxc6  . Just look how powerful White's control on this long diagonal is!  18...h4  19.Qa8+  Kc7  20.Qb7+  Kd6  21.Qc6#  , checkmate! }
*

