[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e5
{ This is the Albin Countergambit, named after Adolf Albin, who played it vs. Emmanuel Lasker in a New York tournament in 1893. It is a sound gambit and was played with good success by a former top-10 player, Alexander Morozevich. Black's idea is to sacrifice the e5-pawn to open up the game and go for rapid development. Accuracy is required here from White. }
3. dxe5 { We take the pawn! } 3... d4
{ Black gains some space and hopes to play around the e5-pawn or to win it back later. }
4. Nf3 Nc6 5. Nbd2
{ This is only the third most popular move behind  5.a3  and  5.g3  , but I like it, as White has a very simple plan to  play Nb3xd4 next. }
5... Bg4
{ Another typical way to develop for Black. They may try to castle long at the right moment with ...Qd7 & ...O-O-O. }
6. h3 { Let's ask the bishop a question: on which diagonal would you stay? }
6... Be6 7. a3
{ I like this slightly unusual but thematic idea to play for b4. } 7... Nge7 8.
b4 Ng6 9. Bb2
{ White is putting lots of pressure on the d4-pawn that will fall shortly. }
9... a5 10. b5 Ncxe5 11. Nxd4
{ Black is still down a pawn and it's tempting to take on c4, but... } 11...
Nxc4 12. Nxc4 Bxc4 13. Qc2 Bd5
{ Believe it or not, here White has many moves that lead to a +2 or more advantage. Here's one possible idea: }
14. h4 { 14.O-O-O  is quite good as well. } 14... Nxh4
{ Black grabs the pawn. } 15. Rh3
{ A remarkable idea to activate the rook. The attack on Black's king begins! }
15... Be7 16. e4 Be6 17. Nxe6 fxe6 18. Rd1 { A nice tempo on the queen. } 18...
Qc8 19. Bxg7 Rg8 20. Be5 { A sad reality, Black is just lost. } 20... Nxg2+ 21.
Bxg2 Rxg2 22. Rxh7 Rg1+ 23. Ke2 Rxd1 24. Qxd1
{ The dust has settled and Black is totally lost here. } *

