[Round "?"]
[White "29) Albin Countergambit"]
[Black "Albin Countergambit 1.d4 d5 2.c4 e5 − 5...Nge7 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e5
{ This is the Albin Countergambit, named after Adolf Albin, who played it vs. Emmanuel Lasker in a New York tournament in 1893. It is a sound gambit and was played with good success by a former top-10 player, Alexander Morozevich. Black's idea is to sacrifice the e5-pawn to open up the game and go for rapid development. Accuracy is required here from White. }
3. dxe5 { We take the pawn! } 3... d4
{ Black gains some space and hopes to play around the e5-pawn or to win it back later. }
4. Nf3 Nc6 5. Nbd2
{ This is only the third most popular move behind  5.a3  and  5.g3  , but I like it, as White has a very simple plan to  play Nb3xd4 next. }
5... Nge7
{ Black's best and most popular move. The knight is either heading to g6 to hit e5, mirroring White's idea, or ...Nf5 to protect d4. }
6. Nb3 Ng6
{ I believe this is Black's best move, but it is less common than  7...Nf5  . }
7. Nbxd4 Ngxe5 8. Nxe5 Nxe5
{ 8...Nxd4?  leads to a bad endgame, for example,  9.e3!  Ne6  10.Qxd8+  Nxd8  11.Bd2±  , when White will enjoy converting the extra pawn. }
9. e3
{ A solid move, White is planning for simple development next: Be2 and O-O. }
9... c5 10. Nb5 Qxd1+ 11. Kxd1 Bg4+
{ Black gets to play a few tempo moves with check, but there's no danger to White's king. }
12. f3 O-O-O+ 13. Kc2 Bf5+ 14. e4
{ White's king is safe, while Black has no compensation for the pawn. } *

