1. d4 d5 2. c4 e5
{ This is the Albin Countergambit, named after Adolf Albin, who played it vs. Emmanuel Lasker in a New York tournament in 1893. It is a sound gambit and was played with good success by a former top-10 player, Alexander Morozevich. Black's idea is to sacrifice the e5-pawn to open up the game and go for rapid development. Accuracy is required here from White. }
3. dxe5 { We take the pawn! } 3... d4
{ Black gains some space and hopes to play around the e5-pawn or to win it back later. }
4. Nf3 Nc6 5. Nbd2
{ This is only the third most popular move behind  5.a3  and  5.g3  , but I like it, as White has a very simple plan to  play Nb3xd4 next. }
5... Nge7
{ Black's best and most popular move. The knight is either heading to g6 to hit e5, mirroring White's idea, or ...Nf5 to protect d4. }
6. Nb3 Nf5
{ The is the most common move, but I believe White should get an edge here. }
7. e4 { A strong move! White forces the endgame, maintaining the extra pawn. }
7... dxe3 8. Qxd8+ Nxd8 9. fxe3
{ It's true that White has a set of doubled e-pawns, but don't forget that one of them is extra! It's not easy for Black to win even one of these pawns. }
9... Be7
{ This move was seen in the Super-GM blitz game Grischuk-Nepo in 2018. } 10.
Nbd4
{ A stronger move than Grischuk's  10.Bd3  . White is centralizing the knight and doesn't mind the trade, as that would undouble the pawns. }
10... O-O { 10...Nxd4?  11.exd4+- } 11. Bd2
{ 11.Bd3  is good as well.   White gets ready to castle long with a nice edge. For example:  11...Nh4  12.O-O-O  Ng6  13.Bd3  Re8  14.Bc3  Bf8  15.Bc2!  A clever move, as Black can't take on e5.  15...Bg4  @@StartBracket@@  15...Nxe5  16.Nxe5  Rxe5  17.Nb5!+-  and Black will lose more material.@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@r2nrbk1/ppp2ppp/6n1/4P3/2PN2b1/2B1PN2/PPB3PP/2KR3R w - - 13 16@@EndFEN@@  16.h3!  Bxf3  17.Nxf3±  , White's extra pawns and the bishop pair give us a nice long-term edge. }
