[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "29) Albin Countergambit"]
[Black "Albin Countergambit 1.d4 d5 2.c4 e5 − 5...Nge7 #8"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e5
{ This is the Albin Countergambit, named after Adolf Albin, who played it vs. Emmanuel Lasker in a New York tournament in 1893. It is a sound gambit and was played with good success by a former top-10 player, Alexander Morozevich. Black's idea is to sacrifice the e5-pawn to open up the game and go for rapid development. Accuracy is required here from White. }
3. dxe5 { We take the pawn! } 3... d4
{ Black gains some space and hopes to play around the e5-pawn or to win it back later. }
4. Nf3 Nc6 5. Nbd2
{ This is only the third most popular move behind  5.a3  and  5.g3  , but I like it, as White has a very simple plan to  play Nb3xd4 next. }
5... Nge7
{ Black's best and most popular move. The knight is either heading to g6 to hit e5, mirroring White's idea, or ...Nf5 to protect d4. }
6. Nb3 Nf5
{ The is the most common move, but I believe White should get an edge here. }
7. e4 { A strong move! White forces the endgame, maintaining the extra pawn. }
7... dxe3 8. Qxd8+ Nxd8 9. fxe3
{ It's true that White has a set of doubled e-pawns, but don't forget that one of them is extra! It's not easy for Black to win even one of these pawns. }
9... Bb4+ { The most common move, accuracy is required from White. } 10. Kf2
{ 10.Bd2?!  allows Black to win the pawn back:  10...Nxe3!  11.Bxb4  Nc2+  12.Kd2  Nxb4=  . }
10... O-O 11. g4 { White grabs some space and pushes the knight back. } 11...
Nh6 { 11...Ne7?  12.a3!+-  traps the bishop! } 12. h3
{ White has a very stable advantage and controls all the key squares. Black has to be careful, as the b4-bishop and h6-knight are short of squares. For example  12...Be7?  13.g5!  Nf5  14.e4+-  and just like that,  the knight on f5 is trapped.  Conclusion: The Albin Countergambit is a must-know gambit for all the 1.d4 players. While it’s rare in tournament practice, the fact that the center opens up so fast may be uncomfortable for positional players.  Luckily, White has a very simple setup with Nbd2-b3 and going after the d4-pawn. The point is simple: White happily trades the e5-pawn for Black’s ...d4 push, establishing a strong knight in the middle of the board. This gives us a nice long-term edge. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "30) Von Hennig-Schara Gambit"]
[Black "Von Hennig-Schara Gambit 3...c5 4.cxd5 cxd4 5.Qa4+ Nd7"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 c5
{ This is the Tarrasch Defense move order. Black immediately strikes in the center, trying to liquidate as many pawns as possible. }
4. cxd5 cxd4
{ This is the Von Hennig-Schara Gambit. It is much less popular than the main line of the Tarrasch Defense 4... exd5, however, recently powerful engines showed that this gambit is totally sound. No wonder, even the best player in the world, Magnus Carlsen, played it in a classical game vs. Sam Shankland in Tata Steel, 2022. Now, many 2700+ players play this gambit regularly. }
5. Qa4+
{ I recommend inserting this check, forcing Black's bishop or knight onto a bad square.   After  5.Qxd4  Nc6  , White's queen is under attack and we would have to move it, losing a vital tempo.  6.Qd1  exd5  7.Qxd5  Bd6!  This is the modern way to play for Black. They get fast mobility and clear compensation for the pawn. }
5... Nd7 6. Qxd4
{ 6.dxe6  fails to  6...dxc3  7.exd7+  Bxd7  8.Qe4+  Be7  9.bxc3  Nf6  , when White is utterly underdeveloped and even nearly lost despite the extra pawn. }
6... exd5
{ After  6...e5  7.Qa4  , White gets a big edge, as Black doesn't have anything for the pawn. }
7. Nxd5 Ne7 8. Nf3 Nxd5 9. Qxd5
{ White has a pleasant edge. The more trades, the bigger White's advantage since we're up a pawn. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "30) Von Hennig-Schara Gambit"]
[Black "Von Hennig-Schara Gambit 3...c5 4.cxd5 cxd4 5.Qa4+ Bd7 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 c5
{ This is the Tarrasch Defense move order. Black immediately strikes in the center, trying to liquidate as many pawns as possible. }
4. cxd5 cxd4
{ This is the Von Hennig-Schara Gambit. It is much less popular than the main line of the Tarrasch Defense 4... exd5, however, recently powerful engines showed that this gambit is totally sound. No wonder, even the best player in the world, Magnus Carlsen, played it in a classical game vs. Sam Shankland in Tata Steel, 2022. Now, many 2700+ players play this gambit regularly. }
5. Qa4+
{ I recommend inserting this check, forcing Black's bishop or knight onto a bad square.   After  5.Qxd4  Nc6  , White's queen is under attack and we would have to move it, losing a vital tempo.  6.Qd1  exd5  7.Qxd5  Bd6!  This is the modern way to play for Black. They get fast mobility and clear compensation for the pawn. }
5... Bd7 { This is the best move by far. } 6. Qxd4 exd5
{ White now has an option: to win the pawn or continue developing. } 7. Qxd5
{ The most principled approach if you want to come close to refuting the gambit!   7.Nf3  doesn't promise White any edge, but at least the game is less theoretical. For example  7...Nf6  8.Bg5  Nc6  9.Qd3  h6!  10.Bh4  and now Black can even play for an edge:  10...Bb4!  11.e3  g5!  12.Bg3  Ne4  .  The pressure on the c3-knight is really annoying.  13.Rc1  Bf5  14.Qd1  h5∓  , with a  big threat of ...h4. White is under a lot of pressure. }
7... Nc6 { This is the 'old theory'. } 8. Nf3 Nf6 9. Qb3 Bc5 10. Bg5
{ I prefer this simple plan to get the bishop outside the pawn chain, as it scores over 70% in my Mega Database, but  10.e3!?  is also strong and preferred by Stockfish. }
10... O-O 11. e3 { White enjoys a nice edge here. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "30) Von Hennig-Schara Gambit"]
[Black "Von Hennig-Schara Gambit 3...c5 4.cxd5 cxd4 5.Qa4+ Bd7 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 c5
{ This is the Tarrasch Defense move order. Black immediately strikes in the center, trying to liquidate as many pawns as possible. }
4. cxd5 cxd4
{ This is the Von Hennig-Schara Gambit. It is much less popular than the main line of the Tarrasch Defense 4... exd5, however, recently powerful engines showed that this gambit is totally sound. No wonder, even the best player in the world, Magnus Carlsen, played it in a classical game vs. Sam Shankland in Tata Steel, 2022. Now, many 2700+ players play this gambit regularly. }
5. Qa4+
{ I recommend inserting this check, forcing Black's bishop or knight onto a bad square.   After  5.Qxd4  Nc6  , White's queen is under attack and we would have to move it, losing a vital tempo.  6.Qd1  exd5  7.Qxd5  Bd6!  This is the modern way to play for Black. They get fast mobility and clear compensation for the pawn. }
5... Bd7 { This is the best move by far. } 6. Qxd4 exd5
{ White now has an option: to win the pawn or continue developing. } 7. Qxd5
{ The most principled approach if you want to come close to refuting the gambit!   7.Nf3  doesn't promise White any edge, but at least the game is less theoretical. For example  7...Nf6  8.Bg5  Nc6  9.Qd3  h6!  10.Bh4  and now Black can even play for an edge:  10...Bb4!  11.e3  g5!  12.Bg3  Ne4  .  The pressure on the c3-knight is really annoying.  13.Rc1  Bf5  14.Qd1  h5∓  , with a  big threat of ...h4. White is under a lot of pressure. }
7... Nf6
{ This is the fresh take on the position, played by none other than Magnus Carlsen. The point is to keep the knight on b8, where it could go to a6-c5 or a6-b4 in the future. }
8. Qb3
{ After  8.Qxb7  Nc6  9.Qb3  Rb8  , Black gets unnecessary compensation, which is something we'd like to avoid. }
8... Na6
{ A plan demonstrated in the Shankland-Carlsen, 2022 game. The knight may now jump to b4 or c5. }
9. Nf3 Nc5 { A nice tempo move, hitting the queen. } 10. Qc2 Rc8
{ Black keeps putting pressure on White's queen. } 11. e3
{ 11.Bg5?  Na4⩱  gives Black an edge already! } 11... Nce4
{ Black puts pressure on the c3-knight. This is considered the best move, according to modern engines, and is Carlsen's choice. }
12. Bd3 Nxc3 13. bxc3 Bb4
{ Tempting, but here White should abandon the c3-pawn! } 14. O-O Bxc3
{ 14...Rxc3  is worse since after  15.Qb1  Be7  16.Bb2  Rc8  17.Rd1  ,  White's pieces are very active. Now Black has to take care of potential tricks on the d-file, while Bd4 and Ne5 are valid ideas as well. }
15. Rb1 b6
{ This is already trouble for Black.  15...O-O  16.Ba3⩲  , with small pressure. }
16. Rb3 Bb4 17. Qb1 Bc5 18. e4
{ White is first to start the attack. Black will lose at least a pawn if they castle now. }
18... O-O 19. e5 { And the h7-pawn falls. } *

