5. Qa4+
{ I recommend inserting this check, forcing Black's bishop or knight onto a bad square.   After  5.Qxd4  Nc6  , White's queen is under attack and we would have to move it, losing a vital tempo.  6.Qd1  exd5  7.Qxd5  Bd6!  This is the modern way to play for Black. They get fast mobility and clear compensation for the pawn. }
5... Bd7 { This is the best move by far. } 6. Qxd4 exd5
{ White now has an option: to win the pawn or continue developing. } 7. Qxd5
{ The most principled approach if you want to come close to refuting the gambit!   7.Nf3  doesn't promise White any edge, but at least the game is less theoretical. For example  7...Nf6  8.Bg5  Nc6  9.Qd3  h6!  10.Bh4  and now Black can even play for an edge:  10...Bb4!  11.e3  g5!  12.Bg3  Ne4  .  The pressure on the c3-knight is really annoying.  13.Rc1  Bf5  14.Qd1  h5∓  , with a  big threat of ...h4. White is under a lot of pressure. }
7... Nf6
{ This is the fresh take on the position, played by none other than Magnus Carlsen. The point is to keep the knight on b8, where it could go to a6-c5 or a6-b4 in the future. }
8. Qb3
{ After  8.Qxb7  Nc6  9.Qb3  Rb8  , Black gets unnecessary compensation, which is something we'd like to avoid. }
8... Na6
{ A plan demonstrated in the Shankland-Carlsen, 2022 game. The knight may now jump to b4 or c5. }
9. Nf3 Nc5 { A nice tempo move, hitting the queen. } 10. Qc2 Rc8
{ Black keeps putting pressure on White's queen. } 11. e3
{ 11.Bg5?  Na4⩱  gives Black an edge already! } 11... Nce4
{ Black puts pressure on the c3-knight. This is considered the best move, according to modern engines, and is Carlsen's choice. }
12. Bd3 Nxc3 13. bxc3 Nd5
{ Magnus attacks the c3-pawn now but also keeps the ...Nb4 idea in mind. } 14.
O-O
{ I like this practical decision from Sam Shankland to give up the c3-pawn. As you see many times in my course, often the side with an extra pawn gives it up for faster development! }
14... Nxc3 15. Nd4
{ This is my novelty, trying to improve on Sam's play. The idea is quick centralizing play. Black now has to be careful to avoid getting into trouble.   15.Bb2  Bb4  16.Bxc3  Bxc3  17.Rab1  Bf6  18.Qe2  Rc7=  and the game was eventually drawn in Shankland-Carlsen, Wijk aan Zee 2022. Black's bishop pair clearly is not inferior to White's B+N.   15.Qb3!?  is another interesting try. For example  15...Ba4  16.Qxb7  Bc6  17.Qa6  Bxf3  18.gxf3  Bd6  , with complex play as in the game Santos Latasa-Dragnev, Vrnjacka Banja 2023. }
15... Bb4 { 15...Bd6  16.Nf5!  is an annoying fork. } 16. Qb3 Qe7 17. a3 Bd6
{ Now White has a choice between the ambitious  18.Qxb7  or the calm  18.Bd2  .   17...Ba5  18.Qxb7± }
18. Bd2
{ 18.Qxb7!?  is also interesting.   After  18...Na4  19.Qxb7  Nc5  20.Qb1  Rb8  21.Qc2  Ba4  22.Qc4±  , with some accurate defense, White maintains the extra pawn.   Also,  18...Ba4  just loses after  19.Qb2  , when we keep  the threat of Bxc3 while Nf5 is something Black must consider as well. }
