{ The best move. } 25. Qa5
{ White keeps playing tempo moves. Notice how the h8-rook is just a silent observer. }
25... Bc8 26. Bc4
{ White has nice compensation and a clear attack. Let me show you how easy it is for Black to go wrong:  26...h6?  27.Ne6!  A deadly discovery!  27...Bxe6  28.Bxe7  Rxc4  29.Bxf6  gxf6  30.Qxa7+-  and White should convert the extra queen.   Conclusion: The Von Hennig-Schara Gambit is totally sound, but we can still pose some problems for Black with my novelty @@StartFEN@@2rqkb1r/pp1b1ppp/8/8/8/2nBPN2/P1Q2PPP/R1B2RK1 w k - 0 15@@EndFEN@@  15.Nd4!Ν  , which is an improvement on the Shankland-Carlsen game. Even if your opponent is booked up, they will be surprised and will have to solve practical problems over the board. Black often has to walk into a boring endgame or risk their king getting exposed as shown in the main line  with Nf5 and Nd6+. White will have all the fun! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "31) Blackmar-Diemer Gambit"]
[Black "Blackmar-Diemer Gambit 2.e4 dxe4 3.f3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. e4 { White gives up the central pawn. } 2... dxe4
{ Of course, we take it if we want to try to refute this gambit! } 3. f3
{ The invention of New Orleans player Armand Blackmar in the early 1900s. But it's not as good as inserting  3.Nc3  first. }
3... e5 { Black uses the tempo to blow up White's center! } 4. fxe4
{ White falls into a well-known trap that everyone should know! } 4... Qh4+
{ White now has an unpleasant choice: move the king or play an automatic g3. }
5. g3
{ After  5.Kd2  , many moves give Black a big edge, but the simplest is  5...Nf6-+  . White's king is just too weak. }
5... Qxe4+ { The point! White now loses the rook and the game. } *

