5. fxe4 { This is the most common move you will see here. } 5... Nxe4
{ It's natural to take with the knight to retain the strong light-squared bishop. }
6. Qf3
{ White's best option, trying to put pressure on our minor pieces while x-raying the b7-pawn. }
6... Nxc3
{ Black's best move, giving White several options on which piece to capture.  6...Nd6  instead is less precise, as it allows White to hope for compensation after  7.Bf4  e6  8.O-O-O  . }
7. Qxf5
{ The most tempting since now Black's knight looks a bit stranded. However... }
7... e6 { A nice tempo move on the queen, which also activates the f8-bishop. }
8. Qd3 { White hits the knight and tries to use the b5-square for the queen. }
8... Nd5 9. Qb5+
{ A tempting check to win the b7-pawn. This is exactly what we want our opponent to do, as we have a little surprise ready! }
9... Nc6 { Please take the free pawn... } 10. Qxb7
{ White takes the bait, unaware of the dangers. } 10... Bb4+ 11. c3 Nxd4
{ What an awesome shot! Definitely a good one to remember and show to your friends! Black wins in all lines now. }
12. cxb4 Nc2+ { The simplest, but  12...Qh4+!  is crushing as well. } 13. Kf2
O-O
{ We finish development and just want to take on a1. Again,  13...Qh4+  works as well, but  13...Nxa1  also wins. }
14. Rb1 Qh4+ 15. g3 Qd4+
{ White is getting crushed here, as they have zero development. For example  16.Kg2  Ne1+  17.Kh3  h5  ,  threatening mate in one, ...Qg4#.  18.Be2  Qe4-+  and Black will win one of the rooks, with a deadly attack. }
