[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "32) Staunton Gambit"]
[Black "Staunton Gambit 1.d4 f5 2.e4 − 5.Bxf6"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5 2. e4
{ This gambit was invented by Howard Staunton, one of the world's strongest players in the mid-1800s. White sacrifices the central pawn for rapid development. However, with accurate play, Black should be able to neutralize this gambit. Objectively, White's compensation is only enough for equality. }
2... fxe4 { We accept the gambit! } 3. Nc3 Nf6
{ So far natural moves from both sides. Black protects the e4-pawn. } 4. Bg5
Nc6
{ Black is seeking a fight and invites White to push the pawn with tempo. I like this line more than ...g6 since it spices up the game!   4...g6  is a safer move, with lots of theory.  4...d5?  is a known blunder! After  5.Bxf6  exf6  6.Qh5+±  ,  White will win the d5-pawn with an edge. }
5. Bxf6 exf6 6. Nxe4
{ A tempting idea to win back the pawn, but White will lose material. } 6...
Qe7 7. Qe2
{ The only move not to lose the knight due to the pin, but it drops the d4-pawn. }
7... Nxd4 8. Qd3 d5 9. Qxd4 Qxe4+ 10. Qxe4+ dxe4
{ Two bishops and an extra pawn should be easily winning for Black. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "32) Staunton Gambit"]
[Black "Staunton Gambit 1.d4 f5 2.e4 − 5.d5 Ne5 6.Qe2 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5 2. e4
{ This gambit was invented by Howard Staunton, one of the world's strongest players in the mid-1800s. White sacrifices the central pawn for rapid development. However, with accurate play, Black should be able to neutralize this gambit. Objectively, White's compensation is only enough for equality. }
2... fxe4 { We accept the gambit! } 3. Nc3 Nf6
{ So far natural moves from both sides. Black protects the e4-pawn. } 4. Bg5
Nc6
{ Black is seeking a fight and invites White to push the pawn with tempo. I like this line more than ...g6 since it spices up the game!   4...g6  is a safer move, with lots of theory.  4...d5?  is a known blunder! After  5.Bxf6  exf6  6.Qh5+±  ,  White will win the d5-pawn with an edge. }
5. d5 { White's best move, gaining space with a tempo on the knight. } 5... Ne5
{ Here, White's most popular moves are  6.Qd4  and  6.Qe2  , getting ready to castle long. }
6. Qe2
{ A popular but unusual queen move. White gets ready to castle long but blocks the light-squared bishop. }
6... Nf7 { Black immediately attacks the bishop on g5. } 7. h4 c6
{ The key idea to remember, and the only move to fight for the edge! All other moves are much worse for Black. Black forces the trade of White's last central pawn. }
8. O-O-O cxd5 9. Nxd5 Nxd5 10. Rxd5 b5
{ I like this pawn sacrifice to open up the queenside.  10...b6  is fine too. }
11. Qxb5 { 11.Rxb5?  Ba6 } 11... a6 12. Qb3 Nxg5 13. hxg5 e6
{ Black opens up the queen with tempo. Now both the rook and g5-pawn are hit. }
14. Re5 d5
{ A funny position. Have you ever seen a rook trapped in the center of the board like this? White is already lost, as ...Bd6 is next. }
15. g6 { A desperate attempt to free the rook. } 15... h6
{ 15...Qa5!  is also strong and winning. } 16. Qa4+ Bd7 17. Qd4 Be7
{ A strong novelty! Black stops the Qxd5 threat due to the pin and gets ready to castle next.   17...Qf6?  was played in a Titled Tuesday blitz game, but it's a blunder due to  18.Qxd5  and Black loses all the edge. }
18. Nh3 O-O 19. Rh5 { 19.Be2  Bf6-+  , with a winning game. } 19... Bf6
{ With a winning attack since White is playing without most of their pieces. }
