[White "32) Staunton Gambit"]
[Black "Staunton Gambit 1.d4 f5 2.e4 − 5.d5 Ne5 6.Qe2 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5 2. e4
{ This gambit was invented by Howard Staunton, one of the world's strongest players in the mid-1800s. White sacrifices the central pawn for rapid development. However, with accurate play, Black should be able to neutralize this gambit. Objectively, White's compensation is only enough for equality. }
2... fxe4 { We accept the gambit! } 3. Nc3 Nf6
{ So far natural moves from both sides. Black protects the e4-pawn. } 4. Bg5
Nc6
{ Black is seeking a fight and invites White to push the pawn with tempo. I like this line more than ...g6 since it spices up the game!   4...g6  is a safer move, with lots of theory.  4...d5?  is a known blunder! After  5.Bxf6  exf6  6.Qh5+±  ,  White will win the d5-pawn with an edge. }
5. d5 { White's best move, gaining space with a tempo on the knight. } 5... Ne5
{ Here, White's most popular moves are  6.Qd4  and  6.Qe2  , getting ready to castle long. }
6. Qe2
{ A popular but unusual queen move. White gets ready to castle long but blocks the light-squared bishop. }
6... Nf7 { Black immediately attacks the bishop on g5. } 7. Bxf6 exf6
{ This is the correct move, even though it opens up our king. You will see that the threats on the e-file are harmless. }
8. Nxe4 Bb4+
{ I like to insert this check to weaken up White's queenside where the king wants to castle.   8...Be7?  Hikaru played this natural move in blitz, but it's a mistake.  9.d6!  cxd6  10.O-O-O⩲  , with an edge for White as seen in Dobrov-Nakamura, chess.com 2019. }
9. c3 Be7
{ Now the bishop returns. You will see shortly why inducing c3 is very important for our attack! }
10. d6
{ White's best. By sacrificing this pawn, White slows down Black's development.  10.O-O-O  O-O⇆  leads to double-edged play. }
10... cxd6 11. O-O-O Rb8 { Black gets ready for the storm. } 12. Ng3 g6
{ Stopping Nf5. } 13. Nf3 b5
{ The point of forcing the pawn on c3 is now clear. Black has created a hook for the attack with ...b4 next. The game is double-edged, but I prefer Black's chances. Here is a possible line:   14.h4  , White starts their play.  14...b4!  15.c4  slows down the attack but also weakens the long diagonal.  15...f5  16.h5  Kf8!  A simple way to defend.  17.hxg6  hxg6  18.Rxh8+  Nxh8  19.Qe3  Nf7!∓  , Black happily  sacs the a7-pawn and will take over the game using the a-file and the strong dark-squared bishop. }
