7. Nxe4 { White wins the pawn back. } 7... c6
{ A more fighting move.  7...c5!?  is also good and typically leads to massive trades after  8.Nxc5!  Qa5+!  9.b4  dxc5!  10.Qxe5  Qxb4+  11.Bd2  Qe4+  12.Qxe4  Nxe4=  , with a roughly equal endgame. }
8. Bxf6 gxf6
{ Black's lack of development is compensated by long-term factors such as the bishop pair and a future pawn center. }
9. f4 { White has to play very actively here. } 9... Ng6 10. O-O-O
{ White's best try. } 10... f5
{ Black removes White's strong knight from the center.  10...Qb6!?  is also good, but  10...Nxf4?  is inaccurate due to  11.Nxf6+!  exf6  12.Qxf4±  , with a big edge for White. }
11. Ng5 Qb6 { Endgames favor Black so we offer one to White. } 12. Qd2
{ White avoids the trades. } 12... Bg7
{ Black has a great position already with a promising attack. Here's how the attack may play out:  13.c3  Qa5  14.Bc4  b5!  15.Bb3  c5!  Black aggressively pushes the queenside pawns.  16.Kb1  c4  17.Bc2  Rb8  ,  with the idea ...b4 to open up the b-file.  18.N1f3?  b4!  19.cxb4  Rxb4-+  and White is helpless against the massive threats.   Conclusion: The Staunton Gambit is a must-know gambit for all the Dutch fans, as White gets a quick attacking setup. However, the tricky @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppppp1pp/5n2/6B1/3Pp3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R2QKBNR b KQkq - 3 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Nc6!?  invites a big fight that favors the better-prepared player. Often, Black is happy to give  the e4-pawn back, but White would have to lose the bishop pair. I prefer Black’s long-term prospects; especially the powerful dark-squared bishop! }
