[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "33) Englund Gambit"]
[Black "Englund Gambit 1.d4 e5 2.dxe5 Bc5 "]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 e5
{ The Englund Gambit is a really bad gambit. In order to understand how bad it is, I did an experiment and looked at all the possible moves vs. 1.d4 with a strong modern engine @@StartBracket@@Stockfish@@EndBracket@@ and  1...e5  is hovering about #18, competing with  1...f6  @@StartBracket@@#19@@EndBracket@@ for the honors.   Guess which move is #20? It's  1...g5  , which is quite sad. So, GM Boris Avrukh may be right, as quoted in his famous 1.d4 books as 'seems to me the worst possible reply to White's first move.' }
2. dxe5 { Of course, we take the central pawn with no hesitation! } 2... Bc5
{ A popular move in blitz/bullet, played by IM Eric Rosen. It's based on a trick that many lower-rated players fall for. }
3. Nf3 d6 { Black offers another pawn. } 4. exd6 Ne7
{ And the knight... hoping for White to auto-capture the piece. } 5. Nc3
{ As long as White plays almost any developing move and doesn't take on e7, we are much better!   5.Bf4!  is good as well, for example,  5...O-O  6.e3!  Don't take the knight!  6...cxd6  7.Nbd2±  , or any other developing move, gives White a big plus.   5.dxe7??  Bxf2+!  Oops, Black is winning the game.  6.Kxf2  Qxd1  , surprisingly, according to the lichess DB, 367 850 people fell for this trick. Wow! Now it's time to pat yourself on the back for buying my course. :@@EndBracket@@ }
5... cxd6
{ 5...Bxd6  doesn't change the evaluation. Black is still lost after  6.Nb5  , when White will get the bishop pair as well. Avoiding that with  6...Bb4+  only makes things worse:  7.Bd2  Bxd2+  8.Qxd2  Qxd2  9.Nxd2  is just a winning endgame for White given the extra pawn. }
6. e3 Nbc6 7. Bc4
{ White will castle next and with an extra pawn and Black's terrible weakness on d6, we are much better. }
