{ White has easy play and will develop harmoniously and castle. Black's a8-rook and c8-bishop are having major issues. It's a one-sided game.   11...Qa5  12.c3!  Let's keep the queens on!  12...h6  13.Be2  Nge7  14.Qf4  ,  hitting the f7-pawn.  @@StartBracket@@  14.O-O  is of course fine as well.@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@r1bk3r/ppppnpp1/2n4p/q2NP3/4PQ2/2P2N2/4BPPP/3RK2R b K - 3 14@@EndFEN@@  14...Rf8  @@StartBracket@@  14...Nxd5  15.exd5  Qxc3+  16.Kf1  , with a huge attack.  16...Nb4  17.Qxf7+-  @@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@r1bk1r2/ppppnpp1/2n4p/q2NP3/4PQ2/2P2N2/4BPPP/3RK2R w K - 4 15@@EndFEN@@  15.O-O  Ng6  16.Qg3  b6  17.h4±  , with unstoppable threats. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "33) Englund Gambit"]
[Black "Englund Gambit 1.d4 e5 2.dxe5 Nc6 3.Nf3 Qe7 #6"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 e5
{ The Englund Gambit is a really bad gambit. In order to understand how bad it is, I did an experiment and looked at all the possible moves vs. 1.d4 with a strong modern engine @@StartBracket@@Stockfish@@EndBracket@@ and  1...e5  is hovering about #18, competing with  1...f6  @@StartBracket@@#19@@EndBracket@@ for the honors.   Guess which move is #20? It's  1...g5  , which is quite sad. So, GM Boris Avrukh may be right, as quoted in his famous 1.d4 books as 'seems to me the worst possible reply to White's first move.' }
2. dxe5 { Of course, we take the central pawn with no hesitation! } 2... Nc6
{ The main line. } 3. Nf3
{ White's most natural move, and we also protect the pawn. } 3... Qe7
{ Black attacks the pawn while eyeing the b4-square for the queen. Swedish player Fritz Englund @@StartBracket@@1871-1933@@EndBracket@@ sponsored a thematic tournament where all games began with  4.Qd5  in this position.  Thus, this whole 1.d4 e5 complex was named after him. }
4. Bf4
{ The most principled, as we know complications after  4...Qb4+  are favorable for White.   If you don't want to study much, the simple  4.Nc3!  to give up  the e5-pawn is also quite strong and given as an alternative.  4.Qd5  f6!  allows Black some decent counterplay. }
4... Qb4+
{ This is the entire point of this setup for Black. But little do they know that these complications heavily favor White! }
5. Bd2 { Inviting Black to grab the b2-pawn. } 5... Qxb2
{ The most common move and principled approach. } 6. Nc3
{ Here, White has to avoid the tempting  6.Bc3?  , as it loses on the spot!   6.Bc3?  walks right into Black's entire opening trick! According to the lichess DB, 400  000  people made this blunder. Can someone please tell them to buy my course?!  6...Bb4!  and just like that, White loses material. For example  7.Bxb4  @@StartBracket@@  7.Qd2  Bxc3  8.Qxc3  Qc1#  , oops.@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@r1b1k1nr/pppp1ppp/2n5/4P3/1B6/5N2/PqP1PPPP/RN1QKB1R b KQkq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7...Nxb4-+  . }
6... Bb4 { The most common move. } 7. Rb1 { White starts to attack the queen. }
7... Qa3 8. Nd5
{ I like this a bit more, but nothing wrong with  8.Rb3!  as well. The engine gives +2 and more in all lines now! }
8... Ba5 { Black keeps the pressure, hoping it's White who will take on a5. }
9. e4
{ Simple chess! White just uses the big lead in development and gets the pieces out. }
9... Nge7 10. Be2
{ I like this simple move, which is also a novelty. We just want to castle next. Obviously, White has many good moves here. }
10... O-O
{ At least the tombstone on Black's king will say 'I castled in this game.' }
11. O-O
{ White has a winning advantage @@StartBracket@@+3 according to Stockfish@@EndBracket@@, but let me entertain you with some possible lines. }
11... d6 { 11...Bxd2  12.Qxd2  only helps White to connect the rooks. } 12. Rb3
Qxa2 13. Bc1
{ A remarkable bishop move. Black either loses a piece or gets the queen trapped. }
13... Ng6 14. Ra3 Qb1 15. Bd3
{ Getting ready to play c3 and trap the enemy queen. } 15... dxe5 16. c3
{ Black will lose the queen. } *

