[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "34) From's Gambit"]
[Black "From's Gambit 1.f4 e5 2.fxe5 d6 − 4...Nf6"]
[Result "*"]

1. f4
{ If you love the Bird's Opening, then you have to be ready for the From's Gambit:  1...e5  . }
1... e5
{ This double-edged move was named after Danish chess player, Martin Severin From @@StartBracket@@1828-1895@@EndBracket@@. An interesting side note is that he also essayed the Danish Gambit @@StartBracket@@@@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e5  2.d4  exd4  3.c3  @@EndBracket@@, which I covered here. }
2. fxe5
{ White's most principled response.  2.e4  transposes to the King's Gambit which I covered here. }
2... d6
{ Black doesn't care about pawns and aims for rapid development. Accuracy is required from White if we want to play for an edge. }
3. exd6 Bxd6
{ Black already has a pretty dangerous threat of ...Qh4+, which leads to mate. }
4. Nf3
{ So far White has played pretty obvious moves, we took the pawn gift and developed naturally, covering the h4-square.   4.Nc3??  is how White can get mated in 3 moves!  4...Qh4+  5.g3  Qxg3+  ,  more flashy than ...Bxg3+ but both mate:  6.hxg3  Bxg3#  . }
4... Nf6
{ This is a more calm development plan, allowing White to consolidate. } 5. g3
{ The easiest, White just wants to fianchetto the bishop and fight for the control of the long diagonal. }
5... Nc6 6. Bg2 Bg4
{ With a classic plan of ...Qd7 and ...O-O-O, hoping for a kingside attack. }
7. O-O { White is not afraid and castles kingside. } 7... Qd7 8. d4
{ White takes the opportunity to seize the center and open up the c1-bishop. }
8... O-O-O 9. Bg5 { A nice square for the bishop, we pin the knight on f6. }
9... h5 10. Nc3
{ White has completed development and stands better. Black's attack is hard to get going since the ...h4 push will just drop another pawn.   10...h4?  11.Bxh4  Bxf3  12.Rxf3!  , the most precise.  12...Rxh4  13.gxh4  Nxd4  14.Rd3!  and White should repel the attack, keeping all the extra material.  @@StartBracket@@  14.Qxd4?  Bxh2+-+  @@EndBracket@@ }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "34) From's Gambit"]
[Black "From's Gambit 1.f4 e5 2.fxe5 d6 − 4...g5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. f4
{ If you love the Bird's Opening, then you have to be ready for the From's Gambit:  1...e5  . }
1... e5
{ This double-edged move was named after Danish chess player, Martin Severin From @@StartBracket@@1828-1895@@EndBracket@@. An interesting side note is that he also essayed the Danish Gambit @@StartBracket@@@@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e5  2.d4  exd4  3.c3  @@EndBracket@@, which I covered here. }
2. fxe5
{ White's most principled response.  2.e4  transposes to the King's Gambit which I covered here. }
2... d6
{ Black doesn't care about pawns and aims for rapid development. Accuracy is required from White if we want to play for an edge. }
3. exd6 Bxd6
{ Black already has a pretty dangerous threat of ...Qh4+, which leads to mate. }
4. Nf3
{ So far White has played pretty obvious moves, we took the pawn gift and developed naturally, covering the h4-square.   4.Nc3??  is how White can get mated in 3 moves!  4...Qh4+  5.g3  Qxg3+  ,  more flashy than ...Bxg3+ but both mate:  6.hxg3  Bxg3#  . }
4... g5
{ The most aggressive. Black just wants to push the pawn to g4 and kick the knight away. }
5. g3
{ An important move. Not only do we want to fianchetto the bishop, but we also secure the h4-outpost for our knight.   5.Nc3?  is exactly what Black is hoping for.  5...g4  6.Nd4??  and this is another mate in 3.  6...Qh4+  7.g3  Qxg3+  @@StartBracket@@  7...Bxg3+  8.hxg3  Qxg3#  @@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnb1k1nr/ppp2p1p/3b4/8/3N2p1/2N3q1/PPPPP2P/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8.hxg3  Bxg3#  . }
5... g4 6. Nh4
{ The knight is a bit passive on h4, but it stops Black's attack on the h-file.  6.Nd4!?  is also an interesting try for an edge. }
6... Be7 { This allows a nice regrouping. } 7. Ng2
{ The knight is heading to f4. } 7... h5 8. Nf4 h4 9. Bg2 h3 10. Be4 f5 11. Bd3
{ An unusual position, but White is better here. Black's king is overexposed and the g6-square is weak. }
