{ The most aggressive. Black just wants to push the pawn to g4 and kick the knight away. }
5. g3
{ An important move. Not only do we want to fianchetto the bishop, but we also secure the h4-outpost for our knight.   5.Nc3?  is exactly what Black is hoping for.  5...g4  6.Nd4??  and this is another mate in 3.  6...Qh4+  7.g3  Qxg3+  @@StartBracket@@  7...Bxg3+  8.hxg3  Qxg3#  @@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnb1k1nr/ppp2p1p/3b4/8/3N2p1/2N3q1/PPPPP2P/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8.hxg3  Bxg3#  . }
5... g4 6. Nh4
{ The knight is a bit passive on h4, but it stops Black's attack on the h-file.  6.Nd4!?  is also an interesting try for an edge. }
6... Ne7
{ The most common move. Black wants to trade the h4-knight with ...Ng6 next. }
7. d4 { White grabs the center and opens up the c1-bishop. } 7... Ng6 8. Nxg6
{ In general, we don't mind trades, as we're up a pawn. } 8... hxg6
{ Black activates the rook and now g3 is quite weak due to the pin. } 9. Qd3
{ The only move that fights for an advantage. We need to protect g3. } 9... Nc6
{ Black sets up a sneaky tactic with ...Nxd4 Qxd4 and ...Bxg3+.  9...Bf5  10.e4  Qe7  11.Bg2  Nc6  12.c3  transposes to our main line. }
10. c3 { White shores up the d4-pawn while building a nice bind. } 10... Bf5
{ The main line, Black goes for rapid development to castle long. } 11. e4 Qe7
{ Hitting e4 and getting ready to castle next. } 12. Bg2
{ White develops and protects the key central pawn. } 12... O-O-O 13. Be3
{ It's important for White to prepare a queenside castle, where our king would be safe. For now, the f5-bishop hangs.   13.O-O?!  Be6!  , with attack for Black. }
13... Rde8
{ This allows White to develop nicely.  13...Rxh2?  doesn't work.  14.Rxh2  Bxg3+  15.Kd1  Bxh2  16.exf5+-  and White just won a piece. }
14. Nd2 { With the idea to castle long next. } 14... Rxh2
{ This fails here as well. } 15. Rxh2 Bxg3+ 16. Ke2 Bxh2 17. exf5 Bf4 18. Nf1
{ White is able to maintain the extra piece and should convert easily. } *

