{ Black sets up a sneaky tactic with ...Nxd4 Qxd4 and ...Bxg3+.  9...Bf5  10.e4  Qe7  11.Bg2  Nc6  12.c3  transposes to our main line. }
10. c3 { White shores up the d4-pawn while building a nice bind. } 10... Bf5
{ The main line, Black goes for rapid development to castle long. } 11. e4 Qe7
{ Hitting e4 and getting ready to castle next. } 12. Bg2
{ White develops and protects the key central pawn. } 12... O-O-O 13. Be3
{ It's important for White to prepare a queenside castle, where our king would be safe. For now, the f5-bishop hangs.   13.O-O?!  Be6!  , with attack for Black. }
13... Be6
{ Black saves the bishop and sets up a sneaky tactic with ...Rxh2 and ...Bxg3+.  13...Rxh2?  doesn't work.  14.Rxh2  Bxg3+  15.Kd1  Bxh2  16.exf5+-  and White just won a piece. }
14. Bf2
{ A must-know move to secure an edge. We have to overprotect g3.  14.Nd2?!  allows a tactic:  14...Rxh2  15.Rxh2  Bxg3+  16.Ke2  Bxh2⩱  . }
14... f5 { The only try left. } 15. Nd2
{ White is about to castle next and stands better. The game may continue with  15...f4  16.O-O-O  f3  17.Bf1  , when Black ran out of ideas on the kingside and White's massive pawns in the center will decide the game.  17...Bc5  18.Kb1  Kb8  19.Qc2  Bb6  20.Bc4±  and White will slowly but surely convert the extra pawn.   Conclusion: This is a must-know gambit for all the Bird opening fans out there. Black is getting a very dangerous initiative, however, if you know the defensive idea of meeting @@StartFEN@@rnbqk1nr/ppp2ppp/3b4/8/8/5N2/PPPPP1PP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 4@@EndFEN@@  4...g5!?  with  5.g3  & @@StartFEN@@rnbqk1nr/ppp2p1p/3b4/8/6p1/5NP1/PPPPP2P/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Nh4!  , then you have nothing to fear! Once the attack is stopped, White builds a powerful pawn center and prepares to castle long. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "35) Grob's Attack"]
[Black "Grob's Attack 1.g4 d5 − 5.Qxb7 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. g4
{ The Grob Attack! It was invented by the Swiss International Master Henri Grob @@StartBracket@@1904-1974@@EndBracket@@. Later, it was picked up by the English International Master Michael Basman with some success. These days it's known to be quite unsound.  White is daring Black: either refute the opening or lose trying and make one for the memes! Now that you bought my course, hopefully, moves such as 1.g4 will bring a smile to your face as I present you with a simple refutation. }
1... d5
{ Simple chess! Black takes control over the center and attacks the g4-pawn. }
2. Bg2
{ White gambits the g4-pawn, hoping for rapid development and quick use of the long a8-h1 diagonal.   A funny side note:  2.f3?  was seen at GM level and White lost the game in 5 moves after  2...e5  3.d3  Qh4+  4.Kd2  h5  5.h3  hxg4  and White resigned in Hou Yifan-Lalith, Caleta ENG 2017. You may wonder, did the former Women's World Champion have a bad day? The answer is actually quite simple: this is her protest game against the organizers after she was paired in 7 out of 9 games vs. women in a big open tournament with lots of men! An interesting way to get your message across...   2.h3  just gives away all central control:  2...e5  and Black will have all the fun with two central pawns. }
2... Bxg4 { Of course, we take the free pawn! } 3. c4
{ The point. Now that the bishop is lured away from c8, you can see that both b7 & d5 are quite weak. }
3... c6 { Simple chess. Black just supports the key d5-pawn. } 4. Qb3
{ Played by Nakamura vs. Mamedyarov. } 4... Nf6
{ Black happily sacrifices the b7-pawn for initiative.  4...e6!  5.Qxb7  Nd7  is also quite strong. }
5. Qxb7
{ White's most popular move, taking the challenge!  5.Nc3  e6  6.cxd5  cxd5  7.Qxb7  Nbd7  transposes to the 5.cxd5 variation. }
5... Nbd7 { Black develops, offering another pawn. } 6. Qxc6
{ This is one pawn too many for White, as yet another tempo is given to Black for free. }
6... Rc8
{ The rook enters the fight with a lot of juicy targets on the c-file. } 7. Qa4
{ 7.Qb5  Rxc4  8.Nc3  e6∓  , with a big initiative for Black. } 7... Rxc4
{ A simple double attack. } 8. Qd1
{ A sad but necessary retreat, as the bishop on c1 was also hit. } 8... Ne5
{ Setting up a cool trick, but pretty much any developing move gives Black a big edge. }
9. d3 { 9.h3  Nd3+!  , the same idea! } 9... Nxd3+
{ The shocker! White is totally lost now. } 10. Qxd3 Rxc1+
{ Believe it or not, all of this happened in a correspondence game in 1986 @@StartBracket@@Rabold-Forster@@EndBracket@@! }
11. Kd2 Qc8 { White is dead lost, as Black dominates the back rank. } *

