[Round "?"]
[White "35) Grob's Attack"]
[Black "Grob's Attack 1.g4 d5 − 5.cxd5 #7"]
[Result "*"]

1. g4
{ The Grob Attack! It was invented by the Swiss International Master Henri Grob @@StartBracket@@1904-1974@@EndBracket@@. Later, it was picked up by the English International Master Michael Basman with some success. These days it's known to be quite unsound.  White is daring Black: either refute the opening or lose trying and make one for the memes! Now that you bought my course, hopefully, moves such as 1.g4 will bring a smile to your face as I present you with a simple refutation. }
1... d5
{ Simple chess! Black takes control over the center and attacks the g4-pawn. }
2. Bg2
{ White gambits the g4-pawn, hoping for rapid development and quick use of the long a8-h1 diagonal.   A funny side note:  2.f3?  was seen at GM level and White lost the game in 5 moves after  2...e5  3.d3  Qh4+  4.Kd2  h5  5.h3  hxg4  and White resigned in Hou Yifan-Lalith, Caleta ENG 2017. You may wonder, did the former Women's World Champion have a bad day? The answer is actually quite simple: this is her protest game against the organizers after she was paired in 7 out of 9 games vs. women in a big open tournament with lots of men! An interesting way to get your message across...   2.h3  just gives away all central control:  2...e5  and Black will have all the fun with two central pawns. }
2... Bxg4 { Of course, we take the free pawn! } 3. c4
{ The point. Now that the bishop is lured away from c8, you can see that both b7 & d5 are quite weak. }
3... c6 { Simple chess. Black just supports the key d5-pawn. } 4. Qb3
{ Played by Nakamura vs. Mamedyarov. } 4... Nf6
{ Black happily sacrifices the b7-pawn for initiative.  4...e6!  5.Qxb7  Nd7  is also quite strong. }
5. cxd5
{ Hikaru's choice in a Titled Tuesday blitz game.  5.Nc3  e6  6.cxd5  cxd5  7.Qxb7  Nbd7  transposes to the 5.cxd5 variation. }
5... cxd5 6. Qxb7
{ The insertion of cxd5 doesn't help White much, Black is still better. } 6...
Nbd7 { A simple developing move, White's queen is a bit stranded now. } 7. Nc3
{ The most common move in the DB.  7.Bxd5?  Rb8  wins a piece on the spot. }
7... e6
{ Black just continues development. White's queen is a bit stranded on b7.  7...Rb8!  is strong as well. }
8. d4
{ White is trying to stabilize the center, but Black now takes over the initiative. }
8... Rb8 { Please take my pawn! } 9. Qxa7 { White is being too greedy here. }
9... Qc8
{ A nice idea to remember! Black is getting ready to trap White's queen with ...Ra8.  9...Bd6∓  10.Qa6  Rb6  11.Qd3  was Grob-Wegmuller, corr 1963. }
10. Qa4
{ The queen is rushing out of danger, but precious time is being lost!  10.Nf3?  Ra8-+ }
10... Bb4
{ A natural developing move, pinning the knight and getting ready to castle. }
11. Bd2 Qc4 { A clever idea, setting up a trap. } 12. Nf3
{ White falls for the trap. } 12... Bxf3
{ 12...Bxc3  also wins:  13.Qxc4  Bxd2+  14.Nxd2  dxc4-+  . } 13. Bxf3 Bxc3 14.
Qxc4 Bxd2+ 15. Kxd2 dxc4 { Black is up a piece and should convert easily. } *

